<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrackKids     12-13 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crack Kids,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boys Ages 10, 13 On Bail After Drug Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two boys, ages 10 and 13, were free on $200 bail
Tuesday after they were accused of operating a sidewalk drugstore
peddling crack, authorities said.
   The youngsters, whose names were withheld because of their ages,
were charged in Dorchester District Court with juvenile delinquency.
   Their parents bailed them out Monday after the boys appeared
before Judge James Dolan, said David Rodman, a spokesman for the
Suffolk County district attorney.
   The youths were arrested Friday night when a police surveillance
team allegedly caught them on a street selling vials of crack to
customers in cars. Police seized 27 vials of the cocaine-baking soda
mix and $56 in cash from the younger boy, who turns 11 on Sunday.
   The youngsters told police they were forced to sell drugs by an
older man, said Boston police spokesman James Jordan. The
neighborhood is the site of frequent drug arrests, he said.
   Officer Dan Linskey said the pair were tough street kids. But he
said the younger one broke down after he was placed in a darkened
cell.
   ``He was afraid of the dark,'' Linskey said. ``He wasn't afraid
of hanging out on the corner. He was afraid of the dark. The kid's
crying because he needed a night light.''
   Rodman said if the youngsters are found guilty, they could be
sent to a Department of Youth Services facility.
</TEXT>
