<1ST_LINE>r a PM-APAppointment     12-13 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Appointment,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gray Named Bureau Chief In Newark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jerry Gray, assistant chief of bureau for The
Associated Press in Newark, has been named bureau chief, succeeding
Drusilla Menaker, who has transferred to the AP bureau in Warsaw,
Poland.
   The appointment was announced Tuesday by AP President Louis D.
Boccardi. Gray will direct all of the New Jersey operations, which
include correspondencies in Trenton, Atlantic City and Woodbury, as
well as the headquarters bureau in Newark.
   Gray, 38, joined the AP in Memphis in 1975. He transferred to the
news cooperative's World Services Department in New York in 1983 and
two years later was assigned to the Nairobi bureau.
   In 1986 Gray was named chief of bureau in Nairobi, and he became
assistant chief of bureau in Newark earlier this year.
   Gray is a native of Greenwood, Miss. He began his journalism
career at the Memphis Commercial Appeal and served in the U.S. Navy
before joining the AP.
</TEXT>
