<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JacobsArrested 1stLd-Writethru a0803 12-13 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jacobs Arrested, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0803,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indian Fugitive Arrested in N.Y. After Chase, Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with arraignment, extradition
proceedings, CORRECTS time of incident in 3rd graf pvs to 4 p.m.
sted 5:30 p.m.; picking up 4th graf pvs, `Jacobs was ...'. ADDS 3
grafs with comments from Jacobs' lawyer.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LUMBERTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian fugitive Timothy Jacobs, who has
been sought on 14 kidnapping charges stemming from a newspaper
takeover, was arrested Tuesday in New York after a high-speed chase,
authorities said.
   Jacobs, 20, was being held at a county jail in Wampsville, N.Y.,
25 miles east of Syracuse. He was arraigned as a fugitive Tuesday
night in Lenox, N.Y., officials said.
   North Carolina authorities said they would begin extradition
proceedings, and a lawyer for Jacobs said he would fight the move.
   Sgt. Josephine Townsend of the state police in Oneida said police
tried to stop Jacobs about 4 p.m. for speeding on the New York State
Thruway 10 miles east of Syracuse. Police said Jacobs left the
thruway and drove at high speeds through two villages until his car
crashed into an empty school bus. No one was injured.
   Jacobs was indicted Dec. 6 during a special session the Robeson
County grand jury on state charges stemming from the Feb. 1 takeover
of The Robesonian newspaper in Lumberton.
   Eddie Hatcher, 31, who was indicted on the same charges, was
arrested on the day the indictments were returned. He has been
released on $25,000 bond.
   A federal jury in October acquitted Hatcher and Jacobs of federal
hostage-taking and firearms charges. During the three-week trial,
the two Tuscarora Indians had argued that they had no other choice
but to take over the newspaper to save their lives.
   The pair said they had evidence linking county officials and law
enforcement officers to drug trafficking, and that evidence had put
their lives in jeopardy.
   Lewis Pitts, the founder of the Christic Institute South, a civil
rights law firm in Carrboro, N.C., that is representing Jacobs, said
Jacobs had found a job and delivering a load of arts and crafts
material when he was stopped by the trooper.
   ``What flashed in front of his eyes ... was the absolute danger
of returning to Robeson County, so he decided to flee,'' Lewis said.
   Authorities in North Carolina said Jacobs will be held in the New
York jail awaiting extradition proceedings. Pitts said Jacobs would
fight extradition to North Carolina rather than face what he called
``blatantly bad-faith prosecution.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
