<HEAD>Lippman Named AP Bureau Chief in Los Angeles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrew Lippman, a veteran Associated Press bureau
chief, has been named chief of bureau in Los Angeles.
   Louis D. Boccardi, AP president, announced the appointment
Monday. Lippman, currently chief of bureau in Indianapolis, succeeds
Martin C. Thompson, who recently was named managing editor at the
news cooperative's headquarters in New York.
   Lippman, 40, will direct AP's operations in southern California
and southern Nevada.
   He joined the AP in Phoenix in 1971 and worked in the Tucson
bureau the following year. He transferred to the AP national sports
desk in New York in 1973.
   Lippman was named correspondent in charge of AP's Cincinnati
bureau in 1974, and six years later became assistant bureau chief in
Los Angeles. He was chief of bureau in Louisville for three years
before being named Indianapolis bureau chief in 1984.
   Lippman is a native of Washington, D.C., and a graduate of
Northwestern University.
</TEXT>
