<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--EvergladesTourism     12-13 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Everglades Tourism,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Million Visitors In '88</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLAMINGO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everglades National Park has welcomed its
one-millionth visitor for 1988, the first time in a decade the park
has attracted so many tourists in a year.
   The National Park Service arrived at the figure through its daily
use reports, with the lucky millionth visitor selected Saturday at
random and given free lodging, tours and canoe rental.
   ``Tourism to South Florida, especially foreign tourism, has been
increasing markedly in the last few years and we're benefiting from
it,'' said Patrick Czarny, marketing director for the Flamingo
Lodge, the only place to rent a room in the 1,300-square-mile park.
   ``We haven't done anything special to promote the park, but I
believe there is much more awareness of the Everglades and the
park's environmental significance,'' Czarny said Monday.
   The last time the park attracted 1 million visitors in a year was
in 1978. Visitation decreased to a 1983 low of 500,000 and has
steadily climbed since.
</TEXT>
