<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-13 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some state lawmakers might think he's been
more naughty than nice, but Gov. William Donald Schaefer told Santa
he's at least tried to be good this year.
   But even if Santa sides with the governor, he'll have a difficult
time getting everything Schaefer wants for Christmas down the
chimney of the governor's mansion.
   ``I have tried to be good in 1988 ... I answered 100,000 letters
from citizens who wrote to tell me they liked _ or didn't like _
what I was doing,'' Schaefer said in his letter to Santa. ``I even
put on 212 silly hats so the newspapers could take pictures of me in
unflattering poses.
   ``Now, Santa, my time has come. Here's what I want from you this
year.''
   Schaefer then ticked off a 17-point wish list that ranged from
better medical care and housing, more resources to help the
disadvantaged, better fishing in the Chesapeake Bay and a
professional football team.
   The governor also said he wouldn't mind winning the Maryland
lottery.
   Typically, Schaefer couldn't resist taking a dig at state
lawmakers, asking Santa to send 188 copies of a nonexistent book,
``Surplus Budgeting Made Easy,'' to ``my friends in the General
Assembly.''
   Schaefer and lawmakers are at odds on whether to spend a
projected surplus.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: versions of the following items moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEILLSVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio sports director Al Hacko thought
he made a safe bet, but it turned out to be a hair-raising
experience.
   On a WCCN radio talk show last week, the former Minnesota
resident flippantly said he would shave his head if the Green Bay
Packers beat the favored Minnesota Vikings in a National Football
League game Sunday.
   Hacko said he was at the game in Green Bay, ending in an 18-6
Packer victory, and ``cried his way home.''
   With plenty of onlookers at a tavern in this central Wisconsin
town, Hacko made good on his bet Monday, but kept his mustache. He
said his new haircut shows how receding his hairline really is.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A college football player from Mississippi learned
the hard way how expensive New York City can be. His teachers were a
limousine driver and a light-fingered pickpocket.
   Wesley Walls, the All-American tight end from the University of
Mississippi, likened himself to Crocodile Dundee, the movie
character who visited New York from Australia.
   ``I went up there and learned a couple of lessons,'' Walls
recalled Monday as he and the other members of The Associated Press
All-America team taped Bob Hope's Christmas Special in Miami.
   He went to New York to be honored last week as one of the
National Football Foundation's scholar-athletes. A limousine driver
charged him $85 for ride to a Manhattan hotel, less than 10 miles
from the airport.
   Then someone took $180 from his pocket at a disco.
   But Walls said his trip wasn't all bad.
   ``I found out the people were more friendly than I thought they'd
be. I was being super-nice and they were being nice back. It was
good hospitality _ not Southern hospitality, but close.''
   Walls wouldn't even mind being drafted by the New York Giants or
New York Jets, who both actually play their games in New Jersey.
   ``I'd come back and be a lot smarter,'' he said.
</TEXT>
