<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Indians     12-13 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Indians,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Meets With Indian Leaders; Can't Remember `Primitive' Remark</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Indian leaders say they are generally
pleased with their meeting with President Reagan, but say they hope
White House invitations will be more frequent in the Bush
administration.
   Indian leaders had been seeking a meeting with Reagan for more
than six months, ever since he said U.S. officials might have erred
in allowing Indians to continue to live in their ``primitive ways.''
He made the comment during a question-and-answer session with
students at Moscow State University last May.
   Reagan told reporters Monday, ``I don't recall saying that.''
   The president's spokesman quoted the president as telling the 16
Indian leaders from 11 states: ``Indians should have the right to
choose their own life _ the right to have a say in what happens in
Indian country.''
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the administration had trouble
arranging Monday's meeting because of difficulty in deciding which
Indian representatives to invite; there are more than 500 American
Indian tribes.
   But Ivan Sidney, chairman of the Hopi Tribe of Kykotsmovi, Ariz.,
told reporters after the Cabinet Room session that Reagan's comments
in Moscow last May ``indicated that there needed to be a contact by
the native people directly with the White House.''
   Reagan, in Moscow for his summit with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, had said he was willing to meet ``any time'' with Indians
seeking to air grievances.
   That demand was heightened after he went on to tell his Soviet
audience that the U.S. government may have made a mistake in
allowing Indians to pursue their ``primitive lifestyle'' rather than
becoming citizens ``with the rest of us.''
   Discussing the ``primitive lifestyle'' statement, Reagan told
reporters during a picture-taking session that ``I don't recall
saying that. I tried in response to a question to explain that
theirs was a freedom, as with all the people of America, a freedom
that is quite different'' from the situation in the Soviet Union.
   Edgar L. French Jr. of Anadarko, Okla., president of the Delaware
Tribes of Western Oklahoma, said that he had signed a letter to the
president from Oklahoma tribal leaders ``stating that he was very
wrong.''
   However, said French, ``It's been said, and we've said what we
wanted to say against it, and let it go. We need to look to the
future, not to what's behind us. The number one problem is economic
development on the reservations.''
   Eddie L. Tullis of Atmore, Ala., tribal chairman of the Poarch
Band of Creek Indians, said the president's remarks ``served a very
useful purpose of raising his consciousness of the need for us to
communicate on a government-to-government basis.''
   ``It could serve a very great purpose if the new administration
builds on what has been started here today,'' Tullis said.
   When the president was asked why it took so long to arrange the
meeting, he said, ``Because I was never apprised that a meeting was
being sought.'' Presidential aides, including Fitzwater, met in
California last August with one Indian group seeking an audience
with the president.
   Secretary of the Interior Donald Hodel, meeting with reporters
after the meeting, said, ``We want to strengthen the ability of the
tribes to help themselves while maintaining the special
relationship.''
   Ross O. Swimmer, assistant secretary of the interior for Indian
affairs, asked who selected the Indian leaders to be invited, said,
``We shared that responsibility with the White House.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
