<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     12-13 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Despite Drought, Cotton Crop At Seven-Year High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 cotton crop mostly escaped the ravages
of drought and is expected to total a seven-year high of 15.2
million bales, up 3 percent from last year's harvest and 2 percent
more than forecast a month ago, the Agriculture Department says.
   Based on field conditions as of Dec. 1, the department's
Agricultural Statistics Board said Monday, cotton production would
be the largest since 15.6 million bales were harvested in 1981.
   Counting almost 5.8 million bales left over from earlier
harvests, the total U.S. cotton supply in the 1988-89 marketing year
is expected to be about 21 million bales, the most in 20 years,
analysts said in a related supply-and-demand report.
   Exports may require only 6.9 million bales in 1988-89, down from
more than 7.6 million last marketing year, reflecting ``fierce
competition'' in the world cotton trade, the report said.
   The increased 1988 cotton harvest resulted from a larger acreage,
up 16 percent from 1987, while average yields per acre declined from
last year.
   As a result of the cotton outlook, USDA on Oct. 31 announced that
farmers will have to reduce their acreage 25 percent next year to
qualify for the price support program.
   The report also indicated dry edible bean production this year at
19.1 million hundredweight, down 26 percent from last year, and
burley tobacco production at 459 million pounds, up 9 percent from
the 1987 harvest.
   Orange production, at 215 million boxes, is up 9 percent from
last season.
   The report did not include new 1988 production figures for other
major crops such as wheat, corn and soybeans; production totals for
those crops will be released Jan. 13.
   Planting of winter wheat for the 1989 harvest was 95 percent
completed by Nov. 1, about 5 percentage points ahead of average, the
report said. But lack of moisture hampered development in much of
the major growing areas.
   ``Near the end of the month, rain and snow provided needed
moisture in portions of the plains and Pacific Northwest,'' the
report said. ``Greenbugs continued to be a problem in Kansas and
Texas. In Texas, central and southern areas remained dry and showed
little or no growth.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Timber harvesting in certain parts of national
forests in Oregon and Washington will be barred in order to broaden
habitat protection for the spotted owl, says the Agriculture
Department.
   F. Dale Robertson, chief of the Forest Service, said Monday that
most of the new habitat areas will range from 1,000 to 2,000 acres
in size, and will serve as protection for nesting owls as well as
providing ``stepping stones'' between larger areas, totaling more
than 1.6 million acres, already protected as owl habitats.
   In the Olympic National Forest, the new habitat areas may be as
large as 3,000 acres each, he said.
   In all, the special habitat areas are expected to reduce the
annual timber harvest on national forests in Oregon and Washington
by about 180 million board feet.
   Each of the 13 national forests that have owls will share in the
linkage system. The exact number will not be determined until the
forests submit final management plans to ensure that spotted owl
populations will be maintained.
   ``This has been an extremely difficult decision to make, but I
believe it strikes a reasonable balance between the two conflicting
goals of sustaining spotted owl populations and providing timber
supplies that are vital to the economies of Oregon and Washington,''
Robertson said.
   The Forest Service, a USDA agency, has been embroiled in
controversy concerning its management plans for spotted owl
habitats, notably in the Pacific Northwest where some people are
concerned that protection of the birds could adversely affect the
timber industry.
   However, Robertson said the controversy has not been confined to
his agency, noting that a lawsuit against Interior's Bureau of Land
Management has resulted in an injunction prohibiting the bureau from
harvesting mature timber on some lands the agency administers in
Oregon.
   Also, the Fish and Wildlife Service is being challenged in court
over its 1987 refusal to designate the owl a threatened or
endangered species.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has formally adopted
a rule allowing processors to use certain acidic substances to keep
supermarket pork chops looking pink and appetizing.
   The rule takes effect Jan. 11.
   Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's Food Safety
and Inspection Service, said the agency has permitted use of the
additives since September 1986 but it held off making a final
decision until public comments had been submitted.
   The substances are ascorbic acid, erythorbic acid, citric acid,
sodium ascorbate and sodium citrate, which are used in fresh cuts of
pork to maintain the meat's color.
   ``The use of these substances in the product does not pose a
health risk,'' Crawford said. ``Fresh pork loses its color long
before it becomes unsafe. The color change makes the product
unappealing.''
   Product labels will identify the added substances and the reason
for their use, he said, for example: ``Sprayed with a solution of
water, ascorbic acid and citric acid to maintain color.''
</TEXT>
