<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Nicaraguans-Asylum     12-13 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaraguans-Asylum,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Immigration Officials Considering Changes For Asylum-seekers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration officials, gearing up for a crush
of Nicaraguans seeking asylum in the United States, are proposing
changes that might make it more difficult for them to work here
legally.
   One change would require that asylum applications be reviewed by
immigration officers before the asylum-seeker is allowed to work in
this country, according to an internal document prepared at the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service and obtained by The
Associated Press.
   Under another change, asylum applicants would have to make a
stronger case for receiving a work permit than they do now,
according to the document.
   INS Commissioner Alan Nelson is to meet this week with Associate
Attorney General Francis Keating to discuss the INS proposals.
   A Justice Department policy adopted in July 1987 by then-Attorney
General Edwin Meese III encouraged INS officials to expedite
Nicaraguan applications for work authorizations.
   Since the Meese directive was put in place, any Nicaraguan who
applied for political asylum has almost automatically been granted a
work permit while his application was being processed.
   The 1987 policy was hailed by most Nicaraguans, who said the
action should have been taken earlier.
   The INS hasn't acted on many asylum applications from
Nicaraguans, but that is apparently about to change.
   In the past year and a half, there has been a sharp increase in
the number of asylum applications from Central Americans, most of
whom cross the border illegally in the Harlingen, Texas, area.
   There is a backlog of nearly 12,000 asylum applications from
Nicaraguans who have come here illegally, INS officials have said,
and an estimated 5,000 more Nicaraguans who have come here illegally
and who haven't filed asylum applications.
   One of the internal INS documents is a two-page memo dated Dec. 5
from the office of INS deputy commissioner James Buck and entitled
``Nicaraguan Asylum, Harlingen Situation.'' It says that an INS
staffer had been directed to prepare a document ``which Keating may
use to support the argument for rescission of the Meese memo
regarding Nicaraguans (requested by Keating).'' The memo was sent to
Keating on Dec. 2, according to the document.
   INS commissioner Alan Nelson had earlier favored rescinding the
Meese memo, according to Justice Department sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity. However, said the sources, Nelson has
changed his mind and has decided not to recommend rescinding or
revising the Meese directive, but rather to make other changes to
address the Nicaraguan question, said the sources.
   It could not be determined what Keating's position on the Meese
directive is or why Nelson had changed his mind.
   A separate INS document proposes that a clarification be sent to
INS field offices immediately informing the field that ``the Meese
memorandum of July 2, 1987 does not require automatic granting of
work authorization to asylum applicants whose claims are frivolous.''
   Another proposal is to establish a procedure under which those
who have filed asylum applications most recently would be reviewed
first under what one of the internal documents calls ``last in,
first out adjudications procedures.'' The INS has not acted on many
of the Nicaraguan asylum applications filed in the past year and a
half and the proposal would mean an additional waiting period for
that group.
   INS spokesman Greg Leo declined Thursday night to discuss any of
the proposals and Justice Department spokesman Joseph Krovisky
declined comment.
   The INS is gearing up to address the crush of applications,
according to the INS documents and agency sources, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Sixteen INS examiners and eight support staff would be detailed
to Harlingen ``to maintain an appropriate asylum processing level
for a 30-day period,'' according to the internal INS documents
detailing the INS proposals.
   Another step being proposed is to press the State Department to
``secure the assistance of Mexico and Central American countries to
slow down the flow of illegal aliens into the United States,'' the
documents said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
