<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MissileAccident 1stLd-Writethru a0405 12-13 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missile Accident, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0405,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Practice Missile Hits Freighter, Kills Crewman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to add background from Navy on where ship had
been headed, how warnings to ships to avoid an area are broadcast,
detail on size of missile, exact location of accident. CORRECTS 7th
graf pvs, `The 250-foot...', that ship now heading to Honolulu sted
Kauai; and CORRECTS type of plane in 8th graf to FA-18 sted F-18A.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE DUNFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crewman aboard an Indian merchant ship was
killed Monday when the ship was struck by a half-ton practice
missile launched from a Navy jet during a military exercise, the
Navy announced.
   The non-explosive missile was fired at a target hulk ship, but
its guidance system locked onto the merchant vessel Jagvivek which
was not supposed to be within the Navy's Pacific Missile range, the
Navy said.
   The missile hit the topside superstructure of the merchant ship,
fatally injuring the crewmember, the Navy said.
   The accident took place 80 miles north-northwest of the island of
Kauai within an area of several thousand square miles of ocean which
had been closed to merchant vessels by a notice to mariners issued
by the Navy on Thursday, the statement said.
   Lt. Cmdr. Gary E. Shrout, a Navy spokesman, said the ship had
been en route to Singapore but he didn't know what it contained or
where it was heading from.
   There was no report of any other injuries. The identity of the
crewman was not immediately disclosed.
   After the accident, the 250-foot Jagvivek headed under its own
power to Honolulu for further damage assessment and possible
repairs, the Navy said in a statement. The ship was expected to
reach here Tuesday morning.
   The FA-18 Hornet jet that fired the anti-ship missile was from
the USS Constellation. The carrier and its seven-ship battle group
was conducting exercises, en route to a Western Pacific deployment,
the Navy said.
   The Harpoon missile has a range of 65 miles and was launched from
the jet toward the target ship many miles out to sea, the Navy said.
   ``Unfortunately, the exercise missile was fired close enough to
the path of the merchant vessel for the missile's seeker to guide on
it instead of the original target,'' said a statement issued by the
Navy at Pearl Harbor.
   A Navy helicopter took the victim's body to Wilcox Memorial
Hospital on the island of Kauai, according to Kauai police.
   The Harpoon missile is more than 12 feet long, weighs more than
1,000 pounds and flies at supersonic speed, guided by an imaging
infrared seeker that locks onto the target, according to Jane's All
The World's Aircraft.
   The warnings for merchant ships to avoid the Pacific Missile
Range are included in routine advisories transmitted on marine radio
frequencies at set times throughout the day, according to the Coast
Guard.
</TEXT>
