<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--DucklingStolen     12-13 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Duckling Stolen,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Theft Leaves Police On Duck Hunt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are on a duck hunt, but so far have no leads
in the theft of a bronze duckling from a park.
   The duckling was one of eight waddling after their mother in a
sculpture that dramatizes Robert McCloskey's children's tale, ``Make
Way for Ducklings.'' In the story, a family of ducks wanders about
the Beacon Hill neighboorhood before a friendly policeman helps them
find a home in the Public Garden.
   Sculptor Nancy Schon discovered Saturday that the eighth member
of the bronze brood had been swiped. The duckling, about 12 inches
high and weighing 60 pounds, apparently was removed with a blow
torch.
   ``We're aghast that some individual would be so petty as to
destroy the dreams of little children who come from all over
metropolitan Boston to see these little ducklings,'' said Victoria
Williams, assistant commissioner for the Olmsted Administration,
which oversees the Public Garden.
   ``We will replace the duck,'' she said Monday.
</TEXT>
