<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Doctors Poorly Trained in Occupational, Environmental
Health</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Academy of Sciences panel says a
medical system that is not geared towards preventive medicine is
leaving most family doctors inadequately trained to treat illnesses
caused by unhealthy environments.
   The Institute of Medicine, in a report issued Monday, called for
establishment of a clearinghouse for doctors to call ``when
confronted with a patient suspected of having an occupational or
environmental disease.''
   The Institute of Medicine, a branch of the National Academy of
Sciences, is forming an advisory committee to draw up more detailed
suggestions for such a clearinghouse.
   ``It should be designed so that a single telephone call satisfies
the practitioner's informational needs,'' the report said. ``It
could be based on an extension of the techniques used by the
nation's poison control centers.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>EPA Report Cites Lax Water Pollution Enforcement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An internal Environmental Protection Agency
report says state and federal governments are not enforcing water
pollution regulations for 150,000 drinking water sources serving 36
million travelers, workers, students and others drinking water
outside the home.
   The report released Monday by a conservation group said the water
on trains, buses and airplanes is not being monitored carefully
enough.
   The group, the National Wildlife Federation, said it planned to
sue the EPA over deficiencies in enforcement of the Safe Drinking
Water Act.
   Such a would seek an order requiring EPA to perform duties
spelled out in the act, said the federation's water specialist, Eric
Olson.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Ask Cavazos to Free Money for Course</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of congressmen want Education Secretary
Lauro Cavazos to release $70,000 to disseminate a Holocaust
education program for which the Reagan administration previously
blocked funding.
   The letter, written by Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., and signed by 65
colleagues, said money for the course has been withheld for three
years even though it has been taught by 1,000 teachers, has rated at
or near the top of its application category and received strong
recommendations for approval from Education Department staff aides.
   But the letter released Monday said the program, called ``Facing
Ourselves and History,'' has been denied money at least partially on
the basis of biased peer reviews. One reviews concluded ``the Nazi
point of view, however unpopular, is still a point of view and is
not presented, nor is that of the Ku Klux Klan.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>First Vietnam-Era Medal of Honor Winner To Retire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army Col. Roger H.C. Donlon, the first
serviceman to win a Medal of Honor for valor during the Vietnam War,
is retiring after 32 years of military service.
   Donlon was awarded the Medal of Honor by President Johnson during
a White House ceremony on Dec. 5, 1964, in recognition of his
bravery in repulsing a Viet Cong attack at Nam Dong on July 6, 1964.
   Donlon, who is the alternate-president of the Army's Physical
Evaluation Board at the Presidio of San Francisco, will retire
during ceremonies scheduled Wednesday morning at Fort Leavenworth,
Kan., where he will live with his wife, the Pentagon said Monday.
</TEXT>
