<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Nikkei Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while share prices fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 123.06 yen, up 0.14 yen from Monday's close
of 122.92 yen. After opening at 122.90 yen, the dollar ranged
between 122.89 yen and 123.15 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 121.13-point
loser the previous day, lost another 74.48 points, or 0.25 percent,
and finished trading at 29,597.81.
   Share prices, which inched down shortly after the market opened
following parallel trends on overseas markets, kept sinking toward
the end of the morning session.
   ``The index fell because the domestic interest rates became
higher as the dollar's uptrend began,'' said an analyst with Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   He said a rise in Japanese interest rates affects market players
psychologically and dampens their buying interest. ``It's kind of a
formula in stock trading,'' he noted.
   Other dealers said most institutional investors were sitting on
the sidelines ahead of the release on Wednesday of U.S. trade
figures for October.
   On the foreign-exchange market, participants also were waiting
for the U.S. trade report, which could set the direction of currency
trading.
</TEXT>
