<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas Executions, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0453-a0455-a0457,0762</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Texas Puts Man To Death In Slaying Of Restaurateur; Double
Execution Averted</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: combines pvs; LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with syringe
leaking, details from death chamber; picks up 4th graf, `Hours
earlier, ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who murdered an immigrant Greek
restaurateur as his wife watched was put to death by injection early
Tuesday in an execution delayed when one of two intravenous needles
sprung a leak.
   Raymond Landry, 39, was pronounced dead at 12:45 a.m., hours
after the U.S. Supreme Court spared a second convicted murderer from
the same fate.
   Landry was the 29th person executed in Texas, more than any other
state, since the Supreme Court reinstated capital punishment in 1976.
   Prison officials began administering the lethal fluid at 12:21
a.m. Landry was not pronounced dead until 24 minutes later. In
between, a needle sprung a leak, sending the lethal mixture shooting
across the death chamber toward witnesses.
   ``There was something of a delay in the execution because of what
officials called a `blowout,''' said Charles Brown, spokesman for
the Texas Department of Corrections. ``The syringe came out of the
vein and the warden ordered the (execution) team to reinsert the
catheter into the vein.''
   After Landry was brought into the death chamber, he shook his
head briefly when asked by Warden Jack Pursleyif he had something to
say.
   At first, he showed no reaction to the drugs, and his lips
quivered.
   The leak occurred at 12:23 a.m. The needle on the inside of his
right arm leaked, sending the solution about two feet toward the
witnesses.
   Pursley quickly pulled a curtain across the viewing area to block
witnesses' views. For more than 14 minutes, witnesses heard the
sounds of doors opening and closing, some mumbling, and at least one
groan.
   The curtain was then reopened and Landry was motionless and
appeared dead with his eyes half closed.
   Three minutes later, two doctors arrived. They declared him dead
at 12:45 a.m.
   Brown said it was the first time such a problem had occurred in
Texas. In 1985 however, authorities repeatedly jabbed needles into
Stephen Morin when they had trouble finding a usable vein because he
had been a drug abuser.
   Landry was convicted in the death of Kosmas Prittis, who was
robbed and shot in the head while he and his family were closing
their Houston restaurant in 1982.
   Hours earlier, the Supreme Court blocked a second execution in
Texas, that of Samuel Hawkins, who was convicted of the 1976
rape-slaying of a 19-year-old woman. Had he been put to death along
with Landry, it would have been the first time since executions
resumed in 1976 that a state had put two people to death on the same
day.
   Landry's execution brings to 104 the number of men and women put
to death in the United States since 1976. The total includes 11
executions this year, three in Texas counting Landry.
   Thought it granted the stay for Hawkins, nation's high court
voted 7-2 earlier Monday to refuse the appeal filed by lawyers for
Landry. Landry's attorney, Michael Charlton, bypassed lower federal
courts and had appealed directly to the high court, while attorneys
for Hawkins were turned down by a federal appeals court in New
Orleans before going to the Supreme Court.
   U.S. Supreme Court spokeswoman Kathy Arberg said the order
sparing Hawkins was entered at 10:25 p.m. Hours earlier, the court
had turned down Landry's appeal in a 7-2 vote.
   Hawkins, 45, was convicted in the death of Abbe Rogers Hamilton
of Borger, who was killed after Hawkins entered her apparently
unlocked home.
   Hawkins also has a second death sentence for the abduction and
slaying of a 12-year-old Amarillo girl. He has been dubbed the
``traveling rapist'' after admitting to some 40 rapes, prosecutors
said.
   Last January, Landry came within three hours of execution before
the Supreme Court issued a stay.
   In appeals for each inmate, defense attorneys cited a case
pending before the Supreme Court involving Texas death row inmate
Johnny Penry. That case challenges the legality of executing
mentally retarded inmates.
   ``This man isn't retarded,'' assistant attorney general Bob Walt
said of Landry. ``I don't think that's going to fly with the Supreme
Court.''
   Landry, an 11th-grade dropout, has a lengthy criminal record,
including arrests for sexual assault and abuse of a juvenile,
assault, family neglect and petty larceny.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
