<2ND_LINE>PM-Burning Boat,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Men Rescued From Burning Boat Arrested For Marijuana
Trafficking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE DUNFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five men rescued after their 150-foot boat caught
fire last week 800 miles northeast of Hawaii have been arrested for
marijuana trafficking, authorities said.
   The five are accused of attempting to scuttle the fishing vessel,
the Iho Maru No. 23, by setting off explosives when the Coast Guard
cutter Jarvis confronted the boat Wednesday, Coast Guard Lt. j.g.
Brad Nelson said Monday.
   The fire, which continued to smolder late Monday, has prevented
authorities from searching the ship's cargo hold, said Coast Guard
spokesman Keith Spangler. A large quanity ot Thai stick marijuana is
believed in the hold, he said.
   The damaged vessel, listing 15 degrees, is under tow by the
Jarvis and is expected to reach Honolulu on Friday or Saturday,
Spangler said.
   Five men from are in custody aboard the Jarvis and will be
arraigned on maritime marijuana trafficking charges when they reach
Honolulu, federal authorities said.
   The fishing vessel's master was identified as Paul Arthur
Greyshock, 35, of Keaau, Hawaii. Crewmembers were identified as Mike
Stewart, 46, and Larry Landis, 45, of Keaau; Scott Davidson, 31, of
Kailua-Kona, and Christopher William Mussell, 38, believed to be
from New Zealand.
   Greyshock has been under investigation for several years,
officials of the FBI, Coast Guard, Customs Service and the U.S.
attorney's office said in a joint statement.
   He came under closer scrutiny after about $50,000 of undeclared
cash was seized from him at the Honolulu International Airport in
August after he arrived from Tahiti, officials said.
</TEXT>
