<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BillboardMonopoly     12-13 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Billboard Monopoly,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gannett and Two Other Firms Accused of Billboard Price Fixing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A subsidiary of Gannett Co. Inc. and two other
outdoor advertising firms conspired to fix prices for Southern
California billboard space, a federal grand jury has charged.
   A spokeswoman for Gannett, which runs North America's largest
outdoor advertising company, said the charges were baseless and
would be ``contested vigorously.''
   The monopoly was run by Gannett Outdoor of Southern California
and former chairman and chief executive officer Hal Brown;
Metromedia Inc. of Secaucus, N.J., and former vice president Michael
F. Tobey; and Foster and Kleiser Corp. of Delaware, said Judy
Whalley, of the U.S. Justice Department in Washington.
   The defendants were charged with suppressing competition in
violation of antitrust laws, Ms. Whalley, acting assistant attorney
general in charge of the department's antitrust division, said
Monday.
   If convicted, the firms could be fined $1 million and the men
could be sentenced to three years in prison and fined $100,000 each.
   ``The charges will be carefully studied, but Gannett believes
they are wrong and are based on a misunderstanding of the facts and
the law,'' spokeswoman Mimi Feller said in a statement.
   ``We believe these charges are without merit,'' said Arnold L.
Wadler, vice president and general counsel for Metromedia Inc., a
privately held telecommunications and technology company of which
Foster and Kleiser is an affliate.
   The allegations focus on a period before Gannett Co. Inc.
acquired Pacific Outdoor Advertising through a merger with Combined
Communications Corp. in 1979, turning it into Gannett Outdoor, Ms.
Feller said.
   The nationwide media company publishes 88 daily newspapers,
including USA Today, the Gannett News Services and USA Weekend
magazine. It also operates 10 TV stations and 16 radio stations, she
said.
</TEXT>
