<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Higgins     12-13 0659</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Higgins,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uncle: Kidnapped Marine `Would Die' Before Betraying His Country</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY40 of Dec. 12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, a
one-time aide to former defense secretary Caspar Weinberger held
hostage in Lebanon, will make his family and country proud
regardless of his fate, his uncle says.
   ``He loves his country,'' Delbert Eagle of Lancaster said after
Higgins was abducted Feb. 17. ``He is capable of standing up as well
as an ordinary man will under the circumstances. ... I don't think
they could bring enough pressure or pain to cause him to betray his
country in any way.
   ``I think he would die first.''
   On Monday, Lebanese kidnappers holding the 43-year-old Higgins
said in a statement they have sentenced him to death as a spy for
Israel.
   ``We have issued the irrevocable sentence to execute this
American spy,'' said the typewritten Arabic statement signed by the
Organization of the Oppressed on Earth.
   But the statement did not mention an execution date.
   Higgins' sister, Mary Fisher of Louisville, said she had no
knowledge of the threat other than what she has heard from reporters.
   ``I have not been contacted by anyone,'' she said Monday.
   When he was abducted, Higgins headed a 75-member observer group
assigned to a United Nations peacekeeping force in south Lebanon.
   A Pentagon official said at the time that Higgins was on
temporary detail serving as the chief of the U.N. Truce Supervision
Organization's Lebanon Observer Group.
   The group monitors cease-fire violations on the Lebanon-Israel
border. Higgins was the top-ranking American officer assigned to the
group, holding the title of senior U.S. military observer.
   By the time Higgins left for college, he was well on the way to
fulfilling the ambition he expressed in his senior yearbook: ``For
my family to always be proud of me.''
   When he was growing up in southern Jefferson County in the late
1950s and early 1960s, his friends never expected the chunky,
cheerful youngster to make his career in the military.
   ``He was just pretty much an average guy at Southern High
School,'' Rudy Fischer, an old friend, recalled after Higgins'
abduction.
   ``I think people were kind of surprised when he went into the
Marines,'' Fischer added. ``You think of the Marines as being macho
types, and he really wasn't like that.''
   Even so, Higgins won appointment to West Point, but chose instead
to study at Miami University of Ohio on a Navy ROTC scholarship.
   He opted for the Marines after suffering seasickness during a
summer cruise to Scandinavia, his brother-in-law, Harold Fischer,
recalled.
   Others who knew Higgins in Louisville remember him as a bright,
well-rounded young man who stood out in school and on the athletic
field.
   Higgins, whose friends knew him as ``Rich'' or ``Pinky,'' earned
mostly A's and B's. He played guard on his high school football team
in 1962 and 1963.
   ``He gave us 100 percent effort,'' said Henderson Wilson, then
the team's line coach.
   Higgins was president of his sophomore class, vice president of
his senior class and won membership in the Beta Club and Key Club,
according to his senior yearbook.
   His fellow seniors and teachers voted him one of the top 10
members of the class of 1963, based on scholarship, leadership,
school spirit and personality, said Assistant Principal Ralph Allen.
   He was commissioned as a second lieutenant when he graduated from
Miami University, and later earned master's degrees in human
resources management at Pepperdine University and political science
at Auburn University.
   Higgins was born in Danville, and lived in Lancaster, Covington
and Louisville. He and his first wife, the former Bonita Spalding of
Louisville, have a 17-year-old daughter, Christine Lynn. He has
another sister, Linda Lee Miller, of Memphis, Tenn.
   Higgins' second wife, Marine Maj. Robin Higgins, works at the
Pentagon.
   Both of his parents have died _ his mother, Mary Ethel Higgins,
in 1979, and his father, William F. Higgins, shortly after his
abduction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
