<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 0507EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HijackCoincidence     12-13 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack Coincidence,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20 Years After, Retired Pilot Surprised By Bizarre Coincidences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM CURRAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When retired TWA pilot Dennis Maloney
picked up a newspaper, he thought he might see a reference to a
hijacking that occurred 20 years ago.
   Instead, Monday's headline, ``TWA flight to Miami is hijacked,''
carried him back to Dec. 11, 1968, when he was the captain of
another Miami-bound TWA flight that was hijacked.
   The two piracies took place 20 years apart almost to the hour.
Both planes were Boeing 727s and the flight numbers contained the
same digits, Maloney said. His was Flight 496, Sunday's was Flight
469.
   ``I couldn't believe it. The same date, the same time, the same
type of aircraft,'' said Maloney of suburban Prairie Village, Kan.,
who retired 18 months ago after 23 years with TWA. ``I bet the
chances aren't 10 million to one of that happening.''
   Sunday's hijacking, only the second involving a domestic U.S.
airliner in 2{ years, never made it to Cuba, the intended
destination of the Cuban exile who claimed to have a bomb,
authorities said. The flight instead went to Grand Turk, part of the
British colony of Turks and Caicos Islands southeast of the Bahamas,
where the man was in custody pending extradition proceedings.
   Maloney's flight, which originated in Kansas City and stopped in
St. Louis, left Nashville for Miami when it was hijacked to Havana.
It was the 19th U.S. commercial airliner forced to Cuba in 1968's
wave of hijackings.
   Stories from 20 years ago described Maloney's hijacker as a
supercool gunman with a smiling female companion who appeared to be
about six months pregnant. Among the 32 passengers and crew of seven
were country singer Tex Ritter, father of actor John Ritter, and pro
golfer Mason Rudolph.
   Maloney, 54, recalled there was early speculation the gunman
might have been Eldridge Cleaver, the Black Panther Party activist
who had disappeared in November 1968 to avoid arrest for violating
parole.
   But after being shown pictures of Cleaver, Maloney and others
said he was not the hijacker. The gunman later was identified as a
man named Patterson, a Black Panther who eventually ended up in
Algeria, Maloney said.
   Maloney said the hijacker grabbed a cabin attendant, forced his
way into the cockpit and ordered the crew to fly to Cuba at gunpoint.
   When the plane landed in Havana, between 200 and 300 Cuban
soldiers surrounded the plane, Maloney said. The hijacker and his
companion were taken off, he was disarmed, and they were marched
away, he said.
   A diplomat from the Swiss embassy arrived and interrogated the
crew and passengers, who were taken to a restaurant and fed before
the passengers were taken to another airport and flown back to the
United States.
   Maloney and his crew flew out of Havana to Miami that evening.
   ``We all lived through it,'' Maloney said. ``There was no
problem, other than the delay. The next morning, I kiddingly said to
one of the administrative guys at TWA, `I promised the crew a week
off with pay.' He said, `I hope you've got enough money to pay for
it out of your own pocket.'''
   Later, as the number of hijackings continued to grow, it became a
policy to allow crews paid leave after an incident, Maloney said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 0512EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     12-13 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Remains In Icy Grip; Strong Winds Gust Through Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Much of the East today remained in the icy grip of arctic air
that brought record low temperatures, while chinook winds howled
through the Rockies.
   Temperatures dropped below zero in eastern New York state and
northern New England but the cold was less intense and widespread
than during Sunday night and Monday morning.
   Albany, N.Y., set a record for today's date when the mercury
plunged to 5 below zero, breaking the 1960 record of minus 1.
Shortly before midnight, Baltimore tied its record for Dec. 12 at 10
degrees and Newark, N.J., broke its 1960 record of 9 with a 6-degree
reading.
   The nation's high temperature Monday was 88 degrees at San
Gabriel, Calif.
   Light snow fell ahead of a cold front moving through the Great
Lakes region. Up to 3 inches covered several areas in Wisconsin, and
northern Illinois received an inch or less.
   The snow spread eastward into northeast Indiana, Ohio, and parts
of Kentucky and Michigan. Strong, gusty winds accompanied the snow,
reducing visibilities. The snow was expected to move into western
Pennsylvania this morning.
   A developing area of low pressure off Florida's east coast
produced sleet and snow along coastal areas of North Carolina.
   Windy conditions developed in the northern Rockies ahead of a
cold front moving across the Pacific Northwest. Livingston, Mont.,
recorded a gust of 58 mph Monday evening. A high wind warning
remained in effect this morning for the east slopes of the Rockies
and the upper Yellowstone Valley in Montana.
   The chinooks _ or winds that blow down the eastern slopes of the
Rockies _were expected to spread southward into the central Rockies
today.
   The cold front over the Pacific Northwest produced rain along the
northern Pacific coast and snow in the Cascade mountains. A snow
advisory was in effect today for the Cascades of Washington state.
   Today's forecast called for snowshowers from western New England
and the mid-Atlantic coast to the lower Great Lakes and much of
Michigan; rain from western North Dakota across Montana, and the
northern Pacific coast, with rain becoming snow in the higher
elevations.
   Predicted highs: teens in northern Maine, 20s and 30s from the
rest of New England across the mid-Atlantic coast, the northern
Appalachians, the Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley, the upper
Mississippi Valley and eastern North Dakota; 40s and 50s from North
Carolina across northern Florida, the central Gulf of Mexico states,
the Tennessee Valley, the central Mississippi Valley, the northern
Plains, the upper Missouri Valley, the Rockies and the northern
Pacific coast; 70s in southern Florida, southern Texas, and from
southern Arizona across Southern California.
   The rest of the nation should generally reach the 60s.
   The nation's temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 8 degrees
below zero at Glens Falls, N.Y., to 73 at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 27 fair; Boston 14 fair; Buffalo 19 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 29 fair; Cincinnati 27 snow; Cleveland 20 snow;
Detroit 23 snow; Miami 65 cloudy; New York 17 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 13 fair; Pittsburgh 18 cloudy; Portland, Maine 5 fair;
Washington 16 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 34 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 38 fair; Denver 38
fair; Des Moines 35 fair; Indianapolis 28 snow; Kansas City 39
cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 37 windy; Nashville 35 windy; New
Orleans 35 fair; St. Louis 35 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 27 fair; Anchorage 19 cloudy; Las Vegas 45
fair; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 52 fair; Salt Lake City 34 fair;
San Diego 51 fair; San Francisco 46 foggy; Seattle 49 windy.
   _Canada: Montreal 10 fair; Toronto 23 snow.
</TEXT>
