<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 0554EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-China     12-13 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-China,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Reported To Have Received 50 Combat Jets From China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran received the final delivery of 50
fighter jets from China before the Aug. 20 cease-fire in its war
with Iraq, well-informed diplomatic sources reported today.
   The J-6 and F-7 jets, Chinese versions of the Soviet-built MiG-19
and MiG-21, were delivered by ship over three years in knocked-down
form through Iran's Persian Gulf port of Bandar Abbas, a key naval
and air base, and assembled in Iran, the sources said.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Chinese
jets, along with a large quantity of air-to-air missiles, were
allocated to the Revolutionary Guards' air wing, not the regular air
force.
   Western military officials could not confirm the delivery. But
Don Kerr, an aviation specialist with the London-based International
Institute for Strategic Studies said the jets had been expected
``for some time''.
   ``The quantity and the timing are certainly right for the
Iranians in their effort to develop weapons systems from other
sources to get around their very serious problems of supply for
their U.S.-built equipment,'' Kerr said in a telephone interview.
   China is Iran's major arms supplier and has provided Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini's regime with anti-ship Silkworm missiles and a
squadron of 10 J-6s in 1985 for training purposes.
   Iran's military collapsed in a series of Iraqi victories before
the United Nations-sponsored cease-fire took effect and it is
seeking to rebuild its forces.
   The International Institute for Strategic Studies reported last
year that Iran signed a $1.6 billion deal with Beijing in 1985 for
combat aircraft, tanks and artillery.
   Mednews, a Paris-based newsletter specializing in Middle East
defense issues, reported Nov. 21 that the deal involved what it
identified as 60 F-7 and F-7M jets, each costing more than $6
million, between July 1985 and February 1987.
   However, the diplomatic sources reported that final deliveries
were delayed until earlier this year.
   Mednews, quoting what it said was a copy of the contract between
the Chinese and the Iranians, said Beijing also agreed to supply 500
PL-2 and 2,000 PL-2A air-to-air-missiles, modeled on the U.S.
Sidewinder missile.
   Also in the deal were 1,000 PL-7 air-to-air missiles, copied from
the French R-550 Matra weapon, and 72,500 57mm air-to-ground
rockets, Mednews said.
   The Chinese also contracted to provide spare engines and
technical backup with aircrews and ground crews to train Iranians,
Mednews reported.
   China has denied it sells arms to Iran or Iraq, although the
Institute for Strategic Studies lists J-6 fighters in Iraq's air
force inventory.
   The delivery of the jets virtually doubled the size of Iran's
badly depleted air strength. But none of the Chinese fighters was
ever reported in combat, even when the Iranians were suffering
military defeats between April and July.
   ``It takes three years to get personnel trained and operational
on new aircraft,'' Kerr said. ``So it's not surprising the F-7s were
not committed in the fighting earlier this year, even when the
Iranians had their backs to the wall.
   ``The personnel flying these planes would still have been very
inexperienced.
   The Iranian air force was built around U.S.-supplied F-4
Phantoms, F-5 Tigers and F-14 Tomcats delivered before Khomeini's
Islamic revolution toppled Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi in 1979.
   Before the Iran-Iraq war erupted in September 1980, the Iranian
air force had 447 combat aircraft.
   But because of a chronic lack of spares, mainly due to a U.S.
arms embargo, and combat losses, Western analysts estimate the
Iranians now only have around 50 operational U.S.-made warplanes,
some without working radars.
   Iraq's air force, equipped mainly with Soviet and French
aircraft, outnumbers the Iranians by at least 6 to 1.
</TEXT>
