<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 0737EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Provenzano     12-13 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Provenzano,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mobster Provenzano Dies While Serving Racketeering Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMPOC, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mobster Anthony ``Tony Pro'' Provenzano,
the man former Teamsters leader Jimmy Hoffa was on his way to meet
when he vanished, has died of a heart attack while serving a federal
racketeering sentence.
   Provenzano died at Lompoc District Hospital, near the federal
prison where he was serving a 20-year term for two racketeering
conspiracy offenses, prison spokesman Chuck LaRoe said.
   The 71-year-old former New Jersey union boss had been confined to
the hospital in Lompoc, 140 miles northwest of Los Angeles, for
treatment of congestive heart failure.
   ``What he represented and has represented in the past is the
worst of the labor movement,'' said New Jersey State Police
Superintendant Col. Clinton L. Pagano.
   A convicted murderer and extortionist, Provenzano engendered
strong loyalty in Teamsters Local 560 in Union City, N.J. It was the
nation's third-largest local with 13,000 members when he ruled it in
the early 1960s.
   Ousted Local 560 officer Michael Sciarra in court called
Provenzano his ``idol'' and said he would ``pray'' for his return
after Provenzano was sentenced to jail in 1978 for ordering the
murder of a union rival.
   Sciarra was on the union board that U.S. District Judge Harold A.
Ackerman deposed in 1984 after finding in a government suit that the
local had been dominated by the Genovese organized-crime family.
   The union functioned under a trustee for 2{ years before members
last week elected a new leadership of Sciarra proteges, headed by
his brother, Danny. A judge had barred Michael Sciarra from running
because of his ties to the local's old regime.
   In July 1975, Hoffa disappeared while on his way to a Detroit
meeting with Provenzano, then president of his local. Hoffa is
presumed dead, but his body was never found.
   According to an FBI memo, Hoffa and Provenzano had feuded when
both were in federal prison. The FBI speculated Hoffa had hoped to
make peace with Provenzano and forge an alliance that would aid his
drive to regain power.
   ``According to the FBI reconstruction of the Hoffa murder, Tony
Pro called the so-called peace parley with Hoffa and then ordered
him killed,'' according to Carl Sifakis, author of Mafia
Encyclopedia.
   Provenzano was born to Italian immigrant parents on New York
City's Lower East Side and began driving a truck in Hackensack,
N.J., in 1934 at age 17. He became a Local 560 shop steward in 1941,
rose to business agent in 1950 and president eight years later.
   One year later, Provenzano came to head the New Jersey Joint
Teamsters Council, which represented 80,000 truckers. In 1960, he
became one of 13 vice presidents of the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters.
   He ``influenced the Teamsters at the highest level. He was the
epitome of control by intimidation,'' said Pagano. ``They controlled
whether a business would or would not function simply by whether
goods moved in or out.''
   Provenzano went to prison in 1966 for extorting $17,000 from a
truck company in exchange for labor peace. His brothers, Salvatore
and Nunzio, who also have been imprisoned for racketeering and
extortion, maintained control of the local.
   Anthony Provenzano was sentenced to life in prison in 1978 in New
York state for a union rival's murder. He was sentenced in federal
court the following year for racketeering.
   He would have been eligible for release in 1992.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
