<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TexasExecution 1stLd-Writethru a0473 12-13 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Execution, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0473,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Execution Delayed By Leaking Syringe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to clarify. SUBS 11th graf, `Landry, an ...,' to fix
tense.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who murdered an immigrant
restaurateur as the man's wife watched was put to death by injection
early today in an execution delayed when a tube from an intravenous
needle sprung a leak.
   Raymond Landry, 39, was pronounced dead at 12:45 a.m., hours
after the U.S. Supreme Court spared a second convicted murderer from
being executed.
   Landry was the 104th person executed in the United States since
the Supreme Court reinstated capital punishment in 1976 and 11th
this year.
   Prison officials began administering the lethal dosage at 12:21
a.m. Landry was not pronounced dead until 24 minutes later. In
between, a tube attached to a needle inside his right arm began
leaking, sending the lethal mixture shooting across the death
chamber toward witnesses.
   ``There was something of a delay in the execution because of what
officials called a `blowout,''' said Charles Brown, spokesman for
the Texas Department of Corrections. ``The syringe came out of the
vein and the warden ordered the (execution) team to reinsert the
catheter into the vein.''
   After Landry was brought into the death chamber, he shook his
head briefly when asked by Warden Jack Pursley if he had something
to say.
   At first, he showed no reaction to the drugs, and his lips
quivered.
   The leak occurred two minutes after the injections began.
   Pursley quickly pulled a curtain across the viewing area to block
witnesses' views. For more than 14 minutes, witnesses heard doors
opening and closing, mumbling, and at least one groan.
   The curtain was then reopened and Landry was motionless and
appeared dead with his eyes half closed.
   Three minutes later, two doctors arrived. They declared him dead
at 12:45 a.m.
   Brown said it was the first time such a problem had occurred in
Texas, which leads the nation with 29 executions since resumption of
capital punishment. In 1985 however, authorities repeatedly jabbed
needles into Stephen Morin when they had trouble finding a usable
vein because he had been a drug abuser.
   Landry was convicted in the death of Kosmas Prittis, a Greek
immigrant who was robbed and shot in the head while he and his
family were closing their Houston restaurant in 1982.
   Landry, an 11th-grade dropout, had a lengthy criminal record,
including arrests for sexual assault and abuse of a juvenile,
assault, family neglect and petty larceny.
   Late Monday, the Supreme Court blocked the execution of Samuel
Hawkins, who was convicted of the 1976 rape-slaying of a 19-year-old
woman. Had he been put to death along with Landry, it would have
been the first time since 1976 that a state had put two people to
death on the same day.
   The high court voted 7-2 earlier Monday to reject Landry's appeal.
   In appeals for each inmate, defense attorneys cited a case
pending before the Supreme Court involving Texas death-row inmate
Johnny Penry. That case challenges the legality of executing
mentally retarded inmates.
   ``This man isn't retarded,'' assistant attorney general Bob Walt
said of Landry. ``I don't think that's going to fly with the Supreme
Court.''
   In January, Landry came within three hours of execution before
the Supreme Court issued a stay.
   Hawkins, 45, was convicted in the death of Abbe Rogers Hamilton
of Borger, who was killed after Hawkins entered her apparently
unlocked home.
   Hawkins also has a second death sentence for the abduction and
slaying of a 12-year-old Amarillo girl. He has been dubbed the
``traveling rapist'' after admitting to some 40 rapes, prosecutors
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 0820EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTLAuction     12-13 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL Auction,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Judge Once Again To Consider Bids For PTL's Assets</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CF1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trustee overseeing PTL says he
believes a bankruptcy judge is likely to reject a bid for the
television ministry by a Canadian businessman and to sell the
ministry's assets piecemeal.
   Trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton said U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus
Reynolds was unlikely to extend the sale and probably would reject
the high bid of $36.25 million made Monday by Stephen Mernick, a
Toronto real estate developer.
   ``His (Reynolds') patience has been tested, and I don't think
he'll want to go any further,'' Benton said Monday.
   Reynolds was scheduled to rule on the sale of PTL's assets during
a hearing this afternoon in Columbia.
   PTL's religious leader, Sam Johnson, said Monday he hoped
Reynolds would keep intact the ministry's complex here, called
Heritage USA, and give PTL's contributors more time to secure
financing to buy back the ministry. Johnson is president of Heritage
Ministries, PTL's non-profit arm.
   Benton predicted Reynolds would order the ministry's assets
liquidated. But he said it was possible the judge would open bidding
again on the 2,200 acres of property, which includes a 500-room
hotel, a water park, a television studio and a 2,000-seat church.
   The bidders and Benton compared Monday's auction, in which bids
were raised in increments ranging from $1,000 to about $1 million,
to a card game in which the players withheld their final bet and
gambled that Reynolds would change the the conditions of the sale
today. One condition was that bidding begin at $50 million.
   ``Nobody won this afternoon,'' bidder Cy Bahakel, a former North
Carolina state senator who owns 15 television stations, said Monday.
``It's a new ballgame tomorrow in court.''
   The ministry filed for bankruptcy reorganization in June 1987,
three months after founder Jim Bakker left amid revelations of
luxurious living and hush money paid to Jessica Hahn, a secretary at
a New York church with whom Bakker admitting having a sexual liaison.
   The offers Monday were far below the appraised value of PTL's
assets _ $92 million to $110 million _ and half of that offered in
the initial auction in November.
   A month ago, Mernick said he would pay $115 million, $50 million
of it in cash. But Reynolds rejected the bid, saying there were
inadequate assurances that Mernick would pay the remaining $65
million.
   The four apparent contenders for the assets _ Mernick, Bahakel,
Johnson's group and a new bidder, Michael Karas, president of First
Canadian Development Co. of Toronto _ all said they were prepared to
bid again today.
   Heritage Ministries did not bid at Monday's auction, which was
closed to the public, but Johnson said he was negotiating with other
bidders on a joint offer.
   Johnson, pastor of the church at Heritage USA, said he held off
bidding because he was unwilling to meet a condition that called for
the downpayment to be forfeited if a bidder was unable to secure
financing.
   Johnson's group held a telethon on PTL's TV show last weekend
that brought its kitty up to $5 million for the downpayment.
   In another PTL development, former PTL officials David and James
Taggart, who face federal tax charges, were sued by New York jeweler
Cartier for $158,925 it says they owe for items they purchased last
year.
   Cartier, in its suit filed in Mecklenburg County Superior Court
in Charlotte, N.C., says the debt is the balance the Taggarts owe
for $203,925 they spent at Cartier on May 23, 1987. That was about a
month after PTL officials dismissed David Taggart, once Bakker's top
aide. His brother, James, did interior design work for PTL until
early 1987.
   The Taggarts have declined requests for interviews for the past
18 months and have referred questions to their Washington attorney,
Ben Cotton, who did not return telephone calls Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
