<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OfficersCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0506 12-13 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Officers Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0506,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Officers Killed In Wrong-Way Patrol Car Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The mood ...,' with 1 graf to clarify
reference to lights and sirens.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City police were ordered to wear
shoulder-harness seat belts after two patrol cars collided, killing
three officers and injuring a fourth on his first day on the job.
   ``It is a terrible loss, three young men in the prime of their
lives. These young men were very eager and very aggressive,'' said
Chief Daryl Gates, who issued the order.
   The officers killed were not wearing seat belts.
   Previously, department policy gave officers the option of wearing
either lap belts or belts with shoulder harnesses. The officer who
survived Monday's 3:25 a.m. crash was wearing a seat belt but it was
not immediately known which type.
   The cruisers collided when the officers were en route to aid
plainclothes detectives who pulled over a car reported stolen. One
of the cruisers was traveling the wrong way down a one-way street.
   Fellow officers wept during their roll calls when told of the
deaths.
   ``It's like a bomb hit them,'' a somber Gates said. ``It's hard
to see grown men cry.'' Flags at all stations were to be flown at
half staff.
   The mood, however, did not soften Gates' criticism of the dead
officers. Both cars appeared to have been traveling in excess of the
35 mph city speed limit, and emergency flashing lights or sirens may
have been in operation. The use of lights or sirens to respond to a
call for backup would have been in violation of department
regulations.
   ``This is a good example of what happens when you do not follow
the rules,'' Gates said. It was not known how fast the cars were
going but Gates said, ``They were moving at a rate of speed you
could call overdrive.''
   Officers may ignore rules of the road only when responding to the
more serious ``officer needs help call.''
   Officer David Hofmeyer, 25, who was driving one cruiser, and his
passenger, Officer Derrick Conner, 28, were dead at the scene. The
other driver, Officer Manuel Gutierrez Jr., 26, died later at
County-USC Medical Center. His cruiser was traveling the wrong way
on the one-way street.
   Gutierrez's partner, Officer Venson Drake, 28, was treated for
cuts and bruises at the hospital and released. Drake graduated last
Friday from the department's training academy.
   Before Monday, the city's worst accident involving police
officers occurred in 1983 when a driver ran a stop light and
broadsided a cruiser, killing two patrolmen. The driver survived the
crash and escaped.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
