<DOCNO> AP881213-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 0838EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Quake-Trapped     12-13 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Quake-Trapped,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Survivor Tells of Ordeal in the Rubble</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man buried by the Armenian earthquake said he bit
the earth and shoveled with his nose to make his way out of the
rubble of his collapsed factory.
   Misha Nuridzhanyan rushed to find his wife and three children,
only to learn they were trapped beneath separate buildings.
   The newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda today published an account by
the Leninakan sewing factory inspector who was caught in the Dec. 7
quake that killed up to 60,000 people throughout Armenia and
destroyed much of his city.
   ``At 11:30, we felt faint tremors,'' Nuridzhanyan recalled.
``Everybody jumped up and ran for the stairs. But we succeeded in
running only 10-15 meters, and then everything collapsed. If I had
not grabbed a pillar, I would have been thrown by the shock, 20
meters, not less. I don't remember anything after that.
   ``When I came to, it was dark. I was curled like a fetus, not
flat, but _ how can I explain _ like a rolled bun, with my head
hunched down between my shoulders. Apparently I instinctively shrank
when everything started to fall all around me.
   ``I waited _ would there be another tremor or not? Certainly, if
another quake hit, nothing would be left of me. Around me, I could
hear my friends shouting to each other.
   ```Where are you?'
   ```My leg is squeezed.'
   ```My hand...'
   ```Please talk to me. Don't keep silent.'
   ``It was terrifying, a nightmare.
   ``I tried to move and could not. Everything was squeezed _ my
hands, my legs, my chest. Just my head was free. From the roof, dirt
and sand were pouring onto me. I felt someone's blood flowing over
me. I bit into the dirt with my teeth, and shoveled with my nose.
   ``Then a light appeared. After I crawled out, I don't know why,
but I looked at my watch _ it still ran. I realized that I had spent
an hour and a half in a grave. I just lay down on the top of the
rubble and my mind went blank. Then I was awakened by voices saying,
`Go home, go home.'
   ``I could see that there was no help, no one was helping to dig
through the rubble. Somebody managed to crawl out by himself. He was
in his underwear, because all his clothes had been peeled off by the
stones as he crawled out.
   ``I went barefoot to a hospital. I stayed there until 4 p.m. Then
I was given a lift home. I went there, thinking: with two little
children, nothing can happen _ because my daughter is going to first
grade and the school is just two stories, so it should stand the
shock. My son is in kindergarten, a one-story building. My wife
works at a two-story building. And the youngest is with my
mother-in-law at home, a five-story building.
   ``I was brought to the rubble. Everything had collapsed. There my
beloved ones were lying, and there they remain today.
   ``I stood up and didn't know where to move. I went to the house
of my sister, where she and her husband screamed at me, ``Misha, you
must go to the doctor, your head is bleeding.'' I couldn't care less
about my head, no, I couldn't leave before I found my child. But I
started to feel sick in the night. I was taken to Yerevan by
helicopter.
   ``Now, I know I have 27 stitches in my head and I feel the pain.
But then, I felt nothing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 0840EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shoreham-NRC     12-13 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shoreham-NRC,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Free To Consider License For Shoreham Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The staff of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
has cleared the way for the five-member commission to consider an
operating license for the Long Island Lighting Co.'s long-delayed
Shoreham nuclear power plant.
   The staff on Monday agreed with a September decision by the
Atomic Safety Licensing Board, which found that New York state and
Suffolk County had willfully obstructed the federal government's
attempt to resolve the Shoreham stalemate.
   The $5.3 billion plant, which was completed in 1984, has been
unable to obtain an operating license because the state and local
governments maintain that the surrounding area of densely populated
Long Island could not be evacuated in an emergency.
   If the commission accepts its staff's advice to uphold the
board's recommendation that the local and state governments be
dismissed from the Shoreham proceedings, no issues will remain to
prevent a full-power license for the plant, said Frank Ingram, a
commission spokesman in Washington.
   Ray Golden, a Lilco spokesman, said the utility was ``very
pleased ... and optimistic that the NRC commissioners will act
quickly on approval'' of a license.
   Brad O'Hearn, a spokesman for Suffolk County Executive Patrick
Halpin, said the county ``will pursue vigorously with the full NRC
board our contention that Shoreham should not be operated'' because
of evacuation concerns.
   Lilco has sought a full- or 25 percent-power license for Shoreham
despite a settlement reached between the state and the utility to
close the plant. The utility's directors have said Lilco would abide
by the settlement if the state Legislature approved it before a
license was granted.
   The lawmakers, who objected to the settlement as too generous to
LILCO, left Albany without approving it. The settlement would allow
the utility to increase rates 5 percent annually over 10 years.
   On Dec. 5, a U.S. District Court jury in New York City found that
Lilco and a former executive engaged in a pattern of lies to obtain
rate increases to help pay for the Shoreham plant.
   The jury awarded $7.6 million to Suffolk County. That amount is
tripled to $22.8 million under the racketeering charges brought
against the utility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 0903EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia-Crash     12-13 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia-Crash,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crash May Have Been Caused By Misunderstanding, Pilot Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crash of a Yugoslav military
plane bringing earthquake relief to Armenia may have been caused by
a misunderstanding between the pilot and Soviet air traffic
controllers, a Yugoslav pilot was quoted as saying today.
   The Yugoslav Air Force AN-12 plane crashed Monday while trying to
land at Yerevan airport, killing all seven people aboard. Local
reporters said the pilot mistook a well-lit highway for a runway.
   Capt. Ljubomir Pavlovic, who landed another Yugoslav plane at
Yerevan airport hours after the crash, told the state news agency
Tanjug that the Soviet Union has not adopted an International Civil
Airports' Association recommendation on measurement of altitude.
   As a result, he said, there was ``a possibility of a
misunderstanding between the Yugoslav crew and the Soviet flight
control in Yerevan.''
   A common method used at domestic airports in the Soviet Union is
to read altitude in meters, while international practice is to read
the distance of the plane above the ground in feet.
   Pavlovic said Yerevan airport, where dozens of flights are
landing daily as earthquake relief pours into Armenia, is not
equipped to receive international flights.
   ``I assume that the airport has now received technical and staff
assistance from Moscow and Leningrad,'' Pavlovic told Tanjug.
   Pavlovic suggested fatigue also might have played a part in the
crash. He said the crew prepared all day Sunday for takeoff, and
flew for four hours before being forced by bad weather to make an
emergency landing in Ankara, Turkey.
   Tanjug described Pavlovic as an experienced pilot who has flown
to the Soviet Union often. He spoke to Tanjug after returning from
Yerevan.
   The Soviets and the Yugoslavs have formed a joint commission to
investigate the plane crash, Tanjug said.
   The Dec. 7 quake devastated Armenia. A Soviet official today put
the death toll from the quake at 55,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
