<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FamilyKilling     12-13 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Family Killing,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Says He Lied in Family-Poisoning Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARCADIA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Efforts to free a farmworker imprisoned in
the poisoning deaths of his seven children two decades ago may be
gaining momentum after a witness admitted he lied at the man's
trial, the man's lawyers say.
   The last surviving witness to an alleged jailhouse confession
that helped convict James Richardson of one of the 1967 killings
recanted his courtroom story during recent interviews with
investigators. The interviews were ordered by Gov. Bob Martinez to
re-examine the trial.
   ``I didn't hear Richardson say anything while I was in there,''
James Weaver, 67, said in the interviews, according to the Florida
Department of Law Enforcement. ``I ain't never heard the boy say
anything about it. ... I hope Richardson will get out. I want him to
get out.''
   Peter Dunbar, the governor's general counsel, said Weaver's
statement also was contained in an old prosecution file that
Richardson's lawyer, Mark Lane, turned over to Martinez' office two
months ago. Lane said the file had been stolen years earlier by
someone concerned about the case.
   ``There appears to be some foundation to some of the
allegations,'' Dunbar said. ``Now, whether or not that has some
bearing is what we'll have to decide.''
   Richardson, 52, of Arcadia was convicted of one of the killings
and sentenced to life after he was accused of putting the deadly
insecticide parathion in food a baby sitter served his children,
ages 2 to 8.
   Lane and Richardson's other attorney, Ellis Rubin, said Weaver's
admission will help when they petition for a new trial Thursday.
   Rubin and Lane said they will file appeals to the state Supreme
Court and the trial court, charging the state knowingly used
perjured testimony.
   ``I want a jury to hear that he was framed, and to bring out the
perjury on the record,'' Rubin said.
   Martinez will wait until after he has been briefed on the state
investigative report this week to decide whether to call for a
clemency hearing, said Brian Ballard, the governor's director of
operations.
   Some of the most damaging testimony against Richardson at his
1968 trial came from Weaver and another jailed felon, James Dean
Cunningham. Authorities contended that Richardson, a fruit picker,
confessed to both men while awaiting trial.
   A third convict who also allegedly heard Richardson confess died
before trial, but his similar account was read into the record.
Cunningham was shot to death in 1979.
   Weaver's recantation is the latest development that casts doubt
on Richardson's conviction, his lawyers say.
   Earlier this year it was reported that the former baby sitter,
Betsy Reese, now 67, told nurses in a nursing home in 1985 that she
had poisoned the children.
   Last week, Arcadia's former police chief, Richard Barnard, said
he believed that Richardson was framed by then-DeSoto County Sheriff
Frank Cline.
   Weaver and Cunningham ``would have done or said anything that
Frank Cline asked them to do, including making false statements
under oath,'' in return for lenient sentences, Barnard said.
   Cline disputed Barnard's allegation. And prosecutors say the baby
sitter, who is immobile and has lapsed into silence, became confused
over the years after having innocently served a poisoned meal.
   Richardson is eligible for parole in 1993.
</TEXT>
