<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1033EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Angola-Namibia 3rdLd-Writethru   12-13 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola-Namibia, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa, Angola, Cuba Sign Agreement on Namibia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with quotes from Botha, Nambian
officials, names of signatories, other detail. No Pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW TORCHIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa, Cuba and Angola pledged
peace in Southwestern Africa today, opening the way for withdrawal
of 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola and independence for the
continent's last colony of Namibia.
   U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker, who led eight
months of intermittent negotiations on three continents, said the
accord is ``a new symbol of peace in the world.''
   It ends years of negotiating over one of Africa's most
intractable disputes.
   Officials of the three countries signed the agreement, to be
finalized in New York on Dec. 22, at a ceremony attended by Crocker,
host President Denis Sassou-Nguesso of Congo and Soviet and United
Nations' representatives.
   ``We want to be accepted by our African brothers. We need each
other,'' South African Foreign Minister R.F. Botha declared after he
signed for the white-led country. ``A new era has begun. We are
removing race discrimination,'' he said.
   Ricardo Alarcon, Cuban vice minister for foreign affairs, and
Angolan armed forces chief Gen. Antonio dos Santos Ndalu signed for
their governments.
   Botha earlier told reporters the U.N.-supervised independence
process for South-West Africa, which is better known as Namibia,
will begin April 1. Elections will be held seven months later and
the mineral-rich territory will be independent in about a year, he
said.
   Mediated by the United States and supported by the Soviet Union,
the agreement will free the former German colony from 73 years of
South African control and end 22 years of sporadic bush warfare.
   ``This will bring an end to international conflict in
Southwestern Africa,'' Crocker said. ``It is the end of a sad
chapter in African history.''
   Still unsettled is the civil war in Angola between the pro-Soviet
government and rebels backed by South Africa and the United States.
But the treaty will bar the involvement of South African and Cuban
forces in that arena, scaling down its potential for regional
conflict.
   Under today's agreement, 3,000 Cuban soldiers will leave Angola
before April 1 and the rest will withdraw within 27 months from that
date. Half the Cubans will be out by the time Namibian elections are
held Nov. 1.
   At the same time, remaining Cuban forces will gradually move
north from the Namibian border. By election time, they are all to be
north of the Benguela railroad, at least 350 miles from Namibia.
   The three countries are to establish a joint commission to
resolve disputes about implementing the peace accords and Angola and
Cuba are to reach agreements with U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar on means to verify the Cuban pullout.
   Crocker praised the ``close, practical and effective cooperation
with our Soviet counterparts.'' The Soviet Union was not formally
involved but played a significant role in bringing the parties
together.
   To applause from African diplomats and government officials,
Crocker said the agreement was a ``case study of superpower efforts
to support solutions to regional conflicts.''
   South Africa had declared its agreement to a 10-year-old U.N.
independence plan, but was backed by the United States in linking it
to a withdrawal of Cubans. They arrived in 1975 to back the dominant
Marxists against South African and pro-West factions.
   In Namibia's capital, Windhoek, political figures said they
looked forward to April 1 with cautious optimism.
   ``April Fool's Day. I don't trust that date. But we'll accept
it,'' said Andreas Shipanga, the black Namibian who chairs the
Cabinet of the transitional government.
   Shipanga said the South Africans had not given the transitional
government advance warning of the independence date.
   He said he hoped the date ``would not appear and disappear like
so many others. We cannot continue in a state of limbo. It is
destroying the country and the morale of our people.''
   Ben Ulenga, leader of the pro-independence National Union of
Namibian Workers, said Namibians would remain skeptical about
independence until the ``last South African troops leave the
country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
