<1ST_LINE>r i PM-QuakeDogs     12-13 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quake Dogs,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search Dogs Stop Work Because of Cut Paws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teams of Austrian dogs scouring the rubble
in Armenia for earthquake survivors can no longer go on because
their paws are cut by glass and stone, reports said today.
   Newspapers quoted Austrian rescue workers in Armenia as saying
the dogs had guided rescuers to at least four survivors in ruins in
Leninakan, Armenia's second largest city.
   At present, there are 154 Austrians helping in the search and
rescue effort in Armenia following the Dec. 7 quake. Some are from
the Austrian army and Red Cross and have been working in Leninakan
along with 20 dogs they brought with them, the Vienna daily Der
Standard said.
   Gerhard Lobenschegg, leader of the Red Cross team in Leninakan,
said all dogs there would have to stop working because of the damage
to their paws.
   A 49-man private team with 40 dogs was working in Spitak, a city
virtually destroyed by the quake, Der Standard said. It quoted the
group as saying dogs can be used for a maximum of only a week at a
time before they are exhausted and must be replaced.
   About 150 Austrian soldiers will probably fly to Yerevan this
week, the Defense Ministry said.
</TEXT>
