<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1045EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionPlaintiff     12-13 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Plaintiff,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Claims To Be Anonymous Plaintiff In Abortion Legalization
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman claiming to be the anonymous plaintiff in
one of two U.S. Supreme Court cases that legalized abortion in 1973
has petitioned a federal court to unseal case records in order to
help reverse the ruling.
   In an interview Monday with The Atlanta Constitution, she said
she wants to be able to prove her identity as the plaintiff to give
her anti-abortion work credibility.
   ``Mary Doe didn't want an abortion. Mary Doe didn't have an
abortion. Mary Doe won't ever have an abortion,'' said the Atlanta
woman, who was not identified by name in the interview.
   In the petition filed Friday in U.S. District Court in Atlanta
without the assistance of an attorney, she requested to be ``allowed
to open the envelope with the true identity of Mary Doe, being I am
Mary Doe.''
   The petition said her name at the time of the case was Sandra Kay
Race Bensing, according to the petition. Now 40, she has since
married twice.
   Records containing the identity of the anonymous plaintiff can be
unsealed only by a judge's order.
   Atlanta lawyer Margie Pitts Hames, who represented ``Mary Doe''
before the Supreme Court, was in London on Monday and could not be
reached for comment.
   She said before the petition was filed: ``I'm not prepared to
talk to anybody about Mary Doe's identity. We took great steps to
see that her identity was kept confidential.''
   Ms. Hames said she lost touch with the plaintiff and has been
trying to locate her for six years.
   No hearing has been set on the woman's request to open the file,
which was sealed at Ms. Hames' request.
   The newspaper reported in today's editions that the woman said
participating in the case was the biggest mistake she ever made. She
said she opposes abortion and hopes the Supreme Court ruling can be
reversed.
   ``I decided from the very beginning I would never consent to an
abortion,'' she said. ``I'm not a religious person but I believe in
God. I know he's real. I know we don't take lives.''
   She said that even after the Supreme Court ruling, she continued
her pregnancy and gave up her newborn daughter for adoption.
   The ruling in the Georgia case, Doe vs. Bolton _ referring to
then-state Attorney General Arthur K. Bolton _ was handed down by
the Supreme Court on Jan. 22, 1973.
   The court said Georgia's conditions for abortions were too
restrictive, that medical committees were unnecessary to approve
abortions and that the state could not prohibit abortions outside
accredited hospitals.
   The case was overshadowed by Roe vs. Wade, a Texas case ruled on
the same day. In that case, the Supreme Court struck down Texas'
abortion law as a violation of a woman's right to privacy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
