<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ColdRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0478 12-13 0801</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cold Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0478,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bitter Cold Grips East, Relief In Sight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with six deaths, details of frozen police
station, winter gear sales, woman who fell in creek, editing to
tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Toe-tingling arctic air lingered over the East today, but a
reprieve was in sight from the season's first big chill, which
contributed to at least six deaths, stalled cars and burst pipes
from the Great Lakes to the South.
   The deep freeze taxed utilities, filled shelters for the homeless
and gave some students a holiday when furnaces quit or buses froze.
Schools were closed today in more than a dozen Kentucky counties
because of snow-slickened roads.
   The subzero cold today set a record for the date in Albany, N.Y.,
where a reading of minus 5 exceeded the minus 1 record set in 1960.
   On Monday, records for the date were set in 25 cities.
   Temperatures were expected to warm into the 30s by Wednesday as a
weather system nudges the arctic air east, said meterologist Brian
Smith at the National Weather Service's Severe Storms Forecast
Center in Kansas City, Mo.
   By this morning, temperatures already had started rising. In
Providence, R.I., it was 24 degrees at 9 a.m. Monday's high
temperature was 20 degrees.
   The warming trend wasn't enough for police in Burrillville, north
of Providence, however. The station's six water pipes froze Monday,
said Chief Wallace F. Lees. One pipe burst, flooding some rooms.
   ``There are still five (pipes) we haven't got thawed out,'' he
said this morning. ``We can't incarcerate any people because of the
cold conditions.''
   Many people took the cold in stride, pausing only to yank on an
extra sweater or dig out a winter cap.
   Elizabeth Vrotkoski and Mary Dobranski worked non-stop Monday
selling cold weather gear at Boscov's department store in
Wilkes-Barre, Pa., where it dropped to minus 5 degrees. By
midafternoon, the women said they had sold 119 pairs of gloves, 40
scarves and 48 pairs of slippers.
   ``We've always had cold weather here, so it's nothing new to
us,'' said Wilma Kuebler, a receptionist at the Emmet County airport
just north of Pellston in northern Michigan, where the temperature
dropped to minus 16 Monday.
   ``Other than a door freezing shut, it hasn't stopped us,'' she
said.
   In Buffalo, N.Y., where it was a record minus 9 degrees Monday,
William Doss' beard was frozen when he reached his downtown office.
``Take my advice: It's best not to get too worked up about the
temperature this early in the season,'' he said.
   The cold brought the plight of the homeless to the forefront, but
some stayed away from shelters and sought cover in subways, parks or
makeshift structures on city streets.
   ``The worst people stay in those shelters,'' said Eli, a
48-year-old homeless man in New York City who wouldn't give his last
name. ``You're better off to stay in the subway because at least
there's police there.''
   In Philadelphia, dozens of homeless people erected a cardboard
city in a subway station four blocks from City Hall.
   In New York City, two men thought to be homeless have been found
dead since Sunday, one on a street, the other in a park. Police said
the cold may have been a factor in the deaths. And a woman found in
a subway station was believed by police to have died of a
combination of a drug overdose and the cold.
   In Baltimore, a house fire killed a woman in her 60s early
Monday. The house had no electricity, and police said the woman
apparently was using candles for heat and light.
   Officials in Luzerne County, Pa., ruled the death of a woman
found on her porch was hypothermia. And at least two other deaths,
both in traffic accidents, in Pennsylvania were attributed to the
weather.
   An 84-year-old woman who survived 2{ hours in an icy 3-foot deep
creek after falling down a 25-foot cliff while feeding birds in
10-degree weather was in stable condition today in northeast Ohio.
   Jesse Norton of Chardon was pulled to safety Monday by a rescue
crew called by a visiting nurse who checks on the woman.
   Light snow fell today in the Great Lakes region and moved
eastward into Pennsylvania, a welcome sight for ski slope operators,
who already were using snow-making equipment in the subzero cold.
   ``We're making a ton of snow,'' said William Ulinski,
superintendent of the Mount Sunapee ski area in Newbury, N.H.
   And two members of the Iceberg Athletic Club plunged into the
Atlantic Ocean off New York's Coney Island for a seven-minute dip
Monday afternoon.
   ``Feel great,'' said the 73-year-old president, Vick Boff. ``It
just makes you feel wonderful. It's something that you actually have
to experience in order to appreciate it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Bush-Transition 2ndLd-Writethru a0548 12-13 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Transition, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0548,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Won't Name Members of Congress to Cabinet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Fuller comments in top 6 grafs, picking up in 5th
graf pvs, Bush meanwhile; subs 3rd graf from end, The big, removing
Tower first name; King meeting at 1 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush won't name any members of
Congress to his Cabinet because he doesn't want to weaken his party
in the House or Senate, both already controlled by the Democrats,
Bush aides said today.
   ``We decided it wasn't fair to deplete our strength in
Congress,'' said Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller.
   Transition spokeswoman Alixe Glen added, ``Many of the vice
president's friends in Congress have indicated a willingness to
serve in his administration. Their appointment would mean a loss of
strong supporters on Capitol Hill.''
   Bush began telephoning and sending notes late Monday to members
of Congress who had been under consideration for various posts,
aides to Bush and several congressmen said.
   Fuller said he expected ``a couple'' of appointments to the new
administration later this week, but he wouldn't specify which
offices would be filled.
   He indicated that background checks are continuing on former Sen.
John Tower of Texas, the leading candidate for defense secretary,
and said the timing of an announcement on Bush's Pentagon chief was
``completely up in the air.''
   Bush, meanwhile, was meeting today with Coretta Scott King, the
widow of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
   The private meeting is one of a series Bush has had with
prominent black leaders, including former Democratic presidential
candidate Jesse Jackson and Benjamin Hooks of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   Bush has yet to appoint a black to a high-level job in his
administration, although he has promised his Cabinet will reflect
the makeup of the American public.
   Bush also was scheduled today to talk with Carlos Andres Perez,
the president-elect of Venezuela. Perez is the sixth foreign leader
_ the third from Latin America _ that Bush has entertained since the
election Nov. 8.
   On Monday, Bush's transition aides interviewed Peter Johnson, a
former head of the Bonneville Power Administration in Portland,
Ore., about the job of energy secretary.
   ``I feel good about it,'' Johnson said of the meeting. But he
said Craig Fuller, the co-director of the transition, and Chase
Untermeyer, the head of personnel, gave him no indication whether he
was a finalist for the job.
   Among others mentioned for the Department of Energy post, former
Rep. Henson Moore of Louisiana, is thought to be a leading contender.
   Another name surfaced Monday for the administrator of the
Environmental Protection Agency: Elizabeth Dole.
   Mrs. Dole, the former transportation secretary and the wife of
Senate Minority leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., was known to have been
interested in the post of ambassador to the United Nations. Bush
picked Thomas Pickering, a career diplomat, for that job, but said
he would like to find something suitable for Mrs. Dole.
   So far, Bush has placed only one woman, Carla Hills, in a high
position. She was nominated to be the U.S. trade representative.
   Another woman, Constance Horner, the head of the Office of
Personnel Management, is considered a strong candidate for labor
secretary. John N. Sturdivant, president of the American Federation
of Government Employees, says it will not try to block Horner's
appointment if she is willing to speak openly with the unions.
   Another woman candidate for the labor job, Rep. Lynn Martin,
R-Ill., appears to be out of the running because of Bush's decision
on not naming members of Congress.
   The big hole in Bush's national security lineup is the defense
secretary. Tower of Texas is still said by sources to be the
favorite for the job, although the FBI has yet to finish checks into
his background.
   Sources close to Tower say the FBI could complete its work this
week, but any announcement might be delayed if Bush decides to name
a full slate at the Defense Department, rather than just the
secretary.
   But the sources also said that transition staff members have told
Tower he will have much to say in choosing his own aides, if he is
awarded the defense secretary's slot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1112EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-D.C.-NewYear's     12-13 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-D.C.-New Year's,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barry Cancels City's New Year's Eve Celebration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry has canceled the city's
annual downtown New Year's Eve celebration, citing a drug and crime
epidemic and budget problems.
   ``I think we're in serious times now, with the crime being what
it is and the drug epidemic. It's no time to celebrate, it's a time
to work hard and to pray,'' he said in a radio interview Monday
night.
   Barry had boasted in 1986 that the nation's capital celebration
would surpass New York City's celebration in Times Square and become
a major tourist attraction in the revitalized downtown Pennsylvania
Avenue corridor.
   The city began the street celebration in 1983. But the 1986 event
sparked criticism after the strangled, partially clad body of a high
school student was found in a remote stairwell at the Old Post
Office Pavilion.
   That slaying, along with 15 arrests and reports of fighting and
bottle throwing, led Barry to change the entertainment at the bash,
emphasizing family fare.
   In the past two years, the city moved to ensure safety at the
celebration by limiting alcohol sales, adding police protection and
changing the musical program.
   Last January, officials said more than 100,000 people attended
the party, far short of the estimated 1 million people who crowd
Times Square.
   As of today, 347 homicides had been reported in the District of
Columbia so far this year. Police have estimated 60 percent are
drug-related. The previous high was 287 in 1969.
   Barry has said the city faces a $150 million budget deficit. He
is scheduled to tell the City Council on Wednesday how he plans to
solve the problem.
   In the radio interview on WHUR, Barry said ``we want to emphasize
family values and a number of other things. And people ought to stay
home.... Those who are churchgoing people ought to go to watch
services.''
   D.C. Council member John A. Wilson, whose ward includes downtown,
said he areed with Barry.
   ``I think he's also starting to prepare people for the
difficulties we're going to have next year because we're going to
have major financial problems,'' said Wilson, chairman of the
council's finance committee.
   Wilson added, ``He doesn't want to be accused of wasting money
right now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0083 </DOCNO>
