<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1117EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EcclesiaChildren     12-13 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ecclesia Children,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parents' Request to Supervise Own Children Denied by State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of 52 children who state
officials say were systematically beaten at a religious camp must
admit their children were abused before the state will consider
returning them, an official says.
   ``We need to hear from the parents a recognition that the
children have been abused,'' said Bart Wilson, Clackamas branch
manager for the state Children's Services Division. ``Our assessment
is that the parents have not yet recognized that.''
   The division Monday also denied the parents' request to serve as
unpaid state volunteers to be near their sons and daughters until
custody is determined.
   The children were taken into state custody immediately after the
Oct. 14 death of 8-year-old Dayna Lorea Broussard, daughter of
Ecclesia Athletic Association founder Eldridge Broussard Jr.
   Four members of her father's organization are awaiting trial on
manslaughter charges resulting from the girl's death at a rural
house southeast of Portland. Broussard also ran the Watts Christian
Center in Los Angeles.
   The other children said they were forced to watch the Broussard
girl's beating, and some were forced to count the blows. They said
beatings with electrical cords and paddles routinely occurred at the
house.
   One parent, Jewell Benefield of Los Angeles, had said earlier
that the children ``are world-class athletes in training, and they
can do things that normal kids can't do,'' such as thousands of
push-ups daily.
   Benefield's comments echoed similar claims Broussard made about
the children, leading state officials to question the control the
association founder maintains over the parents.
   Wilson said his agency needs the parents to make ``clear
assurances that if the children are returned to their custody that
the abuse would not reoccur.''
   The state Monday also denied a request that Broussard be allowed
to make ministerial visits to the children in state custody. He
claims to have been ordained a minister in the Church of God in
Christ in 1976.
   Broussard, however, will be allowed to continue his visits to his
own four children now in custody, Wilson said. Other parents have
been making hour-long visits each week, he added.
   Eighteen of the children are housed at juvenile facilities and 33
in foster homes, Wilson said. An 18-month-old boy was released to
his parents and grandparents in California for an extended but
temporary visit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1121EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Marcos     12-13 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Say Marcos Will Remain Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos has
weak heart muscles and will remain hospitalized for further tests,
his doctors say.
   The 71-year-old Marcos was admitted Friday to St. Francis Medical
Center suffering from what aides called congestive heart failure. He
was listed in stable condition today.
   Marcos' wife, Imelda, said his spirits were lifted by visits over
the weekend from tobacco heiress Doris Duke, a friend of the couple,
and Ms. Duke's newly adopted daughter, Charlene Gail ``Chandi''
Heffner.
   ``He seems to come alive,'' when Duke visits, said Mrs. Marcos.
``She is a good American Samaritan and has saved my faith in this
country. Doris inspires the president; she is an angel from heaven,
a remarkable woman who places a high value on friendship.''
   Duke, who owns a home here, recently provided $5 million bail for
Mrs. Marcos when the former Philippine first lady was arraigned in
New York on federal racketeering charges.
   Marcos, ousted as Philippine president in February 1986 by
Corazon Aquino, faces the same charges, but he and his lawyers
contend he is too frail to travel to New York for arraignment.
   Marcos has weakened heart muscles and was prone to develop
congestive heart failure, according to a statement released Monday
by Dr. Calvin Wong, a Honolulu cardiologist.
   ``These episodes in the past have been treated in his home as an
outpatient. ... Because of increased stress that he has been under,
doctors felt it prudent for Mr. Marcos to be hospitalized in order
to re-evaluate his cardiac condition and to readjust his
medication,'' Wong's statement said.
   Marcos has responded to treatment and his condition has
stabilized but he would not be released pending neurological tests,
Wong said.
   A St. Francis Medical Center spokeswoman who read the statement
refused to elaborate on it.
   A New York physician who examined Marcos here in October said
then that although Marcos suffered various ailments, he was well
enough to travel to New York. Dr. Francis Weld of Columbia
Presbyterian Hospital also concluded that Marcos faked pain during
the court-ordered examination.
   On Monday, Weld said that although Marcos did not have congestive
heart failure at the time of the examination, he could have
developed it since. He said the ailment can be either acute or
chronic.
   Mrs. Marcos dismissed accusations that her husband was faking
illness.
   ``The president would be the first one in New York if he could
travel,'' she said.
   Mrs. Marcos said she was so worried about her husband's safety
that she tasted his hospital food and medicine to make sure it was
not poisoned.
   ``I admit it; I am kind of scared, paranoid,'' she said. ``Are
these not desperate times?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
