<1ST_LINE>r a PM-USAToday-Miscarriages 2ndLd-Writethru a0557 12-13 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USA Today-Miscarriages, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0557,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Plagued by Miscarriages Finds Newsroom Air Clean</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Prichard throughout</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests have found no dangerous substances in
the air at the headquarters of USA Today, where 14 workers are said
to have suffered miscarriages in the last 15 months, the paper's
editor says.
   Editor Peter S. Prichard said Monday that the preliminary results
were provided by an outside testing firm that tested newsrooms at
USA Today's Arlington headquarters over the last two weeks.
   He said that additional testing will be done.
   USA Today employees said last week that an informal survey found
that 14 women who work on the 14th and 15th floors of the building
had suffered miscarriages since September 1987. The employees were
concerned that major remodeling which began in April contributed to
several of the miscarriages.
   ``We're continuing to look at it,'' Prichard told The Washington
Post. ``We don't know the cause (of the miscarriages) and we're
continuing to try to find out.''
   Prichard told employees of the preliminary test results at a
meeting Monday. He also said other floors at the newspaper, owned by
Gannett Co. Inc., will be tested and that an epidemiologist has been
hired to study the cluster of miscarriages.
   In a memo summarizing the results, Prichard said the
environmental firm found the air ``is cleaner than the air in most
buildings.''
   A memo last week signed by Madelyn P. Jennings, USA Today's
senior vice president for personnel, said the newspaper will also
test the effects of video display terminals used by employees.
</TEXT>
