<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Orbison-Fund     12-13 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Orbison-Fund,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer's Widow Establishes Memorial Fund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Orbison's widow has established a
memorial fund in the singer's name for a private arts school
attended by one of his sons.
   ``Roy said often he did not like funerals, and the other thing is
he did not like turning events into a zoo,'' spokeswoman Sarah
McMullen said Monday. ``But we do not want the fans to feel ignored.
We feel this memorial fund will keep alive the generous, humane
qualities of Roy Orbison.''
   The Crossroads School trains students in kindergarten through
grade 12 in the arts and offers scholarships to minority children.
   Orbison's son, Roy Kelton, attends the school and another son,
Alexander, is due to attend next year, according to Barbara Orbison,
the singer's widow. ``The world knows Roy through the gifts of his
voice and his songwriting, but as a private man he was very much a
family man,'' she said.
   At a memorial service Sunday in Gallatin, Tenn., 75 of Orbison's
friends attended a 30-minute tribute where he was eulogized as a
legendary performer with a worldwide following.
   A private memorial service was scheduled today in Los Angeles.
   Meanwhile, the late singer's 1955 Cadillac convertible, featured
in his ``Class of '55'' music video, will be auctioned in Florida by
a classic car auction company.
   David Rupp, a northern Indiana sponsor of the Miami Beach auction
Dec. 30-Jan. 1, said he bought the baby blue Cadillac a few weeks
before Orbison died.
   Orbison's Caddy could bring bids of more than $100,000, twice the
value of an identical restored model with no celebrity connection,
said Mitchell D. Kruse, president of Kruse International, based in
Auburn, Ind.
   Orbison, whose recording career spanned 30 years, died of a heart
attack Dec. 6 at 52.
   He was best known for his 1960s hits and his three-octave voice
which ranged through such songs as ``Oh, Pretty Woman,'' ``Only the
Lonely'' and ``Crying.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Eds: Roy Orbison Memorial Fund, Crossroads School, 1714 21st St.,
Santa Monica, Calif., 90404.
</TEXT>
