<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru a0572 12-13 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0572,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Kills Settler In West Bank</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 4-7 with army statement, increase in total
fatalities. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``A curfew ...'' DELETES redundant
20th graf pvs ``The year-old revolt...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian grabbed a gun from a Jewish
settler in the West Bank today and killed the settler and another
Israeli before he was shot to death by Israeli soldiers, Israeli
sources said.
   The shootings occurred in the Arab village of Burin near the
settlement of Berakha about the time PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat was
speaking to the U.N. General Assembly in Geneva.
   Arab sources said the Palestinian was a shepherd identified as
Hamdan Najjar, 25. They said he had been grazing his flock of sheep
near the Jewish settlement. The Arab and Israeli sources spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   An army spokesman confirmed the settler was killed on his way
home to Berakha when an Arab man seized his gun and shot him. The
spokesman said an army patrol arrived at the scene of the attack and
fatally shot the Palestinian.
   The spokesman declined to elaborate or say whether there were
other casualties.
   Before today, 322 Palestinians and 11 Israelis had died in the
year-old revolt against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. Thousands of Arabs have been wounded, among them many
children.
   Arab residents said Jewish settlers entered Burin earlier today
and went into several schools, ordering teachers and students to
leave. One high school principal was beaten, residents said.
   
   A curfew was imposed on the village, Arab journalists said.
   Also today, a Jewish settler today shot and wounded a 26-year-old
Arab after his car was stoned in the West Bank town of Tulkarem, and
troops shot and wounded a 10-year-old boy in the Tulkarem refugee
camp, Arab reports said. An army spokeswoman said she was checking
the reports.
   The army increased its forces in the occupied territories today
and clamped a curfew on the Gaza Strip in an effort to prevent
violence during Arafat's speech.
   Soldiers used loudspeakers to warn the Gaza Strip's 650,000
residents to stay indoors and not violate the curfew, an Arab
reporter said.
   ``We are imposing a curfew ... and we will open fire on anyone
who breaks it,'' the troops announced.
   Despite the heavy military patrols, Gaza City residents used
helium-filled balloons to set aloft a giant Palestinian flag and
burned tires in the streets, according to an Arab journalist in the
city.
   Telephone lines to refugee camps in the Gaza Strip were cut off,
Palestinian sources in Gaza said.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, about 100 Palestinian women held
an illegal march to show support for Arafat. They carried banned
Palestinian flags and banners saying ``My homeland is Palestine.''
   ``No to the occupation _ Long live Palestine,'' they chanted.
   In Bethlehem, Arabs stocked up on batteries for tape recorders
and radios so they could listen to Arafat's speech, shopowners said.
   An Arab reporter said the residents feared Israel might cut off
electricity in the territories during the speech, as authorities did
in November when Arafat addressed the Palestine National Council in
Algiers and declared an independent Palestinian state.
   Hundreds of additional police were deployed in Arab east
Jerusalem and the army added extra patrols to the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, anticipating violent demonstrations following Arafat's speech.
   In east Jerusalem, police used tear gas to break up a crowd of
elementary school children who blocked the entrance to their school
with rocks and raised banned Palestinian flags, the national Itim
news agency reported.
   A similar confrontation took place near the walled Old City, Itim
said. The clashes followed several days of increased protests in the
Israeli-annexed sector, which generally has been calm during the
uprising.
   Three Arab schools in the city were ordered closed until Sunday,
affecting over 2,000 students.
   The increased patrols in east Jerusalem were also apparently
linked to a firebombing Monday in which six people, including an
American woman, were injured.
   An assailant hurled a firebomb at an Israeli passenger bus
driving along east Jerusalem's main commercial thoroughfare, causing
it to slam into a wall and a parked car, police said.
   Among the injured was Salwa Kanana, from Wisconsin. Police did
not know her hometown.
</TEXT>
