<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1232EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-DomesticPolicy     12-13 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Domestic Policy,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Persistence of Deficit Laid to `Iron Triangle'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan charged in a speech summing up
his administration's record on domestic policy today that an ``iron
triangle'' of members of Congress, the news media and special
interest groups have helped perpetuate the budget deficit.
   Reagan received a tumultuous reception, with applause punctuated
by cheers and whistles, from his audiences of government officials
and employees in Constitution Hall.
   ``One of my great disappointments as I leave office is that the
federal budget itself is not yet balanced,'' the president said.
   ``It sometimes seems to many Americans that what might be called
a triangle of institutions, parts of Congress, the media and
interest groups is transforming and placing out of focus our
constitutional balance, particularly in the areas of spending, and
placing out of focus our constitutional balance, particularly in the
areas of spending and foreign policy,'' Reagan said.
   Reagan noted that some had used the term ``iron triangle'' to
describe this complex, and said he would borrow the phrase.
   ``Administrations come and go, but the iron triangle remains,''
he said.
   ``The House of Representatives, he said, ``has become a virtually
permament chamber no longer truly responsive to the people.''
   ``With a 98 per cent rate of re-election, there is less turnover
in the House than in the Supreme Soviet.''
   The president said the ``iron triangle'' also derives from the
power of special interest groups to ``focus debate and overwhelming
resources like campaign money and letter-writing campaigns on issues
that don't command broad and intense national attention.''
   With this pressure, he said, liberal members of Congress ``take
up the banner'' in support of continued spending programs.
   ``You would think the media might act as a check on all this,''
he said. ``But too often it doesn't.''
   While expressing respect for the news media, Reagan said that
``too many members of the media approach issues like federal
spending from a superficial perspective.''
   ``Our positions are reported in caricature,'' he said. ``Special
interest charges are reported uncritically, and the public's
understanding suffers.''
   ``Shouldn't we expect better of those who act in the name of the
public's right to know?'' the president asked.
   His audience cheered the question.
</TEXT>
