<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BattleshipTexas     12-13 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Battleship Texas,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historic Battleship Texas Mired In Mud On Way To Restoration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PORTE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mud around the Battleship Texas was
keeping the historic vessel from taking its first voyage since 1948,
a tow up the Houston Ship Channel to a Galveston dry dock for
restoration, officials said today.
   Five tugboats with a combined 16,000 horsepower rocked the Texas
back and forth this morning to try to dislodge it from its 40-year
berth.
   But four hours later, the 27-ton national landmark remained mired
in the impression it left in the mud at the San Jacinto Battleground
State Park, said naval architect Edwin Phillips.
   ``We've moved about 25 or 30 feet but it hasn't been a great big
bite,'' Phillips said. ``But eventually she'll come.''
   The Texas, the only surviving U.S. combat ship to have served in
both world wars, is scheduled to undergo a $5.1 million restoration.
   The 40-mile trip to the Todd Shipyard in Galveston is expected to
take 10-12 hours, said Sue Moss, the Texas Parks and Wildlife
Department project historian for the battleship.
   ``In my judgment we would have very severe long-term problems
with the ship if we didn't repair her now. We have had a history of
leaks in the ship, some in the piping system, but some also in hull
penetration caused by corrosion,'' said Wilson Dolman, director of
parks.
   He said several pumps were placed in the ship in case a leak
erupts during towing.
   The restoration is designed to return the ship to its appearance
during its last commissioned service, in the Pacific Theater during
World War II.
   The Texas is toured by about 200,000 visitors a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
