<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DNATest     12-13 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DNA Test,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DNA Test Sought By Murder Defendant Links Him To Slayings,
Prosecutor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A genetic test sought by a man who
claimed it would prove he was innocent of killing three teen-agers
has instead linked him to the crime, a prosecutor said.
   The tests show ``the odds of it being someone other than (Ronald
Stephen) Trimboli are one in 55 billion,'' Tarrant County Assistant
District Attorney Bob Gill said.
   Trimboli, who has been jailed since December 1985, has been tried
twice in the 1985 slayings. His first trial ended in a mistrial
because of juror misconduct and his second ended in a mistrial when
jurors could not reach a verdict. No date has been set for a third
trial.
   He sought the test, which analyzes DNA, to prove he was innocent
in the stabbing deaths of Danielle Lemieux, 14, her 12-year-old
sister, Renee Lemieux, and John Paul Bradley, 17, a family friend.
   A medical examiner's report indicated Danielle Lemieux had been
raped. Tests were made on a semen stain found on a sheet, Gill said
Monday.
   Defense attorney Mike Maloney would not comment on the report,
saying he would first have to consult with Trimboli and two other
defense lawyers.
   In October, Trimboli told reporters he he had urged his lawyers
to ask for the tests. Trimboli said he agreed to the tests even
after his lawyers warned him that the results are virtually
foolproof.
   ``They said if I was guilty, it would hang me,'' Trimboli said.
``I'm innocent, so I had no fear. The truth can only help me.''
</TEXT>
