<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Troops     12-13 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Troops,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungary Taking Lead in Trimming Defense Spending</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary is taking the Soviet bloc lead
in trimming defense spending, and it could have up to one third of
the 62,000 Soviet troops stationed on its soil withdrawn by 1991, an
official was quoted as saying Tuesday.
   The withdrawals would go ahead under the proposals outlined by
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev at the United Nations last
week. Hungary used the Gorbachev proposal as a cue to slash military
spending by 17 percent next year and pension off aging generals.
   Defense Minister Col.-Gen. Ferenc Karpati on Monday announced
another Soviet bloc move to smooth the path to troop reduction in
Europe, saying in a radio interview that the Warsaw Pact would
publish all data on troop strengths and armaments before new
all-European conventional force reduction talks begin.
   This would remove a major stumbling block that stalled the
15-year-old Mutual and Balanced Force Reduction talks in Vienna.
   The new negotiations involving the 16 NATO and seven Warsaw Pact
nations are to begin in Vienna possibly as early as February.
   The West has insisted that Warsaw Pact troops outnumber those of
NATO and that the Soviet bloc countries have more troops than they
admit officially.
   Gorbachev announced last week that six tank divisions would be
withdrawn from Hungary, Czechoslovakia and East Germany as part of a
unilateral reduction of Soviet forces by half a million men in the
next two years.
   Prior to Gorbachev's proposal, senior Hungarian officials had
said they would like to be involved in the first stage of any troop
withdrawals.
   Newspapers Tuesday quoted Matyas Szueros, foreign policy expert
of the Hungarian Communist Party, as saying that Hungary ``may play
a role of coordinator and be a testing ground in the disarmament of
conventional weapons.''
   Gorbachev's proposal will mean in the next two years, the Soviet
forces stationed in Hungary ``will be cut by a fourth, or possibly
by a third,'' Szueros said.
   This could mean about 16,000 of the 50,000 troops to be withdrawn
from the three countries would be removed from Hungary. The
Communist Party daily Npeszabadsag reported last week there are
62,000 Soviet troops in Hungary.
   ``Hungary accepted to be a testing ground for the international
inspection of the implementation of disarmament measures, and it
considers conceivable even a unilateral disarmament which fits into
the pan-European process,'' he said.
   Defense spending has become a key issue in Hungary where a $17
billion foreign debt and double digit inflation have led to lower
living standards.
   Parliamentary deputies have called for reductions of defense
spending, saying the money should go toward improving the social
network for pensioners, big families and the unemployed.
   According to independent estimates, 1.5 million of Hungary's 10.6
million population lives below the accepted $80 minimum monthly
subsistence income.
   Karpati announced that more than 50 top army officers, including
10 generals, who are over 60, will be retired as of Jan 1.
   Hungary also plans to cut its own defense spending by 17 percent
in real terms next year.
   Newspapers reported Tuesday that parliament's defense committee
heard a proposal by the government that appropriations for military
defense would be cut by nearly $100 million in 1989, a 17 percent
cut in real terms.
   Karpati would not say how large Hungarian forces are, but said
that estimates by the International Institute of Strategic Studies
estimate of 105,000 was ``reasonable.'' He said an estimate of
190,000 was too big.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
