<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Zimbabwe-Doctors,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Doctors Sent to Strike-Hit Hospitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army doctors were deployed to main
hospitals Tuesday, the second day of a strike by interns, health
authorities said.
   Negotiations between the state-employed interns and health
ministry officials in Harare and Bulawayo failed to reach an
agreement on pay demands and working conditions, according to a
hospital spokesman.
   Army doctors were assisting senior medical staff in four main
hospitals, and clinics were asked to send only seriously ill
patients to the hospitals, said the spokesman, who requested
anonymity. There were no reports of deaths caused by the dispute.
   About 20 army doctors were taken by military vehicles to the
Central Hospital complex in Harare late Tuesday, according to the
Zimbabwe Inter-African News Agency.
   On Monday, interns were reporting only for duty at casualty and
maternity facilities. Health authorities have refused to disclose
how many interns are involved in the strike.
   The strikers are demanding better pay and working conditions and
a review of contracts that bind them to state medical institutions
for several years.
