<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cussing Cabbies,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northern City Fining Cabbies Who Curse, Cheat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taxi drivers in a northern Chinese city are in for
a surprise if they cheat or curse at passengers, an official report
said Tuesday.
   Cabbies caught cussing or bilking passengers in the city of
Dalian will be forced to make public apologies in the local media
and pay heavy fines, the Xinhua News Agency said.
   The regulations, which went into effect Nov. 28, have become
popular with customers, the report said.
   In the first 10 months of this year, 200 cases of overcharging
and abuse by taxi drivers were reported in the coastal city, Xinhua
said.
   It cited one incident in which a driver overcharged two Japanese
and one Taiwanese the equivalent of $4.50 and then yelled at them
when they refused to pay.
   The driver later was fined about $143 and charged another $40 to
pay for a public radio apology. The total fine is more than double
the monthly salary of most taxi drivers in China.
</TEXT>
