<HEAD>U.S., Greece Begin New Round of Bases Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek and American negotiators Tuesday
began a new round of talks on U.S. bases aimed at renewing the
agreement before it ends next week.
   Government officials said the latest talks are expected to end
Thursday.
   The negotiations, which began a year ago, broke off in September
when Greece said the Hellenikon base near Athens would have to close
after the five-year accord expires Dec. 21.
   Under the present agreement, the U.S. has 17 months to shut down
the bases if a new accord is not signed.
   Hellenikon Air Force base is one of four U.S.-run bases in
Greece. The other bases are a Navy communications unit near Athens,
a Navy supply base at Souda Bay and an Air Force communications
installation on Crete.
