<DOCNO> AP881213-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1315EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Quake 1stLd-Writethru a0436 12-13 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0436,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material first 9 grafs, picking up 3rd graf pvs, Hammer
has</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two additional Air Force cargo planes have been
ordered to prepare for disaster relief missions to the Soviet Union
and a Soviet plane that brought nuclear arms inspectors to the
United States earlier this week is being loaded with emergency
supplies, the Pentagon said today.
   The relief flights were scheduled as American donations to the
Soviet earthquake relief effort reached $3.2 million. President and
Mrs. Reagan say they'll make a contribution of their own.
   The Air Force said a C-141 cargo plane would leave West Germany
today for Pisa, Italy, where it will pick up relief supplies that
include blankets, gloves, hard hats and water tanks.
   That plane will then fly to the scene of the earthquake, at
Yerevan in Soviet Armenia, on Wednesday afternoon, the Pentagon
added.
   A second C-141 is being loaded today at Andrews Air Force Base,
Md., outside Washington. It will carry plastic sheeting to be used
for temporary shelters and should arrive in Russia sometime on
Thursday, the Pentagon said.
   In addition to those scheduled flights, ``an IL-76 that brought
INF inspectors into Travis Air Force Base, Calif., yesterday, to
observe ground-launched cruise missile destruction ... will be
loaded with medical supplies and equipment for the return trip,''
said Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman.
   ``This represents a waiver of INF Treaty provisions by allowing
the Soviet aircraft to remain here an extra day to carry the cargo
out. The Red Cross in San Francisco is coordinating supplies.''
   The Soviet inspectors entered the United States at San Francisco
under terms of the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty, which
requires the United States and Soviet Union to destroy all
intermediate- and shorter-range nuclear missiles in their
inventories.
   The scheduling of airlift missions came as the State Department
announced the the official U.S. contribution had grown to $825,000,
mostly in transportation costs, while private donations totaled $2.4
million, including a $1 million check hand-delivered in Moscow by
Armand Hammer, chairman of Occidental Petroleum Corp.
   Hammer has been a frequent visitor to the Soviet Union and has
done business there for decades.
   Nancy Reagan, asked during a press preview of the White House
Christmas decorations whether she and the president had sent money,
replied, ``We're going to.'' She did not reveal the amount.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said worldwide
contributions to the relief effort totaled $26.1 million. A
department list showed 14 countries making donations besides the
United States. Nine of those countries have military ties with
Washington.
   Redman suggested that the American response was simply a
reflection of the magnitude of the disaster in Soviet Armenia, where
tens of thousands were believed killed and half a million made
homeless by last week's temblor.
   ``It really is a tragedy of immense proportions,'' Redman said.
The United States was a major contributor of aid to the Soviet Union
during World War II, but that relationship ended with the onset of
the Cold War.
   The Soviets are giving highest priority to donations of medical
supplies, including antibiotics and diagnostic and other clinical
equipment, Redman said. Lower priority is being given to such items
as blankets, tents and food, he said.
   According to the Pentagon, the first two plane loads of U.S.
government aid _ weighing more than 50 tons _ arrived in Yerevan,
the Armenian capital, on Sunday. On board were rations, water,
winter clothing and surgical supplies.
   Redman said a commercially chartered aircraft also arrived in
Yerevan on Sunday, consisting of, among other things, dogs and dog
handlers to help search for earthquake victims. Also aboard were
U.S. relief experts and representatives of several Armenian groups.
   The Pentagon said Air National Guard and Air Force Reserve
training flights may be pressed into service because they can be
used to carry private aid without the State Department having to
reimburse the Defense Department for the costs, as is true for State
Department-ordered flights carrying government aid.
</TEXT>
