<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Sweden-Whale     12-13 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Sweden-Whale,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sperm Whale Apparent Victim of Distemper Epidemic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sperm whale washed ashore after dying,
apparently from the virus that has killed thousands of seals, news
reports said Tuesday.
   The 15-ton mammal, found beached near the port of Varberg about
340 miles southwest of Stockholm, was the 11th whale found dead in
the North Sea in less than a month, the Svenska Dagbladet daily said.
   Erling Haack of Stockholm's Museum of Natural History said
biologists were examining the 45-foot whale to establish if it died
of distemper, a virus that causes infections of the respiratory and
nervous systems and the digestive tract.
   A distemper epidemic killed more than 10,000 seals in northern
waters during the summer.
   The museum will keep the skeleton and fins of the whale, as well
as the ivory teeth, each worth about $660, Haack said.
</TEXT>
