<DOCNO> AP881213-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1332EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-20thCenturyArt     12-13 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-20th Century Art,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French, US Works Dominate Overhaul at National Gallery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paintings done in France before World War II
and American works done after it dominate a major overhaul of 20th
century art at the National Gallery that opened Tuesday and will
stay a major feature of the museum for the next two years.
   The upper level of the gallery's East Building, which is
celebrating its 10th anniversary, starts with a room of paintings by
Pablo Picasso. His huge ``Family of Saltimbanques (Tumblers)'' _
nearly eight feet high _ is the first feature the visitor sees.
   Jack Cowart, curator of 20th century art, said an effort may be
made to use computer enhancement to get at a picture that Picasso
painted first on that canvas and then covered with the current one.
The picture underneath can be seen by X-rays, but present techniques
would not enable the color to be reproduced, he added.
   The upper level of the building is devoted almost entirely to
canvasses painted in France, by Henri Matisse, Andre Derain, Amedeo
Modigliani, Georges Braque, Fernand Leger and others.
   ``The Human Condition,'' by the Belgian artist Rene Magritte, was
acquired by the gallery last year and is being shown for the first
time.
   So are two ``Rock Settees,'' seats made of polished pink and
green granite by American sculptor Scott Burton. They come from
boulders unearthed in Cold Spring, Minn.
   Gallery Director J. Carter Brown also announced the gift to the
gallery of five paintings by the American artist Barnett Newman, who
died in 1970. Just below the street, the gallery's Concourse Level
has a room showing Newman's ``Stations of the Cross.''
   Other separate rooms on this level will be devoted to the
paintings of American artists Mark Rothko, Richard Diebenkorn,
Ellsworth Kelly, Jasper Johns and Robert Rauschenberg. Works by Roy
Lichtenstein and Andy Warhol share a room.
   Museum officials said the installation does not try to cover the
whole field of 20th century art.
   ``We're not here to touch every base,'' Brown said.
   He noted that the gallery's older West Building shows a
collection of earlier American paintings, much of it from before
World War II. Nan Rosenthal, also a curator of 20th century art,
pointed out that other museums in Washington specialize in work from
Africa and the Orient.
   The present installation will be kept until the end of 1990, when
the National Gallery begins to celebrate its 50th anniversary. Brown
said changes can be expected then.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
