<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Steinberg 2ndLd-Writethru a0587 12-13 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steinberg, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0587,0851</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steinberg's Behavior Became More Erratic With Cocaine Use</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `The testimony ...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with conclusion of cross-examination.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joel Steinberg's ex-lover testified today at his
murder trial that she lied to police about bruises on their
illegally adopted daughter because she wanted to protect him even
though she believed he had inflicted the bruises.
   Hedda Nussbaum said she told detectives who interviewed her the
morning that 6-year-old Lisa Steinberg was carried unconscious from
their apartment that the child had been hit in the head by a
playmate a few days earlier. She said she also told them that Lisa
``fell a lot while roller-skating.''
   Ms. Nussbaum, 46, admitted under cross-examination by Steinberg's
lawyer, Ira London, that the statements were either wholly or partly
lies.
   ``I was trying to create a cover story at the time for what Joel
had done,'' Ms. Nussbaum testified.
   London reminded Ms. Nussbaum that she had repeatedly said that
she had not seen Steinberg hit Lisa before the girl lost
consciousness.
   ``The bruises on the body, I assumed Joel had done,'' she replied.
   Ms. Nussbaum had told police that a bruise on the girl's forehead
was the result of a slap from a classmate. She testified that while
Lisa had been slapped by a friend, she had not seen any bruise until
later, when Lisa was taken to the hospital the morning of Nov. 2,
1987. She died three days later of head injuries.
   London concluded his five-day cross-examination of Ms. Nussbaum
with two questions that go to the heart of the defense: ``Isn't it
true that you have placed a sanitary cordon around the events to
protect yourself from a painful memory?'' and ``Isn't it a fact that
you hare willfully forgotten things and events to falsify your own
reality?''
   To both questions, Ms. Nussbaum replied, ``No.''
   Steinberg's lawyers appeared to be trying to bolster their claim
that he was not criminally responsible for Lisa's death.
   London has asked court permission to file an insanity defense,
but Judge Harold Rothwax refused. The lawyer has tried to show that
Steinberg actually believed some of the things he told Ms. Nussbaum.
   London said a psychiatrist who examined Steinberg twice has
prepared an affidavit saying the defendant has a ``delusional
disorder _ paranoid type'' and is willing to testify to that in the
state criminal court trial.
   Steinberg, a disbarred lawyer, is charged with fatally beating
his illegally adopted daughter, Lisa. Prosecutors also allege he
beat Ms. Nussbaum.
   Interest in the case has become so widespread that much of Ms.
Nussbaum's testimony has been carried live on local television. CNN
carried some of today's and Monday's testimony nationally.
   Ms. Nussbaum's lawyers Monday released copies of hundreds of
support letters they say she has received since taking the stand.
   ``I can't tell you how much my heart has ached for you. ... There
are so many women across America who are cheering you on,'' wrote
one woman from Pennsylvania.
   Another writer called her ``an inspiration to all battered women
and children across the nation.''
   Ms. Nussbaum, who lived with Steinberg for 12 years, testified
Monday that Steinberg's behavior became more erratic and bizarre as
his use of cocaine increased in the two months before Lisa's death.
   ``Joel was verbalizing a lot of peculiar ideas, unusual things,
telling me stories that seem pretty improbable today,'' Ms. Nussbaum
said.
   ``Things that made no sense?'' asked London.
   ``Yes,'' replied Ms. Nussbaum.
   She said Steinberg told her ``a number of people were staring at
him and trying to hypnotize him. He also told me he thought people
had been trying to hypnotize him for years, even back when he was in
the Air Force.''
   She said Steinberg told her she was not her parents' natural
child and that ``my father had made a deal with someone in Europe''
to get her as a baby.
   Ms. Nussbaum also said Steinberg called the Manhattan district
attorney's office anonymously in 1984 to complain ``that I was
involved with a cult.''
   She said the cult supposedly hypnotized people and used them
sexually, and Steinberg thought she was in the group's thrall.
   ``Did you believe you were being manipulated by a cult?'' London
asked.
   ``I believed it,'' she said, adding she now believes Steinberg
used these stories to control her.
   Ms. Nussbaum said Steinberg's unusual behavior was exacerbated by
cocaine and that she and Steinberg often used the drug around the
time Lisa died.
   Previously, she testified that she and Steinberg used cocaine the
night of Nov. 1, 1987, rather than help Lisa, who was lying
unconscious on their bathroom floor. Lisa was removed from
Steinberg's apartment early the next day by authorities.
   Steinberg denies that he hit the girl.
   The couple raised Lisa from birth after acquiring her from an
unwed Long Island teen-ager. They never formally adopted her.
</TEXT>
