<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JailedJuror     12-13 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jailed Juror,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Jailed For Failing To Answer Summons And Refusing To Serve</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman was taken to jail in handcuffs
after clashing with a federal judge over whether she could be forced
to be a juror.
   Judy Ann Jones, 39, of Brandon was taken into custody Monday at
her pharmacy after she failed to answer a summons. U.S. District
Judge Tom S. Lee ordered her jailed a short time later for contempt
of court on grounds she had removed her name from voting rolls in
order to avoid jury duty.
   Jones was led in handcuffs to Jackson City Jail and released
after paying a $200 fine. She refused Tuesday to talk about the
incident.
   Lee's office called Jones on Monday when she did not respond to
the jury summons, records show, and the woman informed court
officials that she was not qualified because she had taken her name
off voting rolls earlier that morning.
   Jones said she then asked to speak with the judge.
   When that request was refused because Lee was in court, Jones was
quoted as replying, ``Yes, it's funny just how important some people
think they are. I had no intentions of sitting on a jury. I am no
longer a registered voter in Mississippi and I don't ever intend to
be.''
   When Lee heard of the conversation, he ordered her arrest.
   In court, she told him it was essential for her to be at her
pharmacy.
   The judge told Jones it was not her decision whether to respond
to a jury summons. ``Do you understand that?'' he asked.
   ``I understand there's a federal mandate I have to serve if I'm a
registered voter and you send out a letter so specifying,'' she
said. ``However, I'm no longer a registered voter and I do not
qualify.''
   ``Let me put your mind at ease about that,'' the judge shot back.
``That's not an excuse, after you've had a summons, to between
Friday and this morning, remove your name from the voting roll.''
</TEXT>
