<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Transition-Connections     12-13 0853</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transition-Connections,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Transition Officials Have Marshall Islands Connection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's no surprise to see Texas connections as
George Bush, an adopted son of the Lone Star State, puts together
his administration. But a Marshall Islands connection?
   Over at Bush transition headquarters, the Texans have competition
from a network with connections to the sun-drenched, dirt-poor
Marshall Islands, two atoll chains in the Pacific with a total land
mass of 70 square miles and a population of 35,000, the place where
the United States tested nuclear weapons for years.
   In a town where who you know is often as important as what you
know, the Marshalls seem to have friends in high places.
   Wilfred I. Kendall, the little republic's diplomatic
representative, says, ``It's good to know someone higher up. It's
important.'
   The Marshalls network give an example of how connections and
contacts are often the grease that make the city run. Ties are
formed when people in federal agencies, Congress and private busines
are thrown together to work on a single issues.
   Several officials at the Bush transition office are very familiar
with the islands' recent history: They worked on negotiations that
led to independence for the U.S. trust territory in October 1986.
   A key contact for Kendall is Fred M. Zeder, who was chief U.S.
negotiator of the compact with the Marshalls. Zeder and his wife,
Martha, are among the president-elect's best friends. In April,
Zeder accompanied Bush, his friend Nicholas Brady, the secretary of
the treasury; and Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo. on a weekend holiday in
Florida.
   Like Bush, Zeder is a wealthy businessman who moved from
Connecticut to Texas. He has also lived in Hawaii and the nation's
capital. In recent years, the Zeders have given substantial sums to
support Bush politically. In 1987, federal records show, they each
gave the maximum permitted, $5,000 to Bush's political action
committee. Additionally, Zeder gave $11,000 this year to the
Republican National Committee.
   Zeder and James Baker III, the Texan designated to be the
secretary of state, are the highest-paid people at transition, with
salaries at an annual rate of about $71,000.
   Alixe Glen, a spokeswoman for the transition, said Zeder is
``mostly working on appointments and personnel,'' especially those
for the Interior Department, where he once worked.
   Zeder's son, Howard, is the Marshalls' maritime commissioner and
part-owner of a company that operates the republic's new
ship-flagging registry. The registry was partly financed with U.S.
development aid.
   Such an operation _ under which ships fly the flag of the
countries in which they are registered even though the vessels may
be owned by citizens of other countries _ can be remunerative. For
example, Liberia's registry, the world's largest, brings in between
$30 million and $40 million a year.
   Another friend of the Marshalls is Peter S. Watson, a New
Zealand-born attorney who represents the republic in his private law
practice. Watson, who became an American citizen less than a year
ago, is lending a hand on ethics and legal issues at the transition.
   Howard Hills, a lawyer at the State Department handling Marshalls
business, is dealing with logistics while on leave at the
transition. Hills, who worked with Zeder when the Reagan
administration was pushing the compact with the Marshalls, recently
spoke at a reception in New York tossed by the ship registry.
   Manase Mansur, a staffer at the House Interior and Insular
Affairs Committee, the panel that supervised legislation on the
Marshalls atoll chain, also has a position in the transition's
administrative office.
   Glen said the men perform different functions at the office, but
don't work on issues affecting the Marshalls. All except Mansur are
listed as paid employees of the transition.
   Zeder was the subject of criticism after the compact with the
Marshalls was ratified.
   What has irked some is an arrangement in which Zeder's son became
the Marshalls' maritime commissioner as well as having a financial
stake in the ship registry. In October, Majestic Shipping Corp.
became the first company to fly the Marshalls' flags.
   The arrangement would have been barred if former Rep. John
Seiberling, D-Ohio, an ex-member of the interior committee, had had
his way.
   Seiberling sought unsuccessfully to insert language in the
compact that would have ensured ``nobody who worked on negotiations
could receive or be part of any contract under which they would
receive funds from the freely associated states.'' The ban also
would have applied to family members of people involved.
   ``We wanted to make clear that nobody was going to profit from
any deals that were made,'' he said in a telephone interview.
Seiberling retired from the House in 1986.
   Neither Howard Zeder nor Watson, who has served as a spokesman
for the Marshalls and for the registry, will reveal the financial
details of the private company that operates the ship registry.
Watson is associated with the law firm of Coudert Bros.
   Howard Zeder sees the registry as a key element of a plan to
develop the impoverished Marshalls. ``This is one of the few
ventures that has real development potential for the islands,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1353EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mandela     12-13 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mandela,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mandela in `Total Isolation' at Prison Farm, Attorney Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nelson Mandela is in ``total
isolation'' at his new prison farm house, his attorney said Tuesday
after the African National Congress leader met with his wife, Winnie.
   Mrs. Mandela, her daughter, Zinzi, and three grandchildren made
their first visit to the Victor Verster Prison outside Cape Town,
where Mandela was moved to a prison staff house last week.
   The family is allowed unlimited access to Mandela, but Mrs.
Mandela visited for only 80 minutes, saying they won't accept
special privileges from the government until all political prisoners
receive the same treatment.
   Attorney Ismail Ayob, speaking on behalf of Mrs. Mandela, told a
news conference afterward: ``This is not freedom. The move is in
fact a retrogressive step. Mr. Mandela now has no contact at all
with any of his (jailed ANC) colleagues.''
   Mrs. Mandela attended the news conference with Ayob, but did not
speak.
   The Mandela family ``felt saddened and particularly hurt today
when they saw what has happened to Mr. Mandela,'' Ayob said. ``He is
in a house ... surrounded by a great many prison officials. It is a
cruel situation that he is in total isolation.''
   Ayob accompanied Mrs. Mandela to the prison gate, but wasn't
allowed to see Mandela because authorities had not responded to his
request for a visit.
   Mandela's house, complete with a swimming pool, in on a remote
part of the prison complex, closer to a private game reserve full of
zebra and giraffe than the main prison building.
   Some whites have written letters to South African newspapers
expressing outrage that a prisoner is being kept in such
``luxurious'' conditions.
   However, Ayob noted that Mandela had no say over his move. ``I
don't even think he can swim,'' said Ayob.
   Mandela, the country's best known black leader, has been
imprisoned since 1962 and is serving a life sentence for sabotage
and plotting to overthrow the government.
   Mandela, 70, contracted tuberculosis in August, but has recovered
following three months in a hospital. The government's decision not
to send him back to prison appears part of phased release designed
to calm the public clamor over his possible freedom.
   By placing Mandela in a special house, however, the government
has underscored Mandela's special stature.
   The government has expressed concern that if Mandela was released
unexpectedly, the move could re-ignite widespread black protest that
has largely been silenced under a 30-month state of emergency. The
government also is worried that freeing Mandela could unleash a
violent backlash by right-wing whites.
   In a related development Tuesday, recently released activist
Zwelakhe Sisulu visited Pollsmoor Prison in Cape Town to see his
father, Walter Sisulu, a leading ANC figure and close colleague of
Mandela.
   Zwelakhe Sisulu, editor of the New Nation newspaper, was released
from detention Dec. 2 after being held for two years without charge.
Walter Sisulu was convicted with Mandela at the same trial in 1964
and is serving a life sentence.
   Zwelakhe Sisulu is under severe restrictions that bar him from
working as a journalist, participating in politics, or talking to
the media.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CBSSchedule     12-13 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBS Schedule,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Schedule Shakeup Cancels GTG Shows, Mary Tyler Moore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two new situation comedies starring Mary Tyler
Moore and Dick Van Dyke, respectively, are gone from CBS' schedule,
the network announced Tuesday in a schedule shakeup that dumps two
of the three CBS shows produced by Grant Tinker's GTG Entertainment.
   The network, which has ranked last in the ratings so far this
season, said ``Annie McGuire,'' starring Miss Moore, would have its
last broadcast in its Wednesday time period on Dec. 28, suggesting
it might be brought back in the future. But the network said ``The
Van Dyke Show'' and ``Raising Miranda,'' the GTG shows, would have
their final broadcasts this month.
   ``Dirty Dancing,'' a half-hour show based on the hit movie of the
same name will go ``on hiatus'' in January. ``Simon & Simon,'' the
long-running, on-again, off-again detective series, has its last
broadcast in its Saturday time period on Dec. 31. CBS left the door
open to reviving it yet again.
   GTG Entertainment was established by former NBC chairman and MTM
Productions head Grant Tinker in partnership with Gannett. Tinker
founded MTM Productions with his then-wife, Mary Tyler Moore.
   The third GTG show for CBS, the critically praised ``TV101,'' an
hourlong, teen-appeal drama, is being moved next month from its
low-rated Tuesday time slot to Wednesday in place of the Moore and
Van Dyke shows.
   GTG has also not fared well with its only other current TV
enterprise, the syndicated newsmagazine show ``USA Today: The
Television Show,'' though the company insists it is sticking by that
show for the long haul.
   In the most recent ratings from the A.C. Nielsen Co., ``Annie
McGuire'' and ``The Van Dyke Show'' were the lowest-rated network
shows of the week.
   ``Raising Miranda'' was the third lowest-rated show last week.
   Both ``Annie McGuire'' and ``The Van Dyke Show'' had problems
from the start. Both pilots were re-shot and the Moore show was
partially recast. They then emerged to almost universally negative
reviews, even though their stars are two of the most popular sitcom
performers ever.
   Moore and Van Dyke co-starred in ``The Dick Van Dyke Show'' in
the 1960s, and Moore starred as Mary Richards in ``The Mary Tyler
Moore Show'' in the 1970s.
   CBS announced that ``Tour of Duty,'' a Vietnam series, will
return to the schedule Tuesday at 8 p.m. EST. ``Dolphin Cove,''
starring Frank Converse as a dolphin researcher in Australia, will
join the schedule in January in place of ``Dirty Dancing'' and
``Raising Miranda'' on Saturday night.
   The Smothers Brothers will also return to the schedule for four
shows in January and February.
</TEXT>
