<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HousingProjectDeath 2ndLd-Writethru a0576 12-13 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Housing Project Death, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0576,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paramedics Leave Housing Project, Boy Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 6th graf, `He said ...,' with residents
disputing Fire Department's version.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramedics called to treat an asthmatic 9-year-old
boy left a city housing project when their ambulance was pelted by
eggs and returned with police too late to save the boy, authorities
said today.
   Paramedics were unable to revive Carl Jarnagin, who died a short
time later at a hospital, said Bill Crowley, a Chicago Fire
Department spokesman.
   The two paramedics, first summoned by an emergency call at 4:16
p.m. Monday, were not aware of the seriousness of the boy's health
problem when they arrived at the Chicago Housing Authority building
on the city's South Side, Crowley said.
   Crowley was uncertain when the ambulance first arrived at the
Dearborn Homes project, but said it left at 4:28 p.m.
   ``There were different objects hitting the vehicle, and there was
egg on the windshield. Projectiles, maybe stones, were hitting the
vehicle,'' Crowley said. ``For that reason, it was decided to
leave.''
   He said he did not know where the objects were coming from, or
who was throwing them.
   Some building residents disputed the story, saying the paramedics
initially refused to enter the building though nothing was being
thrown at them.
   Sandra Falls, 26, a secretary for the CHA's Local Advisory
Council at the Dearborn Homes, said residents told her nothing was
thrown at the vehicle, but instead ambulance workers refused to
enter the building for 15 to 20 minutes, even with police there.
   ``There was no one throwing rocks out the window,'' added Randy
Taylor, a building resident. ``There was just, I think, fear of the
black community.''
   Crowley did not immediately know the races of the paramedics.
Building residents are overwhelmingly black.
   Police received a call for help from the Fire Department at 4:21
p.m., said Officer Charles Marschke. Police entered the fifth-floor
apartment, found the boy ``unresponsive'' on the floor in a bedroom,
tried to revive him and put out a call for the paramedics to return.
The police report did not mention whether the ambulance had been
attacked, he said.
   According to Crowley, police arrived at the apartment project at
4:34 p.m., and the ambulance returned at 4:40 p.m. Paramedics worked
to revive the boy for 30 minutes before taking him to Mercy
Hospital, where he died, Crowley said.
   The Fire Department will investigate the incident, he said.
``We'll pull our radio tapes and speak to people and try to get a
blow-by-blow of what happened.''
   Paramedics often are accompanied to CHA buildings by police or a
fire unit, making the trip into some high-crime areas safer, Crowley
said.
   ``Going into the projects alone is a problem,'' he said. With
only two unassisted paramedics at a scene where they are likely to
encounter hostility, he added, ``the possibility certainly exists of
them getting injured.''
   ``It was so frustrating for them that this child passed away,''
Crowley said. ``So many times you go to the scene and it's something
very minor.''
</TEXT>
