<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     12-13 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Fighting Reported Between Rival Shiite Militias</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting between rival Shiite Moslem
militias resumed Tuesday in the slums of south Beirut after a
two-week lull, police said.
   A police spokesman said there was no way to confirm whether the
captors of a U.S. Marine colonel had fulfilled their threat to kill
him, and that police had no suspects in the shooting death of a
65-year-old Belgian.
   The Japanese widow of Arthur van Nieuwerburgh, 65, a teacher who
carried Belgian and British passports, returned to Beirut on
Tuesday, the day after her husband was killed near their Beirut
restaurant.
   ``My husband is dead. I don't know what to do,'' Suyun Tsuchida
told reporters after arriving from Ankara, Turkey, where she has
considered opening a Japanese restaurant. She said she did not know
why he was slain.
   Police said one combatant was killed and three civilians were
wounded in fighting between the mainstream Shiite militia Amal,
which is pro-Syrian, and the Iranian-backed fundamentalist Hezbollah
(Party of God).
   The militias, which are vying for dominance among Lebanon's 1
million Shiites, battled with automatic rifles and rocket-propelled
grenades in the Chiyah and Hay Madi slums of south Beirut, police
reported. They said the shooting started soon after daybreak and
lasted about two hours.
   Syrian troops in charge of security in Beirut's Moslem sector
moved in to stop the fighting, the first between the factions since
Nov. 22.
   Many of the 15 Western hostages missing in Lebanon are believed
held in Hay Madi, the main south Beirut stronghold of Hezbollah,
which is thought to be an umbrella organization for Shiite
kidnappers.
   Nine of the captives are Americans. Held longest is Terry A.
Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press,
who was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   The police spokesman, whose name cannot be used under standing
regulations, said there was ``no way ... to ascertain whether the
hostages have been affected by the fighting'' or the threat against
Higgins was carried out.
   Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, commander of a U.N. observer group,
was abducted by a group calling itself the Organization of the
Oppressed on Earth. The U.S. Marine officer, 43, was seized Feb. 17
near the southern port of Tyre.
   A statement signed with the organizaion's name, released Monday,
said: ``We have issued the irrevocable sentence to execute this
American spy. The spy has been turned over to those responsible for
executing this just and revolutionary verdict.''
   No date for carrying out the ``sentence'' was given in the
15-line statement, written in Arabic and delivered to the
independent Beirut newspaper An-Nahar.
</TEXT>
