<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Pentagon-Consultants     12-13 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pentagon-Consultants,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Expanding Probe That Finds Questionable Consulting Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pentagon auditors will expand a review of top
military contractors that already has found U.S. taxpayers are being
billed for millions of dollars in questionable consulting fees,
officials said Tuesday.
   The first investigation covered a dozen contractors, but the new
review will look at 18 more over the next 10 weeks, said William
Reed, director of the Defense Contract Audit Agency.
   The review was ordered by Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci in
the wake of the Justice Department's ongoing investigation of
possible fraud and bribery involving defense contractors.
   That investigation, code-named ``Ill Wind,'' has not yet produced
any indictments. It centers on the use of consultants employed by
defense firms to win Pentagon contracts worth billions of dollars.
   Reed said the review of the dozen firms found that contractors
``were spending considerable sums supplementing virtually every
in-house activity with professional and consultant services.''
   The Pentagon was billed by the dozen firms for $237 million worth
of consultanting fees over the past year, Reed said. Of that total,
investigators found that $57.6 million was questionable and the
contractors are being asked to provide more support for the claims.
   ``Most of these questionable expenditures represent claimed costs
where the contractor could not produce evidence of services
rendered, or, to a lesser degree could not produce written
agreements as to the value of, and type, service being purchased,''
Reed said.
   Normally, contractors pay consultants from their own funds and
then bill the Pentagon for reimbursement.
   Reed did not name the dozen companies and said he was withholding
the information because the cases were still under discussion about
allowable costs.
   Reed made his statements before the Senate Government Affairs
federal service subcommittee, which is chaired by Sen. David Pryor,
D-Ark.
   Pryor said consultants do legitimate jobs, but he added that
``the Ill Wind probe suggests that consultants may also be involved
in criminal activities, involving bribery, fraud, collusive bidding
and trafficking in confidential material.''
   One of the biggest problems, Pryor admitted, is coming up with a
definition of a consultant.
   Reed agreed. ``At the onset of our review, we encountered
significant difficulty in isolating `consultant' services and costs
due to the lack of a universally accepted definition of the term.''
   Pryor criticized the administration's policy of having
contractors police themselves. Administration officials have
testified to Congress that defense firms are being asked to do a
better, more thorough job of making sure all their expenses are
justified.
   The Pentagon audit ``suggests that the much ballyhooed theory of
this administration that defense contractors will police themselves
without strict controls is a pipe dream,'' Pryor said.
   Reed said his agency was urging some changes in federal
regulations governing allowable costs.
   In the wake of the public announcement about the Ill Wind
investigation, Carlucci wrote to the top 200 defense contractors,
urging them to tighten their controls on consultants.
   Since the Pentagon's audit of the dozen companies, Carlucci has
written again to the companies to urge them to act, said Eleanor
Spector, deputy assistant secretary of defense for procurement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
