<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Arafat, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0604,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Rejects Arafat's Peace Initiatives</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Arafat, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 11-20, beginning ``In Washington...'' to update with
Washington reaction, edit to conform and tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, saying the PLO
had not changed its terrorist ways, today rejected Yasser Arafat's
peace initiatives and called on the United States to withhold
recognition of the PLO.
   ``We know what hides behind his (Arafat's) words,'' Shamir told a
news conference after Arafat addressed the U.N. General Assemby in
Geneva. ``We know that as they are spoken acts of terror continue.''
   Shortly before he spoke, Israeli officials announced that a
Palestinian in the West Bank had shot to death two Israelis after
seizing a gun from a Jewish settler. The Palestinian also was killed.
   Referring to the incident, Shamir said ``what happened is another
illustration of a decision by the hostile circles in the PLO to
continue their violence.''
   Calling on Washington to withhold recognition of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, Shamir said that in his speech Arafat spoke
favorably of a ``war of liberation'' and stopped short of
recognizing Israel.
   ``I hope that as long as these conditions are not met the United
States will not recognize the PLO,'' Shamir said.
   He said he was ready for peace talks with Arab states and
Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip but not the
PLO.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, Shamir's political rival in the
coalition government, had no immediate comment on Arafat's speech.
   However, the liberal Citizens Rights movement, which was aligned
with the Labor Party in the recent parliament elections, called on
both the U.S. and Israeli governments to start talks with the PLO.
   ``The Israeli government must now put the PLO to the test and
propose peace negotaitions,'' it said. ``As long as the government
refuses to recognize the significant changes in the PLO position,
then the American administration should recognize the changes, meet
Arafat and advance the cause of peace in our region.''
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
Arafat did not meet conditions for opening a dialogue with the
United States because he did not clearly state PLO recognition of
Israel.
   Israeli radios had reported earlier today that the U.S.
government was expected to announce after Arafat's speech that it
accepted the PLO as a partner in Middle East peace talks.
   However, the radio reports said the U.S. decision was contingent
on Arafat meeting U.S. conditions in his U.N. speech in Geneva.
   To U.S. officials, the three key conditions for opening a
dialogue with the PLO are acceptance of 1967 and 1973 U.N. Security
Council resolutions asserting the right of all Middle Eastern states
to live within secure borders, explicit PLO recognition of Israel
and renunciation of terrorism.
   U.S. officials reportedly proposed some alterations in language
after requesting and receiving the speech in advance. Israel radio
said the United States was told the changes had been accepted.
   Today, several dozen Palestinians, drinking steaming cups of
sweet tea and coffee, listened to Arafat's speech broadcast on the
French-run Monte Carlo radio at the Hakawati theater in east
Jerusalem.
   Palestinian journalist Daoud Kuttab said Arafat had challenged
Israel to join a peace process. ``There are now no more excuses for
Israel not to give a positive response to this message of peace,''
   He said explicit recognition was not possible because it meant
recognizing Israel with specific borders, which should be determined
in negotiations.
   ``Spelling out such specific boundaries could be detrimental to
negotiations. Arafat is leaving the boundaries open to
negotiations,'' said Kuttab.
</TEXT>
