<HEAD>6-Ton Bronze Commemorating 40th Anniversary of Marshall Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco De Mita
presented a six-ton bronze ``thank you'' to the city _ a sculpture
commemorating the 40th anniversary of the Marshall Plan
rehabilitation of Europe.
   During dedication ceremonies Monday, De Mita said the work by
modern Italian master Arnaldo Pomodoro was ``a token of my country's
eternal gratitude.'' Italy got $1.5 billion under the massive aid
plan.
   The bronze titled ``Colpo d'Ala,'' a cube that has broken apart
with a stylized bird poised for flight, is in the center of a
reflection pool at the Department of Water and Power building
downtown.
   ``From here it is almost ready to take flight to a faraway land,
bringing a message of peace, progress and hope from our two
countries,'' the prime minister said.
