<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Trains 2ndLd-Writethru a0547 12-13 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Trains, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0547,0839</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Signal Mix-Up Cited As Possible Cause of Rail Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBs first graf and INSERTS new 7th graf ``The condition...''
to update with Scotland Yard revising death toll to 33. Picks up 7th
graf pvs ``Rescuers aided by...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers said today they believe all bodies
have been recovered from the wreckage of a three-train crash in
south London that killed 33 people and injured more than 100.
   Railway officials said Monday's accident near Clapham Junction,
one of Europe's busiest rail stations, may have been the result of a
signal mix-up caused by work being done on the line.
   Opposition politicians and consumer groups said lax safety
measures and overcrowded trains were underlying causes of the
morning rush-hour crash.
   A crowded commuter train plowed into the rear of a stationary
passenger train. An empty freight train coming in the opposite
direction on a parallel track then hit wreckage from the first crash.
   More than 110 of the estimated 1,500 passengers on the trains
were hospitalized, 32 suffering serious injuries including multiple
fractures, crushed abdomens and amputations, hospital and ambulance
officials said.
   ``Bodies were cut in half, limbs were thrown around by the
impact,'' physician Robin Winch said.
   The condition of the bodies caused officials to repeatedly change
the official death toll from the crash. On Monday night, officials
said 36 people died. But tonight, Scotland Yard revised the death
toll to 33, saying the discrepancy was caused by the mutilated state
of some of the bodies.
   Rescuers aided by arc lights and cranes worked until dawn today
to clear debris from the crash, Britain's worst rail disaster since
43 people died when a subway train crashed in a London tunnel in
1975.
   A British Rail spokesman who requested anonymity said officials
hoped to have commuter trains running again by tonight's rush hour,
and at least some trains running through the accident area.
   The Duchess of York and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
separately visited the injured at St. George's Hospital.
   Allison Killerby, a 26-year-old clerk who suffered deep gashes
across her nose and forehead, recalled:
   ``I saw people's legs and arms and heard them screaming for help
... In one way I wish I had been unconscious so I wouldn't remember
it all so clearly.''
   Eight of the 20 cars overturned and three were hurled into the
air. Some passengers were trapped up to four hours.
   Ronald Arlette, 52, who was on the stationary train, said:
``There was an almighty bang, like an explosion. The carriage went
up and we flew over and over.
   ``Strangely enough, nobody panicked,'' he said. ``I know it
sounds strange, but we just lay there and we had a laugh and a bit
of a joke with each other. It just seemed the best thing to do to
keep our spirits up.''
   The British Railways Board said preliminary investigations
suggested the crash may have been due to a signal failure associated
with modernization of the line's 40-year-old signaling equipment.
   The Railways Board said it ordered an internal inquiry into the
accident, and Transport Secretary Paul Channon announced an
independent public inquiry.
   ``I don't think the actions of the drivers will be significant in
our inquiry,'' Gordon Pettitt, general manager of British Rail's
southern region, said. ``The fault that we had today was associated
with resignaling work in hand rather than a basic fault in the
signaling system itself.''
   He would not confirm one television report that a signaling
expert had found a loose wire that could have caused random signals
_ green, red or yellow _ to be displayed to approaching trains.
   The resignaling at Clapham Junction is part of a $37 million
project begun a year ago to modernize the equipment on the line.
   Transport Minister Michael Portillo said the project was evidence
that neglect did not play a part in the crash.
   ``The investment that is going on into British Rail at the moment
is really at a record level. There's been a huge amount over recent
years. There's an enormous amount planned for years to come,'' he
told The Associated Press.
   ``I see no evidence at all to suggest that any economy measures
have contributed to this accident.''
   Others disagreed.
   ``The system has been creaking at the seams for so long that
something had to give,'' said John Stewart, policy coordinator for
Capital, a public transport pressure group.
   John Prescott, the opposition Labor Party's transport spokesman,
cited a Department of Transport report which he said concluded
deaths and serious injuries on trains had risen 62 percent and
collisions 18 percent since 1982.
   The Railways Board said the state-run British Rail network
accepted full responsibility for the disaster. It said claims for
compensation from relatives of the dead and from those injured would
be dealt with quickly. No amounts were stated.
</TEXT>
