<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Arafat, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0637,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Says Arafat Failed To Meet US Test For A Dialgoue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts grafs 8-9, Asked whether, with Bush response</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat's U.N. speech on the
outlook for peace in the Middle East contained some ``interesting
and positive'' elements but failed to meet U.S. conditions for a
dialogue with the Palestinian organization, the State Department
said today.
   ``These issues must be handled squarely and without ambiguity,''
spokesman Charles E. Redman said.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. official disclosed that the State Department,
working through unspecified ``third parties,'' attempted to persuade
Arafat before the speech to meet the U.S. conditions for a dialogue.
   Israeli sources disclosed that Secretary of State George P.
Shultz had notified Ambassador Moshe Arad Monday night that if the
conditions were met the United States was prepared to deal with the
PLO.
   Shultz and Charles Hill, a close aide who had served in the U.S.
Embassy in Tel Aviv, both called Arad to inform him of the
diplomatic exchanges, said the sources, who insisted on anonymity.
   U.S. policy prohibits diplomatic contacts with the PLO until it
accepts Israel's right to exist. Redman said the United States was
simply responding to requests from ``third parties`` _ he did not
identify them _ on the ``specifics'' of the American conditions for
a dialogue.
   These are: Explicit recognition of Israel's right to exist,
acceptance of 1967 and 1973 U.N. Security Council resolutions
upholding the right of all states to live within secure borders and
renunciation of terrorism.
   Asked whether his administration would meet with the PLO as a
result of Arafat's U.N. speech, President-elect Bush said, ``No.
we've got to get a much clearer statement of everything.''
   Bush said the three U.S. conditions would have to be met. ``I
would welcome any progress, but it's got to be clear on these three
specific points,'' he told reporters during a picture-taking session
as he met with Carlos Andres Perez, the president-elect of Venezuela.
   Redman said the speech contained ``interesting and positive''
aspects, but there were ``problems with all three'' U.S.
requirements for a substantive dialogue with the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   The spokesman specified as positive the ``overall tone'' of the
speech and ``some movement'' by Arafat on the two resolutions.
Redman did not elaborate.
   ``We listened carefully,'' to the speech, Redman said. ``There
were some interesting and positive developments. But it continued to
be ambiguous.''
</TEXT>
