<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1437EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     12-13 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ishaq Khan Takes Presidential Oath of Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ghulam Ishaq Khan, the senior
statesman credited with guiding Pakistan back to democracy, became
Pakistan's eighth president Tuesday following a landslide victory
reflecting his broad-based support.
   Chief Justice Abdul Haleem administered the oath of office during
a 15-minute ceremony in the mirrored Hall of the Presidency, a
modern building that sits between the two houses of parliament.
   He was to address a joint session of the legislature Wednesday.
   On Monday, the 73-year-old former Senate chairman captured 78
percent of 446 electoral votes cast by members of the Senate,
National Assembly and the four provincial assemblies. They acted as
an electoral college.
   Ishaq Khan was the only one of four candidates who had the
support of Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto's left-leaning Pakistan
People's Party and its conservative opposition led by Ishaq Khan's
own Muslim League party.
   Pakistanis of almost all political stripes have credited the
senior statesman with even-handedly guiding the country back to
democracy from 11 years of autocracy and martial law under late
President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
   Zia died in an Aug. 17 military plane crash, Investigators
concluded the plane was sabotaged but did not say by whom.
   Ishaq Khan automatically became head of state, but Monday's vote
confirmed him for a full, five-year term.
   On Monday, Ms. Bhutto's government also sailed through its first
confidence motion in parliament, with 73 percent among members
attending.
   She and Ishaq Khan have expressed mutual admiration but Ms.
Bhutto has called for the repeal of a 1985 constitutional amendment
authored by Zia that gives the president broad discretionary powers.
   Such a repeal would restore the prime ministerial system in
effect during the 1970s when her father, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, was
head of government.
   Zia overthrew Bhutto in a 1977 military coup and had him hanged
two years laters on conviction of plotting to murder a political
opponent.
   Ishaq Khan has not commented publicly on the repeal issue and Ms.
Bhutto, 35, has yet to test support for it in parliament.
   Pakistan's election process began with mid-November national and
local polls.
   It will be completed with by-elections sometime in January to
fill disputed seats, or those from districts where a candidate died
during the campaign.
</TEXT>
