<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PitBullAttack     12-13 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pit Bull Attack,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pit Bull Acquired As Puppy Kills Baby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pit bull that fatally mauled a 6-month-old
girl had been owned by the girl's father since it was a puppy and
was resentful of the attention the baby was getting, according to a
neighbor's son.
   ``I think the dog was just jealous,'' said Timothy Douglas, whose
mother lives next door to Amber Haverstock's parents, Greg and
Carrie Haverstock Vergara. ``It was a house dog who never acted like
a pit bull.''
   Amber, the Vergara's only child, died Sunday in Children's
Hospital Medical Center at Akron five hours after being attacked by
the family's 5-year-old, 60-pound American pit bull. Witnesses say
the dog apparently wanted to eat half a cookie the girl had received
from her mother.
   Douglas, 17, said the Vergaras lived in California until moving
into a Canton duplex about a month ago. They were loving parents,
and one of them was always with the baby, Douglas said.
   Summit County Coroner William Cox said the 24-pound baby died of
heart and lung failure caused by injuries stemming from the bites.
   ``I have heard of deaths like this, but I never expected to see
injuries so severe,'' Cox said in a published report. ``It's just
overwhelming to realize that these injuries came from a dog.''
   Private services for the baby will be at 11 a.m. Wednesday.
   City Prosecutor John Poulos said Monday that an investigation
into the incident will be completed after the baby's funeral.
   Canton Health Commissioner Robert Pattison ordered the dog
quarantined at the Stark County Animal Control Center, where it is
being observed for rabies. He said Health Department and animal
control workers will meet with Poulos to determine whether the dog
should be destroyed before the normal quarantine of 10 days elapses.
</TEXT>
