<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Shuttle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0580,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shuttle Atlantis Reaches Florida</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with shuttle's arrival, picking
up 5th graf pvs, `During the ....'</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede SAN ANTONIO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space shuttle Atlantis today
completed its piggyback ride across the country atop a special
Boeing 747, returning to its Florida launch site a week after
completing its classified military mission.
   The specially modified 747 with the Atlantis on top of it arrived
at the Kennedy Space Center after a three-hop flight across the
country from Edwards Air Force Base, Calif., the shuttle's landing
site.
   The shuttle left Edwards, in the Mojave Desert, on Sunday and
stopped at Davis-Monthan Air Force Base near Tucson, Ariz.,
overnight before flying on to Kelly Air Force Base near San Antonio
on Monday. It remained there overnight before departing for Florida.
   During the four-day flight, the crew of the Atlantis deployed a
spy satellite, according to sources close to the mission.
   The weather was a concern for the shuttle's trip back to Florida,
with officials of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
concerned that flying through rain could damage the thousands of
ceramic tiles on the shuttle's belly. The tiles ward off the extreme
heat of re-entry into the Earth's atmosphere.
   An air-conditioning, heating and filtering unit was flown from
Davis-Monthan and hooked up to the shuttle to maintain its
temperature and filter the air inside the orbiter.
   Atlantis was the second shuttle flight since missions resumed in
September following the Jan. 28, 1986, Challenger disaster, which
claimed the lives of seven astronauts.
</TEXT>
