<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1526EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDS-Babies     12-13 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Babies,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Virus Dormant Longer Than Thought in Some Infants, Study
Suggests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AIDS virus can lie dormant longer than has
been thought in children infected as newborns, implying that a
``large population'' of such children have yet to develop the
disease, a new study asserts.
   Statistical analysis of children infected as newborns suggests
that of those who will develop AIDS by age 10.4, half may remain
healthy until age 4.8, researchers said.
   About 20 percent will develop AIDS within the first year of life
and the rest at about 8 percent a year, the analysis suggested.
   Such incubation periods are longer than those previously reported
in children, and ``strongly suggest there is a large population of
children who are infected but not yet diagnosed'' with AIDS,
researchers wrote in the British journal Nature.
   But they cautioned that their estimates are subject to
substantial error because of lack of solid information about
incubation periods of the AIDS virus.
   One researcher also said it is unclear what fraction of infected
newborns the projections apply to, because nobody knows what
fraction develops AIDS by age 10.4, the cutoff used in the study.
   ``We cannot make any inferences for incubation periods longer
than 10.4 years'' because the disease is too new, said Ivan Auger of
the New York State Department of Health.
   He described the work in last week's Nature with colleagues at
the department, the New York City health department and the Harvard
School of Public Health.
   They developed statistical analyses from the records of 215
children with AIDS who had apparently been infected by their
mothers, which can occur during pregnancy or delivery.
   Currently, most infected newborns who develop AIDS are diagnosed
by age 2, said Margaret Oxtoby of the federal Centers for Disease
Control. Other children have reached ages 7 or 8 before developing
symptoms, she said.
   But the true distribution of incubation periods in children is
not yet known, she said. Current observations underestimate it
because the disease is relatively new, and only children who develop
symptoms soonest after infection are being observed, she said
Tuesday.
   The new study ``just highlights the fact that we haven't seen the
whole epidemic yet,'' she said. ``It's still unfolding in front of
us.''
   While the projections are useful for pointing out that ``there's
more out there than meets the eye ... I would just hesitate in
putting weight on a specific figure,'' she said.
   The analysis suggested that some children may have a brief
incubation period, with half diagnosed within 4.1 months of birth.
But most children appear to have a longer incubation, with half of
them being diagnosed only by about age 6.
   Researchers have no explanation for such a difference, Auger said
Monday.
   Lynne Billard of the University of Georgia in Athens, who has
studied AIDS incubation periods, said she was unaware of any similar
study of children infected by their mothers. The new work is
important for exploring that ground, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1529EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Belgium-Missiles 1stLd-Writethru a0638 12-13 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Belgium-Missiles, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0638,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Cruise Missiles Leave Belgium</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to ADD that Belgium first Western nation to be
rid of medium-range missiles; INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf,
``Belgian Defense ...'' with additional quote from defense minister.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FLORENNES, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans flew the last U.S. cruise
missiles out of Belgium on Tuesday, making it the first Western
nation to be rid of its medium-range nuclear missiles under the
year-old superpower treaty.
   Eight missiles and their launch canisters, sealed in white
containers, were rolled onto a giant C-141 cargo plane at Florennes
Air Base for the flight back to the United States. Florennes is 65
miles south of Brussels.
   ``This marks a very important milestone and a great success for
us,'' said Maynard Glitman, U.S. ambassdor to Belgium and chief
American negotiator in talks leading to the Intermediate-range
Nuclear Forces Treaty.
   Belgian Defense Minister Guy Coeme said, ``Farewell ceremonies
are very often full of bitterness, even of sadness. Here, however,
in the case of the departure of the last cruise missile based on our
territory, one can speak of hope _ hope for peace.''
   ``Within the Atlantic Alliance ... Belgium is the first country
from which intermediate-range missiles have been withdrawn,'' he
said.
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev signed
the accord Dec. 8, 1987. It provides for elimination by June 1,
1991, of all U.S. and Soviet land-based missiles with ranges of 300
to 3,400 miles.
   ``I'm really proud to take these out of here,'' said Airman 1st
Class Tammy Murray, the loadmaster who flew with the plane from
Travis Air Force Base, Calif.
   Glitman confessed that ``I suppose I should be more emotional.''
But he noted, ``The issues that lie behind the negotiations haven't
gone away either. ... We still have a lot of work to do.''
   Unofficial observers also were moved by the sight of the plane
lifting off.
   ``It's beautiful to see them leave,'' said Paul D'Huyvetter, one
of a small group of demonstrators outside the base.
   D'Huyvetter, who held a small pink carnation to mark the event,
said the missiles' departure ``gives us energy to go on'' and press
for further arms control measures.
   In all, 16 ground-launched cruise missiles and four spares were
kept at Florennes base along with four launchers and eight spares.
   The sleek, ground-hugging weapons arrived in March 1985.
   Col. Calvin Chasteen, commander of the tactical wing, said the
first 12 missiles were removed within the last two weeks.
   Glitman said as far as he knew no other American nuclear devices
remained on the base, which has housed the U.S. Air Force's 485th
Tactical Missile Wing since 1984.
   The missiles are being flown to Davis-Monthan Air Force Base in
Tucson, Ariz., where they will be destroyed.
   The European Repair Facility at Gosslies, 10 miles north of
Florennes, is expected to operate until nearly all missiles covered
by the treaty are removed.
   The 21-foot weapons are jet-propelled, winged missiles with
advanced guidance systems.
   No Soviet inspectors attended the ceremony. They visited the base
earlier this year as part of an unprecedented review process given
each side under the treaty.
   Coeme said the Belgian government was studying options for the
base, which include using it as a storage center for U.S. military
equipment or a training school for test pilots for the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1538EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Campion     12-13 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Campion,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rev. Donald Campion, Former Editor of America Magazine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Donald R. Campion, a Jesuit priest,
teacher and journalist who served as editor-in-chief of America
magazine, has died after a long illness. He was 67.
   Campion, who last served as spiritual director for Jesuit
seminarians at Murray-Weigel Hall of Fordham University in the
Bronx, died there on Sunday, the Jesuit Mission Bureau announced.
   The president of Fordham, the Rev. Joseph A. O'Hare, called
Campion ``one of the great American Jesuits of our time.''
   During the 1960s Campion was Rome correspondent for America, a
Catholic magazine published by the Jesuits, and wrote extensively
about the theological changes of the Second Vatican Council.
   Following a hiatus at Fordham University and the World-Wide
Self-Study of the Society of Jesus, Campion served as
editor-in-chief of America from 1968 to 1975. From 1975 to 1978, he
was director of the press and information office for the Society of
Jesus in Rome.
   Campion then served for six years as secretary for information
and communication of the Jesuit Conference in Washington. In 1984,
ill health forced him to return to Fordham.
   Campion is survived by a sister-in-law, Dolores Campion. Funeral
services will be Wednesday at the Fordham University Church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
