<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Protester 1stLd-Writethru   12-13 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Protester, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0595,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Ordered To Pay $5,000 To Abortion Protester</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Schlissmann throughout story.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city violated the constitutional rights
of an abortion protester arrested for not having a parade permit for
a two-person demonstration, a federal court has ruled.
   The U.S. District Court on Monday ordered Jackson to pay $5,000
in damages to Carol Ann Schlissmann, 33.
   Schlissmann said the ruling upholds the right to demonstrate
based on religious beliefs.
   ``If you're a Christian, you don't have to be a doormat,'' she
said following Monday's ruling. ``The Constitution protects all of
us.''
   City officials could not be reached by telephone for comment.
   Schlissmann, who now lives in Michigan, was arrested in May 1987
during a protest at Mississippi Women's Medical Center in Jackson
under a city law that bans public demonstrations without a permit.
She sued the city in July 1987, seeking $1.2 million in damages.
   The city had offered to drop the charge if Schlissmann dropped
her suit, but she declined.
   Attorney Tom Lowe of Jackson, representing Schlissmann,
questioned how the city could arrest Schlissmann and Roy McMillan,
executive director of the Mississippi Abortion Abolition Society,
for demonstrating because the protest involved only two people.
   McMillan and Schlissmann held signs reading, ``Pray to End
Abortion'' and ``Abortion Destroys God's Handiwork.'' The two also
had a small coffin draped with an American flag.
   About 15 minutes after the two began to hand out literature in
front of the clinic, police arrested them for not having a parade
permit, McMillan said.
   The four-man, two-woman jury deliberated 15 minutes before
returning its verdict.
</TEXT>
