<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     12-13 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Back At Florida Launch Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Space shuttle Atlantis, its right
fuselage in need of repairs, returned to its launch site Tuesday
atop a Boeing 747 jetliner after two overnight stops.
   The 747 touched down at the Kennedy Space Center here at 2:25
p.m. to complete a hopscotch flight that began Sunday at Edwards Air
Force Base, Calif.
   Atlantis landed at Edwards, in the Mojave Desert, a week ago
after completing a four-day classified flight during which the five
military astronauts aboard reportedly deployed a sophisticated
reconnaissance satellite.
   Enroute back here, the jetliner made overnight stops at
Davis-Monthon Air Force Base near Tucson, Ariz., and at Kelly Air
Force Base near San Antonio, Tex.
   When Atlantis returned to Earth, NASA found it had suffered
heavier than expected damage to the heat-resistant tiles on its
right fuselage, and the vehicle's processing director, Conrad Nagel,
estimated between 125 and 175 of them will have to be replaced.
   NASA engineers suspect something struck that area of the shuttle
during launch, possibly insulation falling off the external fuel
tank. An agency team has been named to investigate the cause.
   Debris found imbedded in a shuttle tile has been sent to a
laboratory for analysis, and films and photographs of the launch are
being studied for clues.
   Atlantis is covered with about 28,000 tiles designed to protect
it from heat up to 3,000 degrees Fahrenheit when it leaves orbit and
re-enters Earth's atmosphere.
   Officials said the repair work should not affect preparations for
launching Atlantis on its next flight during which astronauts will
dispatch the Magellan spacecraft to explore the planet Venus. The
launch is scheduled April 28.
   Discovery, which was launched on the first post-Challenger flight
on Sept. 29, is scheduled to be launched again on Feb. 18, with a
communications satellite as its cargo.
</TEXT>
