<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ModernHomesteading Bjt   12-13 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Modern Homesteading, Bjt,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rural Minnesota County Tries To Beef Up Population With
Homesteading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INTERNATIONAL FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A declining population has led
a northern Minnesota county to try a version of the nation's old
homestead policy: Anyone can claim up to 40 acres of land if they
build a house and live in it for 10 years.
   ``Our real problem up here is that nobody's here anymore,'' said
Lee Hervey, one of the residents of rural Koochiching County who
proposed the homesteading plan.
   The 2 million-acre county along the Canadian border _ three times
as big as Rhode Island _ has about 15,700 residents, only eight
communities and vast stretches where no one lives.
   It also has about 50,000 acres of woods and farmland abandoned to
the county when its owners failed to pay taxes. That's the land the
county wants to give away.
   ``There are people that live in Chicago, New York or the Twin
Cities that might be sick and tired of the rat race, the rush-hour
traffic ... and, believe me, we'll eliminate that from the lifestyle
real quick,'' said Bob Schwiderski, who directs the homestead
program.
   Added Hervey, ``We really don't have a lot to offer up here
besides the land, so we decided that's what we should offer. The
population's dropping and that hurts the schools, the power company,
everything. If we don't get neighbors, we won't be able to live here
either.''
   More than 180 people have inquired about the homesteading
program, and two dozen have formally applied. County officials say
they hope to hand over the first deeds within a week.
   While other rural areas in the country have offered tax breaks
and other financial assistance to lure residents, federal officials
and development experts said they believed this was the first
large-scale land giveaway since the federal homestead program was
eliminated.
   Homesteading was the catalyst that spurred the settlement of the
Plains and the West. The Homestead Act of 1862 offered up to 160
acres of free farmland to settlers willing to develop the property
and live there for at least five years.
   During the first five years of homesteading, settlers rushed into
Minnesota faster than into any other state _ more than 62,000 of
them by 1880.
   In 1976, long after homesteading had ceased, Congress abolished
the act. Only in Alaska does it continue, under a state-directed
program.
   In Koochiching County, officials hope that International Falls
will boom again once Boise Cascade completes a $525 million
expansion of its big paper mill. But the county's other vital signs
aren't good. Since 1980, the population has dropped by about 2,000
residents.
   Koochiching County isn't the only area of Minnesota seeking new
residents. In October, the central Minnesota town of Osakis began
offering $5,000 in cash to anyone willing to build a house and
settle.
   Koochiching officials persuaded state legislators last year to
sponsor a special local law that allowed them to implement the
homestead program, formally called the Bidstead and Economic
Development Program.
   Under the rules, not only must applicants agree to homebuilding,
taxpaying and occupying their new home, they also must ``maintain an
income sufficient'' to live there. And before their application is
approved, they must submit to a credit and criminal-records check.
   ``We want people that are self-sufficient,'' Schwiderski said.
``We're not looking for an opportunity to increase our welfare rolls
up here.''
   ``There's really not any jobs up here as such.'' added Hervey,
42, who is self-employed. ``We expect them to bring their livelihood
with them.''
   If 250 families applied and settled in the county, ``I would
consider the program successful,'' Schwiderski said.
   Among applicants so far are retirees and couples interested in
relocating their small businesses, Schwiderski said.
   One of the applicants, Tom Johnson Jr., said he returned to his
family's Koochiching County home from Florida because the homestead
program would give him a chance he wouldn't otherwise have to make a
living where he grew up.
   Johnson, 23, has his eye on 40 acres next to his father's
property. He plans to build an earth-berm, passive-solar house on
the land, supporting himself by working for his father's logging
operation.
   ``Ten years is a long time, but I'm planning to stay here the
rest of my life if I can,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
