<DOCNO> AP881213-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1727EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NATO-Study     12-13 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO-Study,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NATO Should Follow Soviet Example With Troop Reductions, Group Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NATO should respond to announced Soviet troop
cuts by reducing its own military forces and match the Soviet plan
to move to strictly defensive forces, a liberal study group said
Tuesday.
   In addition, European members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization should be prepared to pick up a greater share of the
burden of defending the Western alliance, the Institute for Peace
and International Security said.
   Economist John Kenneth Galbraith and Rep. Patricia Schroeder,
D-Colo., a member of the House Armed Services Committee and a
frequent critic of Reagan administration defense policies, head the
advisory board of the Cambridge, Mass.-based research center.
   Mrs. Schroeder, who released the study at a news conference,
noted the announcement last week by Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev that the Soviet Union was cutting its armed forces by 10
percent worldwide. Some of the reductions will be in Eastern Europe,
and the Soviet forces also will be restructured to make them
defensive, rather than offensive, Gorbachev said.
   ``As we face the largest budget deficit in our nation's history,
Mr. Gorbachev's initiative gives us the opportunity to cut our
defense budget without endangering our national security,'' Mrs.
Schroeder said.
   ``Our European allies must still face up to new
responsibilities,'' she added.
   ``In the face of a new, positive arms control climate and the
emergence of Western Europe as a unified world trading entity, our
European allies must prepare themselves not only for this new role,
but for roles and responsibilities that come with being a global
power,'' she said.
   The study proposed several responses to Gorbachev's plan,
including:
   _An immediate ``confidence-building withdrawal'' of 5 percent of
the active ground forces in central Europe by both sides, which
would be 20,000 Soviet troops and 10,000 U.S. troops. Gorbachev had
pledged to implement his reductions by 1991.
   _A pause in deployment of new short-range nuclear weapons by NATO
and the Soviet bloc. Medium-range missiles are being eliminated by a
U.S.-Soviet treaty signed a year ago, but the pact doesn't affect
weapons with so-called battlefield range.
   _Movement to dominance by defense, rather than offense, in the
military structure of each side. One example would be a decrease in
heavily armored forces, including tanks and artillery, because those
forces normally are employed in attack.
   A prime focus of arms control efforts should be the withdrawal of
offensive weapons, the study said.
   One of the hurdles to be overcome is the belief by Western
leaders that NATO forces already are at the minimum level, despite
the Warsaw Pact reductions, the study said.
   Another potential problem it cited was the possibility that
``NATO may be reluctant to break its morbid dependence on nuclear
weapons, even if progress in conventional arms negotiations
undermines the present rationale for those weapons.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1728EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Soviet-Ventures     12-13 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet-Ventures,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Firm, Soviets Establish Joint Venture To Venture Jointly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington's largest law firm announced Tuesday
a joint venture with a Soviet enterprise aimed at creating a variety
of U.S.-Soviet businesses, ranging from pollution control to caviar
production.
   Speaking at a news conference with a telephone hookup to Moscow,
officials of the 300-lawyer firm of Arnold & Porter said U.S. and
Soviet officials of the new venture would meet with prospective
clients later this week.
   New Soviet economic policies of openness, or ``perestroika,''
offer ``access to a market of 280 million highly educated Soviet
consumers with an enormous need for goods and technology,'' said
James Jones, Arnold & Porter managing partner.
   He said Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's policies are
``setting an exciting new course for East-West business
relationships.''
   The firm's consulting affiliate, APCO Associates, hopes to double
the number of U.S.-Soviet ventures by the end of next year. Ten
joint U.S.-Soviet business agreements have been concluded to date,
along with about 100 Soviet ventures with businesses from other
countries.
   Soviet law expert Randy Bregman, who will direct APCO's new
Soviet and East European operations, said he looks to the day when a
Soviet citizen can buy borscht made by Campbell Soup Co.
   He said Campbell is not one of the companies now involved, but
this is an example of the kind of enterprise that might result from
the new agreement with INFEKS, a six-month old Soviet consulting
cooperative affiliated with the U.S.S.R. Ministry of Foreign
Economic Relations.
   Bregman declined to name companies that might deal with the
Soviets through APCO, but he said they include about a dozen
companies involved in food processing, pollution control, medical
equipment, tourism and telecommunications. One U.S. company even
wants to get into caviar production, he said.
   Current Soviet law requires that joint ventures be no more than
49 percent foreign owned, but Bregman said there have been strong
indications this might be liberalized early next year. He said some
contracts already have been written with majority foreign ownership.
   Vladimir Gusinsky, INFEKS president, said from Moscow that the
Soviet enterprise is part of the economic perestroika under way in
the Soviet Union.
   ``We are looking forward to developing economic relations with
U.S. companies,'' Gusinsky said through a translator who also
translated the Washington news conference in Russian over the
telephone hookup.
   APCO President Margery Kraus said the company, which also has set
up joint ventures with Japanese and Iraeli businesses, would open an
office in Moscow early next year.
   She said the company would provide ``one-stop shopping'' for
companies wanting to do business in the Soviet Union, charging fees
for its services. She said there were no plans for APCO to share in
profits of the joint ventures it helps set up.
   Bregman, who has been dealing with Soviet commerce for 25 years,
said the climate for business has changed dramatically under
Gorbachev, with many cooperatives and other enterprises set up with
only partial state involvement. Those run by people with more
initiative are seeking foreign business ties, he said.
   A few years ago, Bregman said, when Moscow citizens saw a man in
a suit, they would approach the individual and say, ``Do you want to
change money?''
   Now, he said, they ask, ``Do you want to do joint ventures?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1755EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Commuters     12-13 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Commuters,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disaster a Lightning Rod for Gripes About Railways</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three-train fatal accident in south London has
become a lightning rod for commuters' grievances over rising fares
and ``sardine express'' service.
   ``We have to stop talking about the profit-and-loss account and
thinking about whether we can go on patching up a 150-year-old
railway system the way British Rail has to,'' said Robert Adley, a
member of Parliament for Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
Conservative Party.
   Some of Adley's constituents from Dorset ride British Rail
through busy Clapham Junction, where the accident involving two
commuter trains and a freight train occurred Monday, killing 33
people.
   ``The system has been creaking at the seams for so long that
something had to give,'' said John Stewart, policy coordinator for
Capital, a public transport pressure group.
   British Rail brings 467,000 commuters to London every morning
rush hour, an increase of 19 percent since 1983.
   ``Death on the Sardine Express,'' blared the tabloid Today. Even
the Conservative-leaning Daily Telegraph said Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's government ``has yet to reveal the commitment to
public services, transport prominent among them, that it has so
admirably displayed in creating a new spirit within the private
sector.''
   On the morning of the crash, railroad union members dressed as
sardines were handing out leaflets at London's Euston Station
complaining about crowding on trains.
   ``Conditions for many commuters are very, very bad. We need new
trains, more staff and longer platforms,'' Neil Milligan, general
secretary of the Associated Society of Locomotive Engineers and
Firemen, said at the Euston demonstration.
   On a small island crowded with 56 million people, commuters must
choose between roads spread thick with traffic jams and
standing-room-only service on British rail.
   Passenger traffic on Network SouthEast, the British Rail division
which serves London and its suburbs, is up 19 percent since 1983.
Capital investment has also grown rapidly, from $644 million
system-wide in 1983 to $1.15 billion this fiscal year.
   British Rail, meanwhile, has been hard-pressed to fill staff
vacancies, particularly among telecommunications and signal workers,
some of them lured away by higher wages offered by the recently
privatized telephone company, British Telecom.
   Earlier this month, British Rail announced incentives worth $450
to $2,175 a year for workers in southern England. In November, as
part of an effort to fill 200 vacancies for train drivers, British
Rail announced plans to develop 73 low-cost apartments and 15 houses
in London.
   Meanwhile, the 10,000-mile British Rail system has pledged to cut
its government subsidy by 25 percent between 1987 and 1990.
   The burden lifted from the taxpayer has fallen increasingly on
the ticket-buyer. British Rail is raising fares by an average of 9
percent on Jan. 8, compared to an inflation rate around 6 percent,
but fares for long-distance commuters are soaring as much as 21
percent.
   The 155-mile round trip from Swindon to London, for instance,
will go from $3,996 a year to $4,825.
   The Central Transport Consultative Committee, the rail system's
statutory watchdog, said in its 1988 report that crowding had become
an epidemic in the southeast.
   ``The existing load factor standards, 110 percent for slam-door
stock, 135 percent for (newer) sliding-door trains, were intended as
maximum loadings _ not average targets to be aimed at,'' the report
said.
   Robin Seymour, the chief inspector of railways, acknowledged
concern about overcrowding in his report. However, he said, ``there
is no evidence to suggest that overcrowding per se may be the cause
of train accidents.''
   Seymour reported there were 1,164 accidents on British Rail and
the London subways in 1987, the lowest total in five years. Deaths
went up from 72 in 1986 to 104, largely due to 31 deaths in the
King's Cross subway station fire.
   The Clapham disaster may have been caused by signal improvements,
part of $37 million being spent on some of the lines leading to
London's Waterloo station.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
