<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Hodge,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Director of San Diego Philharmonic Dies At 75</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leslie Hodge, who conducted orchestras around
the world and was the first resident director of the San Diego
Philharmonic, was killed in a traffic accident. He was 75.
   Hodge, a La Jolla, Calif., resident, was killed last Tuesday when
his car was involved in a collision with a truck stopped on
Interstate 5 in the Sorrento Valley area, 13 miles north of San
Diego.
   He served as resident director of the San Diego Philharmonic,
predecessor to the San Diego Symphony, from 1950 to 1952, and
presented the first series of children's concerts. He also offered
the first winter concerts in San Diego.
   Hodge, a native of Australia, began studying piano at age 4 and
was performing in concert at age 11.
   He was the founding conductor of the Guadalajara Symphony in
Mexico, and was conductor of the Phoenix Symphony from 1952 to 1959.
He spent six years as a guest conductor in West Germany and other
countries.
   Hodge had taught piano for the last 18 years.
   Hodge's survivors include his wife, Barbara, and four
stepdaughters.
</TEXT>
