<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Quake-Nuclear     12-13 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Nuclear,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Says Power Plant Will be Shut in Two Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YEREVAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear power plant built on a
geological fault near the Armenian capital will be shut down in two
years because of the danger, according to Soviet Premier Nikolai I.
Ryzhkov.
   There were many rumors in Armenia and outside the Soviet Union
about damage to the plant after a powerful earthquake shook
northwestern Armenia on Dec. 7. The quake was felt in Yerevan, but
officials said the plant withstood it.
   Local officials have said in recent weeks that a decision had
been made to shut the plant, which Armenian activists have demanded.
But Ryzhkov's statment to reporters at a news conference at the
Armenian Communist Party Central Committee headquarters on Monday
were the highest-level confirmation of that.
   The plant cannot be shut down immediately because it supplies too
much of the republic's electricity, Ryzkhov said.
   ``If it was shut down, life would stop in the republic,'' he said.
   Foreign Ministry officials said after the earthquake the plant
was undamaged and working at full capacity.
