<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1736EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     12-13 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0854</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protests Held to Mark Anniversary of Martial-Law Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students chanting ``Solidarity!'' hurled
stones at riot police Tuesday and were answered with tear gas in a
demonstration at Warsaw University on the seventh anniversary of
Poland's martial-law crackdown.
   Thousands of anti-government protesters rallied in Wroclaw and at
least four other cities, opposition activists said, as the official
press defended the military crackdown ordered Dec. 13, 1981, by
Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   A government spokesman said five policemen were injured badly
enough in Warsaw to require hospitalization and five people _
probably students _ were detained.
   About 2,000 students squared off against several hundred
shield-carrying, helmeted police at the gates of Warsaw University.
   Students hoisted banners saying ``Solidarity'' and ``There is no
freedom without Solidarity'' during a rally organized by the
outlawed Polish Socialist Party just off campus at a monument to the
16th century astronomer Copernicus.
   Banners also were raised for other illegal opposition groups,
including the Socialist Party, the Independent Students Association
and the Confederation for an Independent Poland.
   Police chased the students back into the walled campus, dragging
some of them away. Then students began throwing stones from within
the gates and police answered with tear gas, which filled the chilly
air with stinging smoke.
   Students picked up canisters and threw them back at police, and
after about an hour the situation degenerated into a standoff with
students chanting slogans and the police facing them from behind
their shields across the street.
   Several sweeps by phalanxes of police cleared the sidewalks by
late afternoon, and most of the students drifted away through back
entrances of the university to end the protest.
   In the southwestern city of Wroclaw, an opposition spokeswoman
said 15,000 people rallied with banners saying ``Jaruzelski Must
Go,'' and police did not interfere.
   ``The speeches concentrated on what happened on Dec. 13, 1981,
and the fact that it is high time for democracy to be implemented,''
said Maria Pinior, whose husband, Jozef, was one of the leaders of
the protest.
   The demonstration also included one minute of silence for those
killed during the martial law crackdown, she said.
   The Solidarity Information Service in Warsaw reported smaller
rallies in Lodz, Jastrzebie and Lublin. Zygmunt Lenyk, a spokesman
for the Confederation for an Independent Poland in Krakow, said
2,500 people there marched to the site of Solidarity's former
headquarters.
   ``We survived seven years and we are still here,'' Lenyk quoted
Solidarity activist Jerzy Smagowicz as telling the crowd.
   In a commentary, the Communist Party daily newspaper Trybuna Ludu
said ``one can remember Dec. 13 for years with a measure of
bitterness and divisions. One can open the healing wounds anew.''
   ``But would it not be better for Poland ... if the date of the
lesser evil were overshadowed by a joyful day, the day of
eliminating national discord and of common action for Poland?''
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said, ``We consider the
imposition of martial law to have been a necessary evil, an evil
that turned out to be effective. Today's progress toward
reconciliation would not have been possible without martial law.''
   On Dec. 13, 1981, Poles woke up to find tanks in the streets,
martial music on the radio and thousands of active members of
Solidarity rounded up and interned.
   The lightning blow by the army under Jaruzelski's command put an
end overnight to the legal operation of the East bloc's first
independent trade union, a 10 million-strong social movement that
had electrified the country for 15 months.
   Solidarity was at first suspended and was banned the following
October.
   The operation took place with little bloodshed. Nine coal miners
were killed during a strike at the Wujek mine near Katowice on Dec.
16, 1981, but otherwise there were no known casualties during
introduction of the officially named ``state of war.'' Martial law
was formally lifted in July 1983.
   Officials argued the Solidarity leadership had been taken over by
elements who threatened the political supremacy of the Polish United
Workers (Communist) Party. If Poles had not acted to restore order,
the Soviet Union and its allies would have been forced to intervene
at a higher cost, they said.
   Solidarity remains illegal but is increasingly tolerated by
authorities.
   The union demonstrated it still has a following after leading two
waves of strikes in 1988, the strongest since the martial-law
crackdown. Walesa ended the second wave of strikes when the
government agreed to talk with him.
   On Nov. 30, authorities allowed him to participate in a
nationwide TV debate with official unions chief Alfred Miodowicz,
which Walesa was widely considered to have won.
   But the proposed talks with the government have stalled, with
Walesa insisting that he first wants a signal that authorities are
willing to legalize his union again.
   Solidarity plans ceremonies Friday in Gdansk to honor the victims
of Dec. 16, 1970, food riots and the miners killed resisting martial
law in 1980.
</TEXT>
