<DOCNO> AP881213-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1900EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-VanGogh     12-13 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Van Gogh,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Terrain Stymies Police Search For Stolen Van Goghs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTERLO, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police hunting burglars who stole
three Vincent van Gogh paintings said Tuesday they are hampered by
the size of the scene of the crime: a museum surrounded by the
country's biggest national park.
   Karel van Seventer said, however, the police's rapid response
apparently stopped the thieves taking a fourth painting by the 19th
century Dutch impressionist master.
   ``Weaver's Interior,'' which Seventer earlier identified as one
of the stolen works, was found lying on the floor of the room from
which the other three had disappeared, he said.
   In probably the biggest art theft in the Netherlands, thieves
Monday night broke into the Kroeller-Mueller museum and stole the
oil paintings ``The Potato Eaters,'' ``Wilted Sunflowers'' and ``The
Loom,'' Seventer said. Earlier, he wrongly identified the flower
painting as ``Dried Sunflowers.''
   Alerted by an alarm when burglars smashed a ground-floor window,
police rushed to the museum within minutes and sealed off the
12,350-acre expanse of forests, shrubs and heath of Hoge Veluwe
park, he said. Guards posted in the sprawling single-story museum
said they did not hear the thieves, he said.
   ``It all happened very fast ... We were acting on the assumption
that they were possibly still on the grounds right after the
alarm,'' Seventer told a news conference.
   ``The trouble was the grounds are 5,000 hectares large and made
up of difficult terrain,'' he said. The park has only three roads
accessible by motor vehicle.
   Two helicopter sweeps of the area, which normally is inhabited
only by five gamekeepers and their families, produced no clues.
Police used tracker dogs, also to no avail.
   No official valuation has been disclosed for the works, which
were not insured by the state because of the astronomical premiums
they would command. However, a Dutch art expert speculated ``The
Potato Eaters'' alone could be worth more than the $39.9 million
paid for van Gogh's ``Sunflowers'' at a London auction last year.
   But it would be virtually impossible to sell it on the open
market.
   The spectacular theft was the second in seven months' involving
works by van Gogh and underscored relatively lax security at museums.
   In May, thieves broke into Amsterdam's Municipal Museum and stole
van Gogh's ``Carnations'' and two other impressionist paintings. All
three were recovered undamaged a few weeks later.
   Most officials declined to speculate on why the paintings were
stolen, since it would be virtually impossible to sell them on the
open market.
   However, Dutch Association of Museums spokesman R. Zijp said in a
Dutch TV interview that ``what's most likely is that they'll be held
to ransom, (in) a kind of kidnapping.''
   Van Seventer said no ransom demand had so far been made.
   In another TV interview, Culture Minister Elco Brinkman said
security at the country's national museums was being increased.
   But, ``You can't just go on pouring tens of millions of guilders
into it,'' Brinkman said. ``Some time you'll have to face the
question whether there aren't any better ways of spending that money
on culture.''
   The Kroeller-Mueller museum is named for Mrs. H.E.L.J.
Kroeller-Mueller, the art-loving wife of a prominent industrialist
who bequeathed it to the nation in 1938 with the surrounding park.
   The museum contains 278 van Gogh paintings, sketches and etchings.
   Kroeller-Mueller's ``The Potato Eaters'' is the second in a
series of three, with the final and most important painting on
display at Amsterdam's Vincent van Gogh National Museum.
   The 1885 works were painted in van Gogh's native village of
Nuenen and are among his most poignant expressions of famine and
hardship. Done in dark, harsh tones, they show a peasant family
eating potatoes, their faces lined by suffering and deprivation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
