<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1906EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FBIGambler     12-13 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI Gambler,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Settles Suit With Former FBI Agent Who Gambled Away
Agency Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former FBI agent who claimed his gambling
habit was a handicap, not a reason for dismissal, has settled a suit
he filed against the federal government after he was fired for
gambling away $1,800 in FBI funds, officials said Tuesday.
   The Justice Department has agreed to pay an undisclosed sum to
Anthony P. Rezza, 50, a 22-year veteran of the FBI, according to an
unidentified source cited by the Philadelphia Daily News.
   Rezza also will be entitled to a reduced pension as a result of
the settlement and to attorney's fees, the newspaper reported
Tuesday.
   Rezza had sued the Justice Department seeking back pay, his
pension and lawyers' fees.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joan K. Garner, who handled the
negotiations for the Justice Department, would not comment Tuesday
on the terms of the settlement or the reasons the government agreed
to settle.
   Rezza's attorney, Alice W. Ballard, did not immediately return a
phone call seeking comment Tuesday.
   Ms. Ballard had contended that Rezza was a pathological gambler
in July 1985 when he drove to Atlantic City without permission in an
FBI car and played blackjack with money that was to have been used
for an undercover drug buy.
   Agents found Rezza inside the Trump Plaza Casino. Rezza, now a
private investigator, underwent treatment for his gambling and said
in court documents that he has not gambled since. He also made
restitution of the FBI funds he lost.
   Ms. Ballard said pathological gambling is a handicap, which,
under federal law, obligates the FBI to help, not fire, an impaired
employee.
   U.S. District Judge Edmund V. Ludwig ruled last month that Rezza
was a pathological gambler when the gambling spree took place.
   Court records showed Rezza had lost as much as $40,000 of his and
his wife's money in the preceding five years through gambling.
   Rezza claimed in his suit that the FBI punished him more severely
than it did other agents who committed worse offenses. In response,
the government had to produce files of secret disciplinary actions
against other agents. FBI officials have declined comment on the
files.
   The cases included:
   _A supervisory agent in Philadelphia who placed bets with a
bookie through an intermediary while his squad was investigating the
same bookie. The agent was demoted, suspended for 45 days and placed
on probation.
   _An agent arrested while entering the United States with
marijuana and drug paraphernalia, suspended for 30 days.
   _An agent who falsified a report from a lie detector test in
1983, suspended for 21 days.
   _An agent who failed to report his arrest for drunken driving,
suspended for 40 days and put on probation.
   No names were included in the files presented in court, and they
were accompanied by little detail.
</TEXT>
