<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Obit-Nichols 1stLd-Writethru a0659 12-13 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Nichols, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alabama Congressman Suffers Fatal Heart Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new 11th graf, ``Defense Secretary,'' with Carlucci
comment; adds one graf with funeral arrangements</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Bill Nichols, a staunch Pentagon supporter
who became a leader in efforts to reform the nation's military
establishment, died Tuesday after suffering a heart attack at his
office, an aide to the Alabama Democrat said. He was 70.
   Nichols, who won his 12th term in Congress last month, died in
the emergency room at Capitol Hill Hospital shortly after 8 a.m.,
hospital spokeswoman Lisa Poulter said.
   He was rushed to the hospital after an aide heard a noise in his
office and found him unconscious, lying face down behind his desk,
said Tom McMahan, a Nichols spokesman.
   Nichols, who lost a leg in World War II, was a strong supporter
of President Reagan's military buildup, but he used his chairmanship
of the House Armed Services investigations subcommittee to keep a
close watch over Pentagon spending.
   After widely publicized hearings into such questionable
expendutures as $400 Navy hammers and $5,000 Air Force coffee pots,
Nichols succeeded in amending a military spending bill to require
the Defense Department to report to Congress on procurement reforms
and to prohibit defense contractors from billing the government for
expenses such as country club dues and lobbying costs.
   The courtly, white-haired legislator also headed the
congressional investigation into the 1983 bombing of the Marine
barracks in Lebanon which killed 241 Americans. That investigation
uncovered problems in the military chain of command which prompted
Nichols to push for a reorganization of the joints chiefs of staff.
   Three years later, Congress enacted legislation co-authored by
Nichols and then-Sen. Barry Goldwater, R-Ariz., that provided for
the most far-reaching overhaul of the upper levels of the military
services in four decades.
   The legislation, known as the Goldwater-Nichols Defense
Reorganization Act, strengthened the authority of the chairman of
the joint chiefs and the heads of the nation's joint commands while
reducing the power of the individual uniformed service chiefs. It
also made hundreds of changes in military procedures.
   Rep. Tom Bevill, D-Ala., who served with Nichols for nearly 30
years in the Alabama Legislature and the Congress, said Nichols
``took a lot of heat on that legislation from the Pentagon.
   ``But he held the line,'' Bevill said in a statement, ``and in my
judgment, this legislation will prove to be one of the most
important changes made in the armed services in this century.''
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said in a statement that
Nichols ``was a true friend of the military and a respected member
of the House Armed Services Committee for many years. We will miss
his support, his leadership and his friendship.''
   An aide to Alabama Gov. Guy Hunt, a Republican, said the governor
is required under state law to call a special election to replace
Nichols in the 3rd District congressional seat.
   Nichols was born on a farm near Becker, Miss., but grew up in
Sylacauga, Ala. He earned an undergraduate degree in agriculture
from Auburn University in 1939 and a master's degree in 1941. He was
captain of the school's football team.
   During World War II, Nichols was injured in a land mine explosion
while fighting with the Army in Europe in 1944. He underwent 19
operations and eventually lost his left leg from the knee down. He
was awarded the Bronze Star and Purple Heart.
   Nichols returned to Sylacauga after the war and served as
president of Parker Fertilizer Co. and Parker Gin Co. He was elected
to the Alabama House, where he served until his election to the
Alabama Senate in 1963. He was elected to Congress in 1966.
   He is survived by his wife, the former Carolyn Funderburk; two
daughters, Margaret Vlachou of Athens, Greece, and Memorie Mitchell
of Birmingham, Ala.; a son, Flynt Nichols of Dallas; and three
grandchildren.
   Funeral services will be held Thursday afternoon at the First
United Methodist Church in Sylacauga. The Rev. J. Charles Boling,
Nichols' minister and lifelong friend, will officiate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
