<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Trains     12-13 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Trains,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driver Left Engine Moments Before Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One driver involved in the fatal triple-train crash
in south London left his engine moments before the accident to call
signal operators from the side of the tracks, British Rail said
Tuesday.
   Scotland Yard revised the death toll to 33, down from 36, saying
the discrepancy was caused by the mutilated and dismembered state of
some of the bodies. The victims included nine women and 24 men, all
but two of whom died at the scene.
   The state-run railroad has said Monday's crash, which injured 113
people, 32 seriously, probably was caused by a signal-related fault
during modernization of 40-year-old equipment.
   Neither British Rail nor driver Alex McClymont would comment on
news stories that he was reporting the signal lights were flickering
between red, green and yellow and confusing drivers.
   ML Engineering of Plymouth, the company responsible for designing
and supplying the new signaling equipment, said ``the difficulty
appears to be in the wiring to that equipment'' which was British
Rail's responsibility.
   Gordon Pettitt, general manager of British Rail's southern
region, said McClymont acted properly in stopping his train to call
signal operators because his train was not equipped with a two-way
radio.
   ``Therefore, the driver, quite correctly being concerned at what
he had seen, we believe, got down and talked to the signalman at the
earliest possible stage,'' Pettitt said. ``He acted absolutely
correctly.''
   Asked in an TV interview whether the accident could have been
averted if the driver had a radio, Pettitt said: ``I think it's
likely that it may have avoided it and it certainly may have avoided
such serious results.''
   As workers removed the last of the mangled metal and retrieved
personal belongings of the estimated 1,500 people, the Duchess of
York and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher visited the injured, and
Pope John Paul II sent his condolences.
   The stretch of track that had been closed since the disaster
reopened Tuesday night.
   McClymont's train was idling outside the Clapham Junction rail
station, one of Europe's busiest, when a fast-moving passenger train
slammed into it during the morning rush hour, entombing some
passengers in the twisted metal and hurling out others.
   An empty freight train traveling in the opposite direction on the
adjoining track struck the spillover wreckage as well as some
passengers trying to scramble to safety. A fourth train, crowded
with commuters, stopped a few feet short of the wreck, British Rail
said.
   A British Rail spokesman who requested anonymity said McClymont
was still in a state of shock and, like all railroad employees
involved in Monday's accident, did not work Tuesday.
   ``We hope to get his account if he is fit enough to talk to us,''
when the railroad's internal investigation begins Wednesday, the
spokesman said. The driver of the other passenger train, John Rolls,
was killed, he said.
   Transportation Secretary Paul Channon said the lack of radios on
some British Rail trains would be one subject of an independent
inquiry he has ordered into Britain's worst rail accident since 1975.
   McClymont said Monday night he was ``standing at the side of the
track, talking to the signalers on the telephone,'' when he heard a
train approaching.
   ``Then, a split second later, there was a hell of a bang and
everything shot forward,'' he said. ``It was a terrible sight.''
   Pettitt said plans to equip trains with radios might be speeded
up. All new trains are being fitted with radios, but they are being
installed gradually in older trains like the ones involved in the
crash, he said.
   British Rail said it will issue checks for about $3,600 as soon
as possible to families who need financial help for funerals or to
visit hospitalized relatives.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
