<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Prison Fire,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20 Prisoners Dead in Fire at Mexico Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A candle at an altar to Mexico's patron
saint started a pre-dawn fire Tuesday that engulfed a dormitory at a
state prison, killing 20 inmates and injuring six, authorities said.
   Raul Garza, state communications director, said 19 prisoners died
of smoke inhalation or burns at the prison and another died a few
hours later at University Hospital in Monterrey, the capital of
northern Nuevo Leon state.
   The fire broke out at the state penitentiary when a candle at a
small altar to the Virgin of Guadalupe, the patron saint of this
Roman Catholic country, ignited a curtain.
   ``Yesterday was a religious holiday to the Virgin of Guadalupe,
so there were an inordinate amount of altars and candles in the
dormitory,'' said Garza in a telephone interview from Monterrey.
   He said the flames spread to curtains hanging from four-level
bunk beds in a ward housing 116 prisoners.
   ``The mattresses also caught fire, and there was a lot of
smoke,'' Garza said. ``The mattresses were made of a material that
doesn't burn easily, but unfortunately it creates a lot of toxic
smoke.
   ``It was an accident that cannot be attributed to anybody,'' he
said.
   Three prisoners were in University Hospital's intensive care unit
Tuesday, and three others were being treated in the prison hospital,
Garza said.
   The Excelsior news agency quoted an unidentified woman as saying
she was on a conjugal visit with her husband when the fire broke
out. It quoted her as saying the prisoners beat on the doors, but
nobody would let them out.
   Garza denied the report. ``All the prisoners were evacuated
within 10 minutes and moved to other wards,'' he said. The entire
prison houses about 1,800 prisoners.
   The spokesman said the fire was brought under control about half
an hour later and state authorities were investigating.
</TEXT>
