<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Arafat-Arrests     12-13 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arafat-Arrests,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 20 Jews Protesting Arafat Speech</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arafat, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police briefly detained 20 U.S. and European Jews
who were protesting in front of the U.N. building during PLO
chairman Yasser Arafat's speech Tuesday, police said.
   ``They attempted to walk in a silent prayer vigil, wearing prayer
shawls,'' said Howard Jonas, a member of the group. He said police
arrested members of the group without warning and took them away in
vans.
   Jonas said he was not detained because he was walking slightly
behind the group.
   He identified the arrested Americans as Rabbi Avraham Weiss;
David Mann, president of the Board of Jewish Education; Hillel
Jaffee; Bernard Glickman and Glenn Richter, all of New York.
   The 15 Europeans were college students from Switzerland, France
and Italy, he said.
   The 20 were released after several hours, according to a police
officer who refused to identify himself. He said they were detained
for interfering with traffic.
   The Swiss implemented strict security measures for Arafat's
visit, including a ban on demonstrations near the U.N. building.
</TEXT>
