<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Nielsens     12-13 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nielsens,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Night Court' Tops Rankings in Thursday Reappearance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A repeat of ``Night Court'' visiting its old time
period was the highest-rated prime-time show in the Nielsen ratings
last week as NBC's Thursday comedies held a reunion at the top of
the rankings.
   Some of the shine appeared to be off ABC's ``Moonlighting.'' Its
season premiere ranked 13th, compared to last season's premiere at
fifth. ``thirtysomething'' followed in its season premiere and
ranked 29th.
   NBC's entire Thursday night lineup made the top 10. ``Night
Court,'' ``The Cosby Show,'' ``Cheers'' and ``A Different World''
ranked 1, 2, 3, 4. ``L.A. Law'' was ninth.
   The rest of the top 10 were: ``Golden Girls,'' NBC; ``Roseanne,''
ABC; ``60 Minutes,'' CBS; ``Who's the Boss?'' ABC, ``L.A. Law,''
NBC; and ``Empty Nest,'' NBC.
   NBC has moved ``Night Court'' to Wednesday. ``Dear John,'' a new
show, went into the ``Night Court'' slot on Thursday, but has
frequently failed to make the top 10.
   NBC's network premiere of the theatrical film ``Spies Like Us''
landed in 17th place, besting ``Roots: The Gift'' on ABC on Sunday.
``Roots'' ranked 25th.
   NBC won the week ending Dec. 11, its 25th in a row, with an
average, prime-time rating of 15.1. ABC had a 13.2, and CBS 10.7.
   CBS tried to get a bigger sampling for its new comedy ``Murphy
Brown,'' running it with the season premiere of ``Kate & Allie'' on
Sunday night. The special ``Murphy'' ranked 32nd, only slightly
higher than the regularly scheduled episode on Monday at 37th.
   The news race was a virtual tie with less than half a rating
point separating the three broadcasts. The ``CBS Evening News''
edged the others with an 11.2 rating and 20 share. ``ABC World News
Tonight'' had a 10.9 and 20 share. ``NBC Nightly News'' had a 10.8
and 20 share.
   Each rating point represents 904,000 households with television.
The share is a percentage of sets in use.
   The lowest-rated prime-time shows of the week were: ABC's
analysis of President Reagan's news conference, ``Simon & Simon,''
``Murphy's Law,'' ``West 57th,'' ``Dirty Dancing,'' ``TV101,''
``Knightwatch,'' ``Raising Miranda,'' ``The Van Dyke Show'' and
``Annie McGuire.''
   CBS announced Tuesday it was canceling ``Van Dyke'' and ``Raising
Miranda'' and putting ``Dirty Dancing'' on hiatus. Mary Tyler
Moore's ``Annie McGuire'' and ``Simon & Simon'' were also canceled,
but with a possibility of returning in the future. CBS also said it
would move ``TV101'' from Tuesday night to Wednesday night.
   ABC had previously announced it was canceling ``Knightwatch.''
</TEXT>
