<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Arafat-Israel     12-13 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arafat-Israel,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Rejects Arafat Peace Feelers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arafat, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on Tuesday
rejected PLO chief Yasser Arafat's call for peace talks and said
Israel would never accept the PLO as a partner for negotiations.
   Calling the PLO's new image of moderation ``a mirage,'' Shamir
urged the United States not to be duped into thinking the
organization had changed its ways.
   ``We know what hides behind his (Arafat's) words,'' Shamir told a
news conference. ``We know that as they are spoken acts of terror
continue.''
   Arafat's appeal to the U.N. General Assembly in Geneva won praise
from prominent Israeli doves, including the liberal Citizens Rights
Movement, but it failed to sway the center.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, Shamir's political rival from the
center-left Labor Party, remained silent in apparent agreement with
Shamir. He was expected to react in a parliament speech Wednesday.
   Shamir was uncompromising in his rejection of the Palestine
Liberation Organization and Arafat's peace feelers.
   ``We shall not negotiate with the PLO under any conditions nor
recognize it,'' the prime minister said. ``From our point of view,
the PLO is no partner for any peace process.''
   Before Arafat's speech, Israel's state-run radios raised
expectations the U.S. government was poised to recognize the PLO.
They said U.S. officials had received an advance text of Arafat's
speech and had coordinated changes in wording with the PLO.
   In Washington, the State Department relieved some of Israel's
concern by announcing that Arafat's speech fell short of meeting
U.S. conditions for opening a dialogue with the PLO.
   Those conditions are explicit recognition of Israel's right to
exist, unequivocal acceptance of U.N. resolutions 242 and 338 as a
basis for negotiations and renunciation of terrorism.
   The U.N. resolutions accord all nations in the region the right
to exist within secure borders and call for the withdrawal of
Israeli troops from territory occupied in 1967.
   About the time Arafat addressed the United Nations, Israeli
officials announced that a Palestinian in the West Bank had shot and
killed two Israelis after seizing a gun from a Jewish settler. The
Palestinian was then killed by Israeli soldiers.
   Referring to the incident, Shamir said, ``what happened is
another illustration of a decision by the hostile circles in the PLO
to continue their violence.''
   Although Arafat condemned terror ``in all its forms,'' Israeli
officials noted he continued to praise the ``struggle for
liberation,'' a reference to the Palestinan uprising in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip in which 13 Israelis have died.
   They also noted the PLO had not clearly recognized Israel's right
to exist.
   The Citizens Rights movement, which was aligned with the Labor
Party in the recent parliament elections, called on both the U.S.
and Israeli governments to start talks with the PLO.
   ``The Israeli government must now put the PLO to the test and
propose peace negotiations,'' it said, calling on U.S. leaders to
exert pressure by meeting with Arafat.
   Similar views were expressed by doves in the Labor Party itself.
   ``One has to be blind not to see that the moderate stream is
becoming the dominant one in the PLO,'' Labor parliament member Lova
Eliav said on Israel television.
   Amiram Goldblum of the Peace Now movement said in an interview
that the PLO's new moderation was having an impact. He said 30 to 35
members of Israel's 120-seat parliament now supported a favorable
response to Arafat's peace initiative.
   Palestinian moderates here welcomed Arafat's speech.
   Daoud Kuttab, a journalist who listened to the speech with
several dozen other Palestinian intellectuals at a theater in Arab
east Jerusalem, said Israel had ``no more excuses'' for avoiding
talks with the PLO.
   He defended Arafat's refusal to extend explicit recognition of
Israel, saying this would mean recognizing Israel with specific
borders.
   ``Spelling out such specific boundaries could be detrimental to
negotiations,'' Kuttab said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
