<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HamadiTrial     12-13 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi Trial,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Asks Syrian President To Testify At Hamadi Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for confessed TWA
hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi on Tuesday asked the court to summon
Syria's president to testify at the trial.
   President Hafez Assad could shed light on the June 1985 hijacking
of the TWA Athens-to-Rome flight that was diverted to Beirut, where
hostages were released and sent to Damascus, the Syrian capital,
said Gabriele Steck-Bromme.
   Mrs. Steck-Bromme also asked the court to summon Nabih Berri,
Lebanon's Justice Minister and leader of the Shiite Amal militia,
who helped negotiate the release of passengers.
   Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger made no immediate ruling on Mrs.
Steck-Bromme's motion.
   During the 17-day ordeal, 39 Americans were held hostage and U.S.
Navy diver Robert Stethem was shot and killed. Hamadi, a Lebanese
Shiite Moslem who is charged with air piracy and murder, admits he
was one of the hijackers, but denies he shot Stethem.
   Mrs. Steck-Bromme also said U.S. authorities reneged on their
promise not to prosecute the hijackers if the hostages were released
from the seized plane. She said the U.S. officials made the pledge
before the American hostages were handed over to Red Cross officials
and sent to Damascus. The U.S. government has denied that any deals
were made.
   After Mrs. Steck-Bromme's motion, a journalist called by the
court to testify as a Middle East expert said American authorities
made such a promise but did not keep it.
   West Germany last year rejected a U.S. request for Hamadi's
extradition, but much of the prosecution's case against Hamadi is
based on evidence collected by U.S. authorities and on testimony
from American witnesses.
   Adel Elias, 50, a Middle East correspondent for the West German
news magazine Der Spiegel, testified that Berri had told him about
U.S. promises tied to the release of the Americans.
   Elias, a Lebanese-born journalist who is now a West German
citizen, also described the difficult conditions in which poor
Shiite families live in west Beirut, where Hamadi was raised.
   Mrs. Steck-Bromme maintains Berri could testify about the aim of
the hijackers, who had demanded the release of more than 700 Arab
prisoners held in Israel. Shortly after the end of the hijacking,
Israel freed some of the prisoners but said their release was not
linked to the air piracy.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport in January 1987 after
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
</TEXT>
