<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ApolloAnniversary     12-13 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Apollo Anniversary,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Astronauts Remember Historic Apollo 8 Mission 20 Years Ago</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the three Apollo 8 astronauts reminisced
Tuesday about their mission around the moon 20 years ago this month
_ a feat they said helped lift the nation out of despair at a trying
time in its history.
   ``You have to remember the time span of when Apollo 8 went up,
which was the end of 1968 ... not a very stellar year here in this
country,'' James Lovell, who served as command module pilot,
recalled at the Museum of Science and Industry. The spacecraft's
command module is on loan there from the National Air and Space
Museum in Washington.
   ``Bobby Kennedy was assasinated, Martin Luther King ... the
Vietnam war was going on, the Democrtaic convention in Chicago ...
we had all sorts of riots _ and it was sort of a down year,'' Lovell
added.
   ``It was some sort of project or an achievement that everybody
could look up to ... it was a goal that you could go outside and see
the moon and know that the United States had finally put a
spacecraft around the moon ...
   ``It couldn't have happened at a better time,'' he said.
   Joining Lovell at the museum was Frank Borman, the Apollo 8
commander. The third astronaut on the mission was William Anders.
   Apollo 8 is perhaps best remembered for footage broadcast
internationally of the three astronauts reading passages from the
biblical book of Genesis on Christmas Eve 1968, with a stunning view
of the Earth from 250,000 miles away.
   ``Up to that point it was the largest audience that had ever
listened to a human voice,'' Lovell recalled
   The mission, launched Dec. 21, 1968, hurled the three astronauts
25,000 miles an hour, a speed no human had endured. During the
six-day space flight _ then the longest on record _ the men circled
the moon 10 times, photographing potential sites for future Apollo
landings there.
   The Apollo 11 mission _ the first to put a man on the moon _
landed six months later, on July 20, 1969.
   Borman recalled the Apollo program as generating ``almost a
nationalistic fervor'' that faded as space flights became blase.
   Borman, 60, left the space program in 1970 and took the helm at
Eastern Airlines, where he served as chairman for 11 years until his
resignation in 1986. He currently serves as vice chairman at Texas
Air.
   Lovell, also 60, resigned from the space program in 1973 and
currently serves as executive vice president at Centel Business
Systems in Chicago.
   ``Apollo 8, I think, will always be the single most highlight of
my professional life,'' Borman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0172 </DOCNO>
