<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BaseClosings     12-13 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Base Closings,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Expecting Two-Dozen Military Bases To Get Ax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is expecting a Pentagon commission to
recommend that about 24 military bases be closed, according to House
and Senate aides who were briefed Tuesday on what to do if a base in
their area gets the ax.
   Fifty anxious congressional staff members from Northeast and
Midwest states met for two hours to be briefed by Reagan
administration officials and to swap rumors about which bases might
be declared obsolete.
   The aides were told by officials of the Northeast-Midwest Senate
Coalition and its counterpart group in the House that they likely
will receive the list of recommended base closings on Dec. 30 _ the
Friday kicking off New Year's weekend.
   While the briefing was closed to reporters, participants said the
``working figure'' for the expected number of bases on the list was
24. That estimate was provided at the briefing by Robert Bayer of
the Senate Armed Services Committee staff.
   The Defense Secretary's Commission on Base Realignment and
Closure has kept quiet about its deliberations, refusing even a
request by 17 senators to learn whether it would take geographic
considerations into account.
   The commission was created from legislation designed to save the
government up to $5 billion per year by shutting down bases deemed
no longer useful.
   Northeast and Midwest lawmakers have urged the commission to
consider ``regional inequities'' as it draws up its list of unneeded
bases. At the briefing, the Northeast-Midwest Congressional
Coalition distributed charts and tables showing Northeast and
Midwest states getting less than their fair share of defense dollars.
   ``We wish to prevent the further entrenchment of regional
inequities stemming from the location of existing military
facilities,'' said an Oct. 25 letter to the commission from Sens.
John Heinz, R-Pa., Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., and 15 other
senators.
   But all the the commission would say in reply was that it has
developed five factors to consider each base's value to the
military, and that environmental and economic factors also would be
weighed.
   House and Senate staffs have focused their attention on large
bases. The Congressional Research Service recently obtained from the
Defense Department a list of all bases employing 100 people or more
to help members prepare for Dec. 30.
   But Bayer said Tuesday the commission also may opt to sell off
some bases' high-value properties while leaving the facility's
overall mission intact _ a move that would come under the heading of
base ``realignment.''
   John Lynch, associate director of the Defense Department's Office
of Economic Adjustment, said communities that lose bases might be
advised to quickly mobilize private sector and government support
rather than trying to contest the decision.
   ``Often, the wrong course may be to fight,'' Lynch said. He said
government grants are available to help communities adjust to losing
a base.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci will have until Jan. 15 to
accept or reject the commission's list.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0173 </DOCNO>
