<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Weather-Survivor     12-13 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weather-Survivor,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>82-Year-Old Woman Survives 2{ Hours In Icy Creek</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARDON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 82-year-old, legally blind woman who said
she spent 2{ hours in an icy creek after falling down a cliff while
feeding birds in 10-degree weather was hospitalized in fair
condition Tuesday.
   Jesse Norton was wearing several layers of clothing, boots and
gloves which helped her survive, Geauga Hospital spokeswoman Sharon
Kilpatrick said.
   Ms. Kilpatrick said Ms. Norton's body temperature was 81.9
degrees when she was admitted to the hospital Monday after being
pulled to safety by a rescue crew.
   Warm intravenous fluids restored Ms. Norton's body temperature
and she was cognizant Tuesday afternoon but in a special care unit
and unble to talk on the telephone, Ms. Kilpatrick said.
   Ms. Norton, of Chardon, apparently was feeding birds when she
fell down a 25-foot cliff into a creek that feeds into the Chagrin
River, said Laura Johnson of Chardon, a home health aide who checks
on Ms. Norton weekly.
   Ms. Johnson said Ms. Norton was legally blind and told her she
had been in the water 2{ hours.
   ``Jesse's a pretty strong woman,'' said Ms. Johnson, 25, who is
employed by the Visiting Nurse Service of Chardon.
   When she went to Ms. Norton's house and realized the woman had
tumbled down the cliff, Ms. Johnson called her supervisor, Laurie
Bender.
   ``Knowing this woman personally, it doesn't surprise me (she
survived),'' Ms. Bender said. ``She is very active.''
   Ms. Johnson said after calling Ms. Bender she grabbed a robe, rug
and blanket to wrap up the woman, and slid back down the hill. She
said she pulled Ms. Norton from the water and waited with her for
help.
   ``We just cuddled up and kept warm,'' said Ms. Johnson, adding
Ms. Norton was in and out of consciousness. She recalled telling Ms.
Norton, ``She was going to be all right and think positive and help
would be here soon. Actually, I was trying to keep her calm.''
   Ms. Johnson began rubbing the woman's body to warm her.
   Ms. Johnson said her family's involvement in emergency services
work helped prepare her. ``All my relatives belong to a fire
department and this is in my blood. (With such experience) you don't
show fear,'' she said.
</TEXT>
