<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Transition-Organization     12-13 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transition-Organization,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Team Gathering, Analyzing Information From Reagan Agencies</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush's designated Cabinet
officers are supervising teams of people mapping out strategy for
the new administration, aides said Tuesday.
   Meanwhile, White House Chief of Staff Kenneth Duberstein was
given the names of transition aides who will be contacting various
government agencies to collect information about their operations.
   The information-gathering and review process at the transition
office will be broken into two parts, transition officials said in a
statement.
   The first phase involves a group of people known as Transition
Office Contacts, or TOCs, who are responsible for departments or
agencies. For example, six people directed by James A. Baker III,
the designated secretary of state, are the contacts for the State
Department.
   The TOCs ``gather and analyze the information provided by the
particular department (in books and briefings) and then prepare the
material to be used in the second phase of the transition process by
the Cabinet officer-designate,'' the statement said.
   The second phase, headed by designated Cabinet officers such as
Baker and Robert Mosbacher, the appointed commerce secretary, are to
continue the information-gathering but also ``facilitate hands-on
administration of the department after the inauguration and Senate
confirmation.''
   The transition has notified the White House and the General
Services Administration, the government's housekeeping agency, of
the process.
   The GSA is handling logistics for the transition, which is
operating on a budget of about $3.5 million.
</TEXT>
