<HEAD>INS Chief Cites Abuses, Backlogs for Changing Nicaraguan Asylum
Process</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: `The proposals,' to include element
of possible denials of work permits; INSERTS 4 grafs of reax from
spokesmen from Nicaraguan groups in Miami after 13th graf, `The
most.' Picks up 14th graf pvs, `Internal INS'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. immigration commissioner Alan Nelson on
Tuesday said his agency's proposals to conduct swift reviews of
asylum applications from thousands of Nicaraguans are necessary to
clear up a huge backlog and stem abuses.
   The proposals, if implemented in their entirety, could result in
denials of work permits to many asylum-seekers, detention and
eventual deportation.
   ``The game plan is to devote additional resources to deal with
the asylum backlog'' involving Nicaraguans and other Central
Americans, Nelson, chief of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service, said in an interview.
   In Harlingen, Texas, nearly 12,000 Nicaraguans crossing the
border illegally have filed applications since June seeking asylum
in the United States, claiming they have been persecuted in their
home country.
   Under a July 1987 directive signed by then-Attorney General Edwin
Meese III, once Nicaraguans file asylum applications it is virtually
automatic that they are granted work permits in the United States
while their applications are pending.
   Meese's order, hailed by Nicaraguans in the United States, had
the effect of liberalizing political asylum policy for Nicaraguans
who feared persecution if they returned to their homeland.
   A clarification of the Meese order was sent this month to INS
field offices saying the Meese memorandum doesn't require automatic
granting of work authorization to Nicaraguan asylum applicants whose
claims are deemed frivolous.
   Nelson said that in Harlingen, salesmen are offering phony
packets of asylum documents to Nicaraguans and other Central
Americans seeking refuge in the United States.
   ``We have to have an orderly immigration system,'' Nelson said.
``We want those with legitimate claims to immigrate and get them
approved, but we must avoid abuses, and we're seeing evidence of
that in south Texas.''
   INS has devoted few resources to reviewing the Nicaraguans'
asylum applications, but with a current nationwide backlog of 22,000
applicants and increases continuing, INS' approach is about to
change.
   Nelson said half a dozen INS employees were being sent to Texas
to deal with the backlog of asylum applications and that some INS
workers in Los Angeles were being diverted to handle the backlog
there.
   ``After the first of the year, we'll likely add more to these
three areas to cut the backlog,'' Nelson said.
   The most recent asylum applications will be reviewed first and
``we'll work our way back to the older applications,'' on a last-in,
first-out basis, Nelson said. The speeded-up asylum reviews also
would apply to other Central Americans seeking refuge in the United
States.
   Canceling work permits issued to Nicaraguans or not issuing work
permits to new asylum applicants won't stop the influx of
Nicaraguans coming into the United States, said Roberto Arguello,
chairman of the public relations committee of the Nicaraguan
American Bankers Association in Miami.
   ``Nicaraguans would rather work under the worst kind of
conditions imaginable than to face the harsh realities that the
Sandinista government has imposed over them,'' Arguello said.
   Arguello said he anticipates that by the summer over 1,000
Nicaraguans a week will be coming to Miami, with the current level
at more than 400 a week, including people ``from all walks of life.
We have some Nicaraguans coming to Miami who cannot even read
Spanish.''
   The INS steps are ``not going to stop people from coming,''
predicted Maritza Herrera, executive director of the Nicaraguan
American Foundation in Miami. ``They come here and they're going to
stay in the underground economy, underpaid.''
   Internal INS documents obtained by The Associated Press show the
agency is contemplating a series of proposals which, if implemented,
could result in many Nicaraguans being detained promptly and
ultimately deported once their asylum claims are rejected.
   Nelson is to meet this week with Associate Attorney General
Francis Keating to go over various proposals, which the INS
commissioner said have already been discussed with the State
Department. Nelson refused to say specfically whether the proposals
had been discussed with the White House, but he added that ``these
things don't happen in a vacuum.''
   Nelson said the internal documents were draft proposals that were
still in the discussion stage. They include:
   _Having the majority of asylum applicants in Harlingen remain
there while INS makes a determination whether their applications are
frivolous.
   _Applicants denied asylum would immediately be served with court
orders and enter the deportation process.
   _Ensuring ``the effective utilization of all possible detention
capacity'' without adversely affecting the INS's criminal alien
program or detention of Mariel Cuban detainees. INS detention
facilities currently are crowded, and INS spokesman Duke Austin
downplayed the idea that substantial numbers of Nicaraguans would be
placed in detention facilities while awaiting final disposition of
deportation proceedings.
   _Instituting a fee system for asylum requests and work
authorization requests and use the funds to help clear up the asylum
case backlog.
</TEXT>
