<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LongRiders     12-13 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Long Riders,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Straphangers Marathon Ends with Subway Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY33</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three subway buffs completed their version of
what they called the longest subway ride in American history
Tuesday, a 29-hour, 47-minute marathon through each of the city's
466 stations.
   ``We're here, grubby but triumphant,'' said Richard Temple,
expedition leader. ``And all on one token. We never left the
system!''
   For $1, the three young men got a chance to view the sunrise over
Queens, taste pastry under Columbus Circle and enter a squalid
ladies' room in Coney Island.
   Seizing an opportunity afforded by the opening of three new
subway stations _ the first in 20 years _ the trio claimed to be the
first people to ride through every station of the enlarged system.
   Why did they do it?
   ``Because it's there,'' Temple said. ``It's something I've always
wanted to do, being something of a subway junkie.''
   Because of subway delays, the three friends _ Temple, 28, Phil
Vanner, 25, and Tom Murphy, 29 _ finished almost three hours behind
schedule.
   Despite the subway's well-publicized woes, the travelers'
assessment was favorable, beginning with a view of the sun rising
from the elevated J train Monday, and ending Tuesday morning with a
tasty eclair purchased at a shop in Manhattan's Columbus Circle
station. They even found roses awaiting them at the finish, a gift
from some Transit Authority employees.
   They said they went 15 hours before meeting their first
panhandler, and encountered just four in all. Only two cars were
significantly marked by graffiti.
   The riders took turns catnapping, and bought some snacks at shops
in stations. Although they brought along books and a tape player,
``we mostly looked out the window and relaxed,'' Temple said.
   The trio said the low point of their trip came Monday night on
the N line to Coney Island, a one-hour, 45-minute ordeal on an
unheated train that often slowed to a crawl behind a trash
collection train.
   ``We were questioning our sanity.'' recalled Vanner.
   When the trip began at 6:13 a.m. Monday at the Jamaica-Van Wyck
station, the riders expected to be on the rails for 27 hours. But
various mixups _ including a rerouting during rush hour on Tuesday
morning _ forced them to improvise.
   With 466 stations and 232 miles of track, New York City's subway
system is easily the nation's largest, and by some measures _
including the number of cars and stations _ the world's largest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
