<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DC-NewYear's     12-13 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DC-New Year's,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Withdraws City Support For New Year's Celebration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry Jr. has canceled the city
government's participation in the annual New Year's Eve celebration
because of concerns over crime and cost, but organizers said it will
go on under private sponsorship.
   Officials of the Old Post Office Pavilion, a complex of
restaurants and shops that was focus for the party, said they
learned last month that Barry planned to call off the mass event.
But they said Tuesday they will have their own party with big band
music, dancing and other festivities targeted for the 35-45 age
group.
   ``We feel that it's an important tradition in Washington,'' said
Christine Masterson, Pavilion marketing director.
   Each year that event attracted revelers to downtown Washington,
including an estimated 100,000 poeple last year.
   On Monday, Barry withdrew city support for the celebration,
citing the city's $150 million budget deficit and a drug and crime
wave that has pushed the capital's homicide total to a record 347
this year.
   In a radio interview, Barry said canceling the event will save
little money. But, he said, ``I think we're in serious times now,
with the crime being what it is and the drug epidemic. It's no time
to celebrate, it's a time to work hard and to pray.''
   The cancelation spells the end for Barry's ambitious hopes for
the New Year's celebration, which began in 1983.
   Barry boasted in 1986 that it would surpass New York City's
celebration in Times Square, which attracts about 1 million people,
and become a major tourist attraction in the revitalized
Pennsylvania Avenue corridor between the White House and the Capitol.
   But a slaying during the 1986 celebration, along with 15 arrests
and reports of fighting and bottle throwing by youths, led Barry to
make the entertainment more family-oriented.
   In the past two years, the city moved to ensure safety at the
celebration by limiting alcohol sales, adding police protection and
changing the musical program.
</TEXT>
