<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Arafat-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0666 12-13 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arafat-Reax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0666,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arabs See Progress in Arafat's Speech</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Arafat, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Egyptian comment, Sweden's
role, other detail. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians said Tuesday they saw progress
in Yasser Arafat's speech to the United Nations but expressed doubt
that Israel would accept the PLO peace plan.
   Israeli officials dismissed the appeal, and U.S. officials said
his speech did not meet conditions Washington has set for dealing
with Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel said: ``We know what
hides behind his words. We know that as they are spoken acts of
terror continue.''
   Abdul-Jawad Saleh, deported mayor of the West Bank town of El
Bireh, said: ``Even if Arafat comes out and writes Shamir a letter
saying `I recognize the state of Israel, I condemn terrorism, I stop
terrorism,' Shamir would say `Go to hell.'''
   Saleh, who lives in Amman, was among many Palestinians who
listened to a live radio broadcast of the PLO chairman's speech
Tuesday to a special session of the U.N. General Assembly in Geneva.
Television stations in Egypt, Kuwait, Qatar and Abu Dhabi also
carried the address live.
   Arafat urged Israel to join U.N.-sponsored peace talks intended
to produce a peace settlement based on security for all nations of
the region, including Israel and a Palestinian state.
   King Hussein of Jordan, visiting Paris, said on French
television: ``Chairman Arafat has responded to every demand of the
United States. I know what was requested of the PLO as I was
personally involved in the past.''
   The United States has set three conditions for a dialogue with
the PLO: that it clearly recognize Israel's right to exist, renounce
terrorism and accept U.N. resolutions that give all nations of the
region the right to exist within secure borders.
   U.S. officials said Arafat's speech was interesting but did not
meet the conditions.
   In Washington, Swedish Embassy spokesman Lars Romert said his
country served as a ``messenger'' between the U.S. government and
PLO. He said the Palestinians sought clarification of American
conditions for official dealings.
   Esmat Abdel-Meguid, foreign minister of Egypt, followed Arafat to
the podium in Geneva and said: ``I call on Israel ... to respond to
this positive Palestinian proposal to reach a just and lasting
peace.''
   Egypt signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1979, the only Arab
nation to have done so. Jordan and Egypt have been essential
elements in virtually every U.S. peace proposal since Israel was
born in war 40 years ago.
   Rami Khoury, a Jordanian journalist and publisher, said of
Arafat's speech: ``I think its very positive and ... historic. Its
really the first time ... in a practical way that the PLO's
acceptance of coexistence and the two-state solution has been taken
to the next level of a practical series of steps.''
   Khoury said Israel, the United States and some European countries
demanding specific conditions from the PLO ``have so painted
themselves into a corner that when Arafat offers to make peace, they
say, `No, you've got to say the words in this order.'''
   Many Palestinians said they oppose further concessions until the
PLO gets something in return from Israel and the United States.
   ``What more do they want from us?'' asked Khalid Saadi, a
38-year-old Amman businessman. ``Recognition cannot come from one
side. Israel has to recognize the Palestinian state and the
Palestinian people.''
   Mohammed Hamdam, a physician, said: ``We call on the whole world
to understand that what was asked of the PLO was given.''
</TEXT>
