<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Honoraria 1stLd-Writethru a0689 12-13 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honoraria, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0689,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Will Congress Trade Private Perks For Government Paychecks?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to CORRECT byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of Congress' most visible and
controversial perks _ the $1,000 breakfast, the $2,000 lunch and the
$10,000 all-expenses-paid tours of defense plants _ came under fire
Tuesday from a presidential commission.
   The panel, while recommending 50 percent pay increases for top
federal officials, suggested that members of the House and Senate
honor their part of the bargain by dumping their honoraria.
   The commission said members of Congress should be paid $135,000
instead of $89,500, but they should give up the speaking and writing
fees that brought in a record $9.8 million in 1987, up 30 percent
over 1986.
   Unlike bureaucrats and judges, members of Congress are free to
use their positions to collect speaking fees, most often from lobby
groups and trade associations with a stake in a member's votes in
committee or on the floor.
   ``The potential for abuse or the appearance of abuse is obvious
to the public,'' the salary commission said in a report to President
Reagan. ``The only principled argument that can be made for the
practice of accepting honoraria is that official salaries are too
low.''
   This put the commission in line with longtime honoraria critics
like Fred Wertheimer, president of Common Cause, the self-styled
citizens lobby.
   ``The growing practice of accepting honoraria from special
interests raises intolerable conflicts of interest and gravely
undermines the integrity of Congress and the public trust in
government,'' Wertheimer said Tuesday.
   There is no limit on how much a member can make through
honoraria. The 1987 Capitol Hill champion, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski,
the Illinois Democrat who heads the tax-writing Ways and Means
Committee, pulled in $245,000.
   There are limits, however, on how much a member can keep. The
Senate has a limit amounting to 40 percent of official salary, or
$35,800. The House's limit is 30 percent of salary, or $26,850.
There is a $2,000 cap on a single honoraria payment.
   To keep within the limit, Rostenkowski gave $219,156 of his 1987
honoraria earnings to various charities, leaving $25,844 for
himself. The Senate's top honoraria earner in 1987, Minority Leader
Bob Dole, R-Kan., made $106,050 on the speaking circuit, gave
$80,000 to charity and kept $26,050 for himself, neary $10,000 less
than he could have kept.
   Neither man nor any of their colleagues would suffer an earnings
cut under the commission's plan. A senator now keeping honoraria to
the limit would be $9,700 ahead of the current system if the pay
goes to $135,000. A House member at the limit would end up $18,650
ahead.
   According to financial disclosure statements, 87 senators
received $3.1 million in honoraria in 1987, keeping $2.3 million, or
nearly 74 percent. In the House, 390 of the 435 members shared $6.67
million and kept about 78 percent of it _ $5.24 million.
   Rostenkowski, Dole and Rep. Bill Gray, D-Pa., were the only
lawmakers in the six-figure honoraria league. The average take among
the 87 senators was $36,069, with an average of $9,433 going to
charity. The average House member who accepted speaking fees took in
$17,122, giving $3,686 to charity.
   The money doesn't flow equally to members or have much apparent
relevance to speaking ability.
   Committee and subcommittee chairmen, who play pivotal roles in
shaping legislation, are far more popular than back-benchers when a
trade association is looking for someone to address a luncheon.
   A lawmaker's committee assignments frequently can be divined from
a list of his or her honoraria sources: banks hire members of the
banking committees; defense contractors favor defense committee
members for their speakers.
   The defense industry has also come up with the multi-honorarium
junket. Pentagon contractors get together and fly a group of
lawmakers to California, where they are housed and fed and take
turns touring five plants and making speeches at $2,000 a pop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
