<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaRouche 1stLd-Writethru a0657 12-13 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,740</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS grafs 7-9 ``Another defense'' to update</NOTE>
<HEAD>Tax Lawyer Says He Advised LaRouche Not To File</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tax lawyer testified Tuesday he advised
political extremist Lyndon H. LaRouche Jr. not to file federal
returns because he had no income, and that he was so uncaring about
his basic needs that he wore baggy suits and worn-out shoes.
   The lawyer, Mayer Morganroth of New York and Southfield, Mich.,
told a federal jury that LaRouche's publishers and political
supporters provided his food, clothing, housing and other
necessities to enable him to conduct research, write articles and
make speeches promoting his various causes.
   Morganroth said he believed the goods and services did not
represent income for LaRouche but were intended to benefit the
publishers and other LaRouche organizations, from whom LaRouche
``didn't get paid anything.''
   The lawyer said he gave his view of LaRouche's tax liability at a
1979 meeting with LaRouche and his chief accountant, Gerald Doherty,
and that his position was endorsed at a December, 1984, meeting with
Harold Dubrowsky, a Detroit lawyer for the prominent accounting firm
of Grant Thornton.
   At the second meeting, which LaRouche reportedly did not attend,
Morganroth quoted Dubrowsky as saying it was ``a totally defensible
position'' to say that LaRouche received no income and need not file
tax returns.
   Morganroth was a key witness called by defense attorneys to
testify on the 13th day of LaRouche's trial in U.S. District Court
on tax and mail fraud conspiracy charges.
   Another defense witness, Thomas Seay of Washington, who conducted
a year-long review of LaRouche financial records for the defense
team, said LaRouche was an employee of all the organizations under
his control but did not receive any taxable income. Seay agreed that
LaRouche and was not required to file any federal income tax returns.
   Under questioning by prosecutors, Seay conceded that he did not
have any access to financial records prior to July 1986 and which
were seized by federal agents who raided LaRouche's Leesburg, Va.,
headquarters in October, 1986.
   Seay also acknowledged under questioning that he did not know for
sure whether LaRouche received a minimum $1,080 in income, which
requires filing tax returns.
   LaRouche is charged with conspiring to defraud the Internal
Revenue Service by failing to file returns for any tax year since
1978 and having all his personal expenses paid by various
corporations he controls.
   In addition, LaRouche and six associates are charged with mail
fraud and conspiracy for allegedly raising more than $30 million in
loans from supporters that they never intended to repay.
   If convicted of all 13 counts against him, LaRouche faces a
maximum penalty of 65 years in prison and fines totaling $3.25
million.
   Morganroth testified he didn't know who was paying LaRouche's
expenses but that ``it was assumed wherever he went he was provided
a roof and security so he could write and do research for his
writings.''
   Said Morganroth: ``His clothes were quite minimal. His shoes were
worn down. The suits he had on were baggy, like someone had thrown
them away. His teeth needed work on them. It was obvious he didn't
care for his daily needs.''
   The witness said he had not received even half of the estimated
$500,000 in legal fees he had charged the LaRouche organization for
his tax advice, and had written off $125,000 as a bad debt.
   Asked if he was a LaRouche supporter, Morganroth replied: ``Far
from it.''
   Another defense witness who testified Tuesday was Richard Morris,
a San Francisco corporate lawyer and former aide to William P. Clark
when Clark was deputy secretary of state, White House national
security adviser and Interior secretary during President Reagan's
first term.
   At the White House in 1982-1983, Morris said, he had numerous
conversations with LaRouche supporters who passed along their
concerns about Reagan's Star Wars plan for a space-based missile
defense system, terrorism in West Germany, Third World debt and
intelligence matters regarding the Soviet Union.
   Morris said he forwarded any credible information from LaRouche
supporters to specialists on the National Security Council staff.
But he heeded orders from U.S. intelligence agencies and refused to
give any information to LaRouche operatives in return.
   Morris said his contacts in the CIA and the Defense Intelligence
Agency warned him that ``LaRouche was a socialist, fascist,
communist, a member of the KGB and even a Democrat.'' But Morris
said that then and now he believed LaRouche supporters ``were acting
in good faith and in the best interests of the United States as they
saw it.''
</TEXT>
