<DOCNO> AP881213-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 2030EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FSLIC-Malpractice     12-13 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FSLIC-Malpractice,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Law Firm to Pay FSLIC $35 Million in Malpractice
Judgment</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Mmahat is cq throughout</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal district court in New Orleans has
awarded the fund that insures savings institutions a $35 million
malpractice judgment against a law firm, regulators said Tuesday.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates federally
insured S&Ls, said the court awarded the judgment to the Federal
Savings and Loan Insurance Corp. against John Mmahat and his firm,
Mmahat and Duffy.
   Based on improper advice from Mmahat's firm, the Gulf Federal
Savings Bank, Metairie, La., repeatedly granted loans in excess of
bank board limits, the agency alleged.
   Mmahat was both chairman and majority shareholder of the bank and
head of the law firm, the bank board said. It said the firm
collected more than $5 million in legal fees from the bank between
1982 and 1985. The institution was placed into receivership in
November 1986.
   The bank board said the federal court award on Friday was one of
the largest malpractice verdicts on record.
</TEXT>
