<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     12-13 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Says Its Own Jets Bombed Kandahar</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Najib, one name, is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government
now says its own warplanes, not Pakistan's, dropped the bombs last
weekend that killed 24 people in Kandahar province, Western
diplomats reported Tuesday.
   The initial Kabul radio report directed suspicion at Pakistan by
saying low-flying aircraft approached the southern province from the
east, but the diplomats said a later report admitted the Afghan air
force dropped the bombs.
   ``In a burst of unexplained candor, Soviet and regime media have
announced the attacks by Afghan aircraft of civilian targets in
Kandahar and ... announced an attempted takeover of the 2nd Corps
headquarters, Nov. 21, by disaffected officers,'' one of the
diplomats said. All spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Official reports of the attempted takeover said several renegade
military officers led 400 ``extremists,'' presumably a reference to
guerrillas, into the corps headquarters but the invaders were
repulsed.
   ``Whether or not these public statements of events, which would
have received much less notice otherwise, are intended to portray
the PDPA and regime as incompetent, they certainly are accomplishing
that end,'' the diplomat said.
   President Najib of Afghanistan is head of Afghanistan's Communist
Party, called the People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan, or PDPA.
There have been reports the Kremlin is easing him out.
   Diplomats corroborated guerrilla claims that portions of a
strategic highway linking the Afghan capital to Pakistan were closed.
   The road is a major route for food convoys to Kabul and the
eastern city of Jalalabad. Diplomats reported heavy fighting and
said ``many army wounded'' had been taken to Kabul.
   Guerrillas have stopped all vehicle traffic near Sarobi, 30 miles
east of Kabul, and travelers ``must walk for a number of hours
before finding transporation to continue their journey,'' a diplomat
said.
   Moslem insurgents began fighting in Afghanistan after a Communist
coup in April 1978, and Soviet military forces entered the country
in December 1979.
   An estimated 115,000 Red Army soldiers were in Afghanistan when a
U.N.-mediated agreement to withdraw them was signed April 14 in
Geneva. About half have been pulled out and all are to be gone by
Feb. 15, 1989.
   At least 3 million Afghan refugees live in towns and refugee
camps just inside the Pakistani border, which the guerrillas use as
bases and supply points. The rebels are supported by Pakistan and
the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
