<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2dLd-Writethru a0741 12-13 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2d Ld - Writethru, a0741,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Kills Settler, Fires on Army Patrol</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to CORRECT that attack outside Berakha,
not in Burin, ADD nature of soldier's wound, claims by settlers;
picks up 10th pvs `Soldiers in'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERAKHA, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian shepherd crushed
a Jewish settler's skull with a rock Tuesday, grabbed his rifle and
fired on an army patrol, killing a soldier before other troopers
killed him, the army reported.
   Two soldiers were wounded, the army spokesman's office said.
   The deaths of the settler and soldier bring to 13 the number of
Israelis killed since a rebellion began Dec. 8, 1987, among the 1.5
million Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. At
least 323 Palestinians have been slain and more than 7,000 wounded.
   Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, Israel's West Bank commander, said the
attack occurred near near Berakha, a hilltop Jewish settlement two
miles south of Nablus. It took place shortly before PLO chairman
Yasser Arafat addressed the U.N. General Assembly in Geneva and
called for peace with Israel.
   Settlers at Berakha said Palestinians from Burin, the nearby
village where the assailant lived, had uprooted trees and planted
their own crops on settlement land.
   Mitzna told reporters the shepherd's family was involved in a
land dispute with the settlement, but whether that prompted the
attack was not clear.
   ``In the afternoon, an Israeli resident of Berakha was brutally
murdered by an Arab shepherd,'' Mitzna said. ``The shepherd crushed
the Israeli's head with a stone, then took his M-16 and ambushed a
military patrol.
   ``This shepherd is known to us. In the past, members of his
family sabotaged some tractors and plows in the settlement.''
   The 70,000 Jews who occupy 131 settlements in the West Bank and
Gaza are allowed to carry weapons for protection.
   Mitzna said the Palestinian killed the driver of a patrol jeep
and wounded an Israeli officer in the leg, and the army spokesman
said another soldier was slightly wounded.
   Soldiers in the jeep returned the fire, killing the shepherd,
Mitzna said. Arab sources said he was Hamdan Najjar, 25, and often
grazed his flock near Berakha.
   The settler, identifed as Yaakov Pereg, 33, was on routine patrol
outside the settlement, Mitzna said. Berakha, founded in 1981, is
home to about 20 religiously observant Jewish families.
   Soldiers put a curfew on Burin and searched the area.
   Mitzna and Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, the army chief of staff, met
with settlement leaders Tuesday night. The settlers demanded that
Palestinian stone-throwers be deported from the occupied territories.
   Villagers said Jewish settlers entered schools in Burin earlier
in the day, ordering teachers and students to leave. A high school
principal was beaten, the residents said.
   Four Palestinians were wounded in confrontations elsewhere in the
West Bank, including a 13-year-old boy shot in the chest and right
arm at the Fara refugee camp near Nablus, hospital officials said.
   Soldiers imposed a curfew on the entire Gaza Strip, shouting
through megaphones they would fire on those who violated the order
confining all 650,000 Palestinians to their homes, residents
reported.
   The round-the-clock curfew was imposed in an effort to prevent
anti-Israeli violence after Arafat's address in Geneva.
   An Associated Press reporter taken on a tour of Gaza by the army
saw smoldering tires and watched patrols weave in and out of narrow
alleys hunting curfew violators. Two outlawed Palestinian flags
attached to helium balloons floated over Gaza City.
   Residents of the city went onto their balconies after Arafat
spoke. They exploded fireworks and emitted the shrieks and
ululations associated with Arab celebrations.
   In Nablus, West Bank Palestinians filled the streets and blared
recordings of the speech taped from Arabic radio stations. Some
burned tires and chanted nationalist songs while masked youths
danced, waving balloons and pictures of the Palestine Liberation
Organization chairman.
   In Jerusalem, police used tear gas to disperse Palestinian
elementary school children who blocked the entrance to their school
with rocks and raised Palestinian flags, Israel's national news
agency Itim reported. It said a similar event occurred near the
walled old city.
   Three Arab schools in the city were ordered closed until Sunday,
affecting over 2,000 students.
</TEXT>
