<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-13 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold In East Kills 5 in New York, Winds High in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The cold front in the northeast United States took a deadly toll
on New York City's homeless, killing as many as five people who
failed to find shelter, while warm winds in the Great Plains on
Tuesday brought record high temperatures.
   Two days and nights of bitter cold in the Northeast led
authorities to search for homeless on the streets.
   ``I don't recall when we had any numbers (of cold-related deaths)
this high,'' said Ellen Borakove, the spokeswoman for the New York
medical examiner.
   The temperature in New York City plummeted to 5 degrees before
dawn on Monday _ a record for the date _ and as low as 15 the next
night.
   The cold reached down to Florida, where residents in the northern
part of the state scraped frost from their windshields Tuesday
morning as temperatures dipped into the low 20s.
   Snowflakes were reported in portions of the Florida Panhandle.
   A rapidly moving weather system in the Northeast spread light
snow from the Upper Ohio Valley to the northern and middle Atlantic
Coast states. Snowfall was mostly about an inch or less, causing
some slippery driving.
   Another fast moving weather system brought a mixture of snow,
freezing rain and rain to portions of northwestern Minnesota,
northern North Dakota and northeastern Montana.
   The eastern slopes of the Rockies had high winds.
   Winds gusted to 69 mph at Squaw Mountain, Colo.; and also topped
60 mph in such towns as Casper, Wyo., Mines Peak, Colo., Boulder,
Colo.; Livingston, Mont., Cody, Wyo., Sheridan Wyo., Billings,
Mont., and Rollinsville, Wyo.
   The westerly winds along the east slopes of the Rockies resulted
in warm temperatures in the Great Plains states. Temperatures
reached the 60s Tuesday afternoon in western portions of the Great
Plains from Montana to Texas. Rapid City, S.D., with 64 degrees, and
Goodland, Kan., 73 degrees, set record high temperatures for the
date.
   Elsewhere, lowland river flood conditions continued to improve
slowly in Arkansas. A flood warning continued for the Sulphur River
Basin in northeastern Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 16
degrees at Altoona, Pa., State College Pa., and Limestone, Maine, to
81 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   The low in the nation Tuesday morning was 8 degrees below zero at
Houlton, Maine, Glens Falls, N.Y., and Concord, N.H.
   For Wednesday, the National Weather Service forecasts snow or
snow showers in the northern and central Rockies, the northern half
of the Great Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley to the upper
Great Lakes. Snow is expected to most widespread over Colorado and
Wyoming. Show showers also are forecast from western New York to
northern New England.
   Highs are expected in the teens and 20s in the northern Rockies,
the northern Great Lakes, northern New England, North Dakota and
northern Minnesota; in the 30s and 40s from southern New England and
the mid-Atlantic states to the southern Great Lakes, the upper
Mississippi Valley, the central Plains, the central Rockies and much
of the intermountain west to the Pacific Northwest; in the 70s in
southern Florida, eastern and southern Texas and the desert
Southwest; and in the 50s and 60s in most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
