<2ND_LINE>AM-NIreland-Slaying,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Shoot Man Who Repaired Cars Owned By Security Forces</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Irish, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two gunmen walked into a car
repair workshop Tuesday and shot to death its owner at point-blank
range, police said.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for killing John
Currie, 31, but suspicion fell on the mainly Roman Catholic Irish
Republican Army, which is fighting to drive the British out of
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland.
   Published reports said Currie, a Protestant, repaired vehicles
owned by members of the security forces. The IRA repeatedly has
warned civilians against carrying out work for the police or other
security personnel in the province.
   The gunmen singled out Currie from among several of his
colleagues in the workshop in Portadown, 25 miles southwest of
Belfast, said police Inspector Fred Campbell. They escaped in a
hijacked car whose owner was held captive in a disused house in
nearby Lurgan, Campbell said.
   Currie was the 54th civilian to die this year in political and
sectarian violence in Northern Ireland. More than 2,700 people have
been killed in nearly 20 years of violence in the province.
