<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Onassis     12-13 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Onassis,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heiress Ingested Sedative Before She Died, News Agency Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A news agency reported Tuesday
that Greek heiress Christina Onassis took a significant dose of a
sedative before she died last month, but it did not blame her death
on the drug.
   Responding to the report, the friend who was hosting Ms. Onassis
when she died said the drug was for the heiress' housekeeper and
ruled out any possibility of suicide.
   ``I'm surprised, and I can't believe it,'' Mrs. Marina Dodero
said of the report. ``I doubt it, and the forensic results are not
in.''
   The private news agency, Noticias Argentinas, drew no connection
between Ms. Onassis' death and the barbituate, which it identified
as Optalidon. The agency based its report on judicial sources it did
not identify.
   Ms. Onassis, the 37-year-old multimillionaire daughter of the
late Aristotle Onassis, died Nov. 19 at the country home of Mrs.
Dodero.
   Initial reports said she apparently suffered a heart attack, and
a preliminary coroner's statement said the death was caused by a
buildup of fluid in the lungs. Federal Judge Alberto Piotti is
directing an inquiry into what caused the accumulation of fluid to
determine whether the death was from natural causes.
   Piotti's secretary told The Associated Press in a telephone
interview Tuesday that final forensic reports have not been
submitted to the judge. ``We don't have knowledge of that
information'' about the sedative, the secretary said.
   Mrs. Dodero said in an interview with a Buenos Aires television
station that the heiress ``was afraid of taking medicine.''
   She said the Optalidon was for Ms. Onassis' housekeeper, Heleni
Syros.
   Ms. Onassis' family ruled out last month any possibility that Ms.
Onassis committed suicide.
   ``She was completely happy,'' Mrs. Dodero said Tuesday. ``She
would never take an action of that kind because of the enormous love
she had for her daughter,'' 3-year-old Athena.
   The child will inherit most of her mother's wealth, estimated at
$500 million. Christina Onassis' father, who was married to
President Kennedy's widow Jacqueline Kennedy, built his fortune on
shipping and real estate.
</TEXT>
