<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CSX-DrugTesting 1stLd-Writethru a0762 12-13 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CSX-Drug Testing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0762,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Railroad Seeks Exemption From Federal Drug-Testing Order</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th graf bgng, `FRA Administrator,' to
UPDATE with unions suing Tuesday in federal court in San Francisco
over drug testing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department is reviewing a
request by one of the country's major railroads to eliminate random
tests as part of a drug testing program for railroad workers,
officials said Tuesday.
   CSX Transportation Inc. filed a petition with the Federal
Railroad Administration this week asking that a railroad not be
required to conduct random drug tests if it already has a ``proven''
drug testing program under way.
   The DOT maintains that random testing is an integral part of an
effective drug testing program for transportation workers involved
in safety related jobs.
   But CSX, one of the nation's largest railroad companies, said
random testing ``is at best an untried experiment'' and that there
are other methods to combat drug abuse problem in the railroad
industry.
   FRA Administrator John Riley said the petition ``will be given
full and fair consideration,'' as will any other suggestion for a
modification of the drug testing requirements that were announced
last month.
   Unions representing 200,000 railroad workers sued Tuesday in
federal court in San Francisco, challenging the drug testing program
in the railroad industry.
   The suit contends random drug testing, without suspicion of
current drug use, violates constitutional standards for searches. It
also contends the FRA has no legal authority to order random testing.
   A suit by the unions in the same court resulted in a ruling by
the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in February prohibiting
post-accident drug testing by railroads without reasonable suspicion
of individual drug use. That case was one of two drug testing cases
argued before the Supreme Court last month; no ruling has been
issued.
   The Transportation Department on Nov. 14 said millions of
transportation workers, including railroad workers, will be subject
to a broad range of drug tests beginning in December 1989.
   The random tests have been strongly opposed by labor, but most
transportation companies have endorsed them as being necessary.
During a series of hearings on drug testing, CSX was the only
railroad that opposed random testing.
   In its petition, CSX said it does not believe the evidence
supports random drug testing as the most effective means of
combating drug abuse in the industry.
   CSX asked that a railroad be exempted from the random testing
requirement if it can show that its existing drug testing program
``works as well or better than the expectations of random drug
testing.''
   ``Random testing in the railroad industry is at best an untried
experiment with many admitted unknowns,'' CSX said in a statement.
``That belief is based not on supposition, but on (the railroad's)
actual experience.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1927EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PTL 1stLd-Writethru a0699 12-13 0868</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0699,0890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Sale Of PTL Asssets To Canadian Businessman</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with background on Mernick and
to
CORRECT in 3rd graf `associated' to `associates'; picks up 4th graf,
`The Heritage ...' SUBS 9th graf, `Mernick has ...' with 4 grafs to
UPDATE with more Mernick background, quotes; picks up 10th graf,
`Had no ...' INSERTS 6 grafs after 12 graf, `Bahakel, a ...' with
comment from other bidders, possible appeal; picks up 13th graf, `A
month ...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Tuesday ordered the assets of
the troubled PTL television ministry sold to a Toronto real estate
developer for $65 million.
   Stephen Mernick, a 34-year-old Orthodox Jew, bid $36.25 million
on Monday in a session at Heritage USA headquarters near Fort Mill,
but after meeting Tuesday with attorneys for the ministry and for
the creditors, he agreed to increase his bid to $65 million.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds approved the sale at a
hearing in Columbia, just more than a week after PTL founder Jim
Bakker and three former associates were indicted by a federal grand
jury in North Carolina.
   The Heritage USA theme park and accompanying satellite television
operation were left behind by Bakker in March 1987 after it was
revealed he had a sexual liaison with New York church secretary
Jessica Hahn and paid her to keep quiet about it.
   The ministry filed for reoganization under bankruptcy laws in
June 1987, and attempts to sell it had included two auctions before
Tuesday's session. The sessions Monday and in November produced no
acceptable bids.
   Included in the sale were 2,200 acres of property, a 500-room
hotel, a water park, a television studio and a 2,000-seat church.
   Reynolds polled major creditors and nearly all approved the sale
to Mernick, saying they believed it was the best deal they would get.
   Mernick would take over the administration and operations 41 days
after Reynolds approved the sale and closing would be 60 days later.
   ``We're excited,'' Mernick told reporters outside the courthouse.
``We're very excited and happy we won. We look forward to being
here.''
   He would not answer questions about plans for Heritage USA,
including whether Heritage Ministries, the non-profit religious
spinoff, would be able to continue leasing the television ministry
and church at Fort Mill.
   Mernick has said he was buying the property as an investment but
would considering keeping Heritage USA operating as a Christian
theme park.
   ``We are in the middle of ongoing discussions'' with Heritage
Ministries, Mernick said.
   Mernick's family has roots in Toronto real estate that go back 40
years, but he was little known outside the area's Orthodox Jewish
community until March when he purchased the old Firestone Canada
Inc. tire plant in Hamilton, Ontario.
   His holdings include a landfill in the Toronto area, a 50 percent
interest in a local waste disposal and recycling company, and
wholesale and retail travel agencies.
   Had no acceptable bid been submitted, PTL would have been broken
up and sold, court-appointed bankruptcy trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton
said after Monday's failed auction.
   Bidders this week also included Michael Karas, president of First
Canadian Development Co. of Toronto; Sam Johnson, president of PTL's
religious operations who is trying to get major contributors to buy
back the ministry; and Cy Bahakel, owner of 15 television and radio
stations.
   Bahakel, a former North Carolina state senator, said his partner
in his attempt to by PTL's assets is George Shinn, majority owner of
the Charlotte Hornets basketball team. Shinn considered buying
Heritage USA last spring, but never made a formal bid.
   Faison Barnes, an attorney for Bahakel, objected to the bidding
procedures.
   ``It appears to us that was a negotiated deal between yesterday's
auction and the appearance in court today,'' Barnes told reporters.
``We're going to very careful consideration to an appeal.''
   Johnson acknowledged that Heritage Ministries was about $1
million behind in lease payments to PTL, but said he remained
confident that contributors would eventually back the effort to buy
back Heritage USA.
   Johnson said Mernick told him, ```We want to work with you. We're
sensitive to your needs.'''
   A month ago, Mernick said he would pay $115 million, $50 million
in cash. But Reynolds rejected the bid, saying there were inadequate
assurances that Mernick would pay the remaining $65 million.
   The offers Monday were far below the total appraised value of
PTL's assets _ $92 million to $110 million. In an appraisal dated
Aug. 18, Arthur Little & Co. of Atlanta said PTL's assets would be
worth $76 million to $85 million if sold piecemeal.
   The grand jury that indicted Bakker on Dec. 5 is scheduled to
reconvene Jan. 17, a source familiar with the investigation said
Tuesday in Charlotte. The source demanded anonymity.
   The panel has accused Bakker and former top aide Richard Dortch
of diverting more than $4 million in PTL money to support their own
``lavish and extravagant'' lifestyles.
   Two other former aides, brothers David and James Taggart, each
were indicted on six tax charges.
   Bakker _ who has avoided reporters since his indictment _ and the
others are to appear in court Thursday.
</TEXT>
