<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 2100EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brite     12-13 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brite,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ken Needham hopes Americans' hunger for
Louisiana-style spicy cooking will call for a matching thirst. He's
selling beer with pepper in it.
   Needham has introduced Cajun Beer, a brew that combines the
tastes of cayenne pepper, cane sugar and beer.
   ``Cajun has been here (in America) for 250 years, and it's here
to stay,'' said Needham, 68, of Paw Paw in southwestern Michigan.
   Needham's isn't the only Cajun brew on the market. The
proprietors of Mulate's restaurants, authentic Acadian eateries in
Baton Rouge and Breaux Bridge, La., recently began marketing their
own style of Cajun beer, distributed primarily in Louisiana.
   Needham's beverage is produced at Pabst Brewing Co.'s Milwaukee
facility and is being distributed to bars and restaurants in eight
Midwestern and Plains states. Distribution is to being next month in
several more states, including Louisiana.
   If all goes well, the beer, which sells for $5 per six-pack, will
be available in stores next year.
   Needham hopes the beer is hot but not, well, too hot.
   ``I was looking for a medium-style European beer with seasonings,
but I didn't want you to taste the seasonings in the beer until
after you had swallowed it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
