<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Trial     12-13 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Trial,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Asks 15-Year Sentence For Brezhnev Son-in-Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state prosecutor has asked for a sentence of 15
years in prison at hard labor for the late Soviet leader Leonid
Brezhnev's son-in-law, Yuri Churbanov, who is on trial for
corruption, Tass reported on Tuesday.
   The official Soviet news agency said prosecutor Alexander Sboyev
summed up his case on Monday and Tuesday and that defense lawyers
will take the floor ``after a short interval.''
   Churbanov was first deputy interior minister before Brezhnev died
in 1982. He is accused of accepting more than a million dollars in
bribes to protect a criminal network that extended throughout the
southern republic of Uzbekistan.
   The trial of Churbanov and eight other defendants has been the
centerpiece of a recent campaign aginst the Brezhnev era, whose
18-year rule in the Soviet Union is portrayed as a time of
corruption and stagnation.
   Churbanov, now 51, married Brezhnev's daughter Galina in 1971 and
almost at once began rising rapidly to the upper echelons of the
interior police force.
   ``The state prosecutor regarded the bribe as a malicious
instrument of corrupted consciousness, which become simply monstrous
in the hands of law enforcement bodies,'' Tass said.
   ``The defendants held key posts in Soviet law enforcement bodies
whose duty it is to fight against injustice, embezzlement, state
deceit and, of course, bribery in all its forms.''
   Churbanov was accused of accepting $1,133,000 in bribes, but
Sboyev suggested a reduction to $675,000 in the amount of money
Churbanov allegedly took since it could not be proven that he had
accepted the rest of the money.
   Sbobyev also recommended reducing the sum of bribes allegedly
accepted by Khaidar Yakhayev, a co-defendant who also faces 15 years
at hard labor.
   The prosecutor recommended sentences for the seven other
co-defendants ranging from six to 13 years in hard labor camps.
   He asked that all property of the defendants be confiscated.
</TEXT>
