<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Beat Civilians As President Speaks on Human Rights</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Soldiers investigating the death of
a colleague arrested and beat several civilians on the same day
Haiti's military ruler delivered a speech on human rights, radio
stations said Tuesday.
   The unidentified air force soldiers on Saturday invaded Tiremasse
Street, a poor neighborhood in the capital city of Port-au-Prince,
after hearing of the death of Sgt. Fouille Grand-Champ, the
state-run newspaper L'Union said Tuesday.
   Radio stations and the privately run TeleHaiti said Grand-Champ
killed himself after shooting and wounding his fiancee, Leone
Germain. L'Union said the soldiers heard that Grand-Champ had been
assassinated.
   A number of civilians were released after being beaten and
slapped, news media reported. Haiti-Inter radio said the soldiers
clubbed a schoolgirl as they walked down Tiremasse Street.
   The beatings came on the same day that Haitian ruler Lt. Gen.
Prosper Avril spoke on the human rights achievements of his
3-month-old government. Haiti last week ratified five international
human rights conventions.
   ``Soldiers take justice into their own hands ... These are the
signs of the inexistence of justice in this country,'' Arnold
Antonin, co-director of the National Network for the Defense of
Human Rights, told The Associated Press Tuesday.
   Rank-and-file soldiers named Avril as president after ousting
former ruler Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy in a coup on Sept. 17, saying
they were sickened by state-sponsored violence.
   Namphy came to power after former President-for-Life Jean-Claude
Duvalier fled to exile in France in February 1986.
</TEXT>
