<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-John,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Welsh Legislator Brynmor John Dies At 54</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Welsh legislator Brynmor John, who served in the
Labor governments of Harold Wilson and James Callaghan during an
18-year career in the House of Commons, died Tuesday. He was 54.
   John suffered a heart attack while walking outside the Houses of
Parliament and died at nearby St. Thomas's Hospital, the hospital
said.
   He retained his parliamentary seat in the Labor stronghold of
Pontypridd in south Wales with a huge 17,277 majority in the June
1987 general election. He first won the seat in June 1970.
   John served as an undersecretary in the Ministry of Defense under
Wilson in 1974-76 and as a minister of state at the Home Office
under Callaghan from 1976 to 1979.
   He was Labor's opposition spokesman on Northern Ireland in
1979-80, defense spokesman in 1980-81, social security spokesman in
1981-83 and agriculture spokesman from 1984-87.
   John, a lawyer, is survived by his widow, Ann Pryce, a son and a
daughter.
   Labor leader Neil Kinnock called him ``one of the most effective
and decent members of the Labor Party and a valued colleague in
Parliament.''
   Labor's spokesman on Welsh affairs, Barry Jones, said John ``had
the heart of a lion. He was a politician of integrity, respected by
all, and with an unswerving devotion to his constituency.''
</TEXT>
