<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Rebels,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Die in Guerrilla Attacks Across Peru</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marxist rebels looted government buildings and
battled police at a river port during a jungle raid that left three
people dead, authorities said Tuesday.
   In the Andes Mountains, Maoist guerrillas killed an army officer,
a mayor, and a policeman in three separate incidents, police also
said.
   Two guerrillas of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, a
pro-Cuban group, and a villager were killed Sunday when the
insurgents clashed with police defending Puerto Inca. The town is on
the bank of the Pachitea River 135 miles northeast of Lima.
   About 50 rebels ransacked and looted a government development
office and two state banks before they were driven off, police said.
   The Tupac Amaru group began attacks, mainly in Lima and other
urban centers, in 1984.
   In the Andes, a larger Maoist guerrilla group known as the
Shining Path executed an army captain, police said. He was in
civilian dress, but the rebels checked his identification and
dragged him from an interstate bus Monday near Concepcion, 120 miles
east of Lima, authorities said.
   They said other Shining Path insurgents on Monday executed Mayor
Alfredo Chamorro in the village of Pallanchacra near Concepcion.
   Also Monday, police and rebels from the group were reported to
clash at a mountain pass near Cuzco, 355 miles southeast of Lima. A
policeman was killed and five Shining Path guerrillas were wounded,
police said.
   The Shining Path has been fighting since 1980 to topple Peru's
elected government. It is not believed to maintain ties with the
Tupac Amaru group.
   The government says more than 12,000 people have died in violence
stemming from the Shining Path insurgency.
</TEXT>
