<HEAD>Marcos To Remain Hospitalized</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with physician saying Marcos
expected to be discharged before the weekend. Picks up 4th graf pvs,
`Although his...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos
remained hospitalized Tuesday for further medical tests but will
probably get out by the weekend, officials said.
   The 71-year-old Marcos, who was hospitalized last Friday with
chest pains, was listed in stable condition Tuesday at St. Francis
Medical Center.
   Dr. Calvin Wong, a cardiologist, said Tuesday in a statement that
Marcos would be given a general physical examination Wednesday and
was expected to be discharged before the weekend.
   Wong said earlier Marcos had weak heart muscles and was prone to
congestive heart failure but that his heart condition had stabilized.
   Although his heart condition has stabilized, hospital spokeswoman
Norma Kop said Marcos had undergone neurological tests and a ``bone
scan'' and would have more tests Wednesday.
   Marcos faces federal racketeering charges in New York accusing
him of plundering his nation's economy during his 20-year rule and
stashing some of the money in the United States.
   He was to be arraigned in New York, but he and his lawyers
contend he is too frail to make the 10-hour flight. A
court-appointed doctor who examined him before his most recent bout
of hospitalization concluded that he did have medical problems but
not severe enough to prevent him from traveling. That same doctor
also concluded that Marcos faked claims of being in pain during the
medical examination, an allegation that Marcos' spokesmen deny.
   Marcos' wife, Imelda, has pleaded innocent to the same charges
and is free on bail. They have lived in exile here since being
ousted from the Philippines in 1986.
