<2ND_LINE>AM-Stepson Death,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stepdad Driving One of 3 Cars That Hit And Kill Teen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW PORT RICHEY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man driving a car on a dark road
hit a bicyclist who turned out to be his stepson, police said. The
boy died after he was then hit by two other cars.
   Larry Dean Kelley, 16, was hit from behind as he pedaled along a
curve just before daybreak Monday.
   ``In the flash of the headlight I saw his black nylon jacket, his
blond hair coming our from under his hat and the black bicycle
frame,'' said his grieving stepfather, Richard Hogenson. ``As I
heard the thud and was bringing the car to a stop, I thought, `Gee,
I hope that's not Larry.'''
   He added, ``I saw him just before impact and I didn't have time
to slow down.''
   Young Kelley was was thrown over the roof of Hogenson's car. A
second car then hit him and a third car dragged him 45 feet along
the road, the Florida Highway Patrol said. The teen-ager was
pronounced dead at the scene.
   Hogenson, who estimated he was driving at about 50 mph, said the
accident was unavoidable from the moment he saw the bicycle at a
distance of about 10 feet.
   Trooper William Bishop said the speed limit on the unlighted road
is 55 mph, and the bicycle had reflectors but no light. The boy's
dark clothing was also a factor in the accident, Bishop said.
   ``It's very coincidental, but we have nothing to say otherwise,''
Bishop said.
   Kelley, a high school sophomore, had moved out a number of times
after conflicts with his parents in the past three years, most
recently Dec. 2, the stepfather said. He was staying with friends.
   ``Larry was a lot like most teen-age kids. He was going through
the typical teen-age upheavals,'' his stepfather said. ``He was a
nice kid. He was very independent. He wanted to do things his own
way.''
</TEXT>
