<HEAD>Presidential Nominees Swap Charges in Killing of Election Official</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with governing Christian Democrats
accusing opposition mayor of involvement in killing election
official, opposition denying it. ADDS byline. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top leaders of the governing
party and the major opposition party clashed Tuesday night over
charges that an opposition mayor took part in killing an election
official.
   Fidel Chavez Mena, the nominee of the governing Christian
Democrats in the March 1989 presidential election, said that Mayor
Antonio Vasquez of Soyapango was among several people who forced
Francisco Eduardo Bonilla from his car Monday night and shot him.
   He said Eduardo Bonilla was in the process of registering
Soyapango residents to vote at the time of the shooting.
   Alfredo Cristiani, presidential nominee of the right-wing
Nationalist Republican Alliance, said a party investigation turned
up nothing to link Vasquez to the killing. Vasquez is a member of
the Alliance, known as Arena.
   Christiani told a news conference in San Salvador that an Arena
investigation ``has found no evidence that involves (Vasquez) as the
author of the murder.''
   The Arena leader accused the Christian Democrats of using the
incident for political purposes and said, ``It's the judicial
tribunals and not politicians or candidates who can give
conclusions.''
   He said his party would cooperate with official investigations
and that ``if anyone is found to be involved, we would be the first
to say that all the weight of the law should fall against the guilty
one.''
   Christian Democratic officials said Vasquez was among a group
that forced Eduardo Bonilla and several companions to get out of the
car in Soyapango, four miles north of San Salvador, the capital. One
of those who got out was beaten and Eduardo Bonilla was shot when he
tried to intervene, they said.
   There was no official confirmation of the account.
   Elsewhere, a land mine exploded Monday under a train carrying
railroad employees in central El Salvador, killing one person and
injuring five, officials said.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said on
Tuesday that they suspected leftist rebels laid the mine on the
track near San Vicente, about 37 miles east of San Salvador.
   A passing railcar triggered the blast, they said. It was carrying
a work crew to repair damages from a recent railway explosion, they
said.
   In Washington on Tuesday, State Department spokesman Charles
Redman blamed leftist guerrillas for the deaths of nine elected
officials in the past seven months and declared:
   ``The communist insurgents apparently view popular support for
democracy not as an opportunity but a threat.''
   Marxist-led guerrillas are pitted in a 9-year-old war against the
U.S.-supported government. More than 65,000 people, most of them
civilians, have been killed.
