<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing Project Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paramedics Leave Housing Project, Boy Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with boy's mother disputing
official version, saying she saw no one outside project. Picks up
8th graf, `A secretary...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old asthmatic boy died after paramedics
refused to enter the public housing project where he lived, and the
boy's mother disputed officials' claim that the ambulance waited for
police protection because it was pelted with eggs.
   ``We'll pull our radio tapes and speak to people and try to get a
blow-by-blow of what happened,'' Fire Department spokesman Bill
Crowley said Tuesday.
   He refused to identify the two paramedics.
   The paramedics, summoned by an emergency call at 4:16 p.m.
Monday, were not aware of the seriousness of the Carl Jarnagin's
health problem when they arrived at the six-story Chicago Housing
Authority building on the South Side, Crowley said.
   And when they arrived, Crowley said, ``there were different
objects hitting the vehicle.''
   He said egg was on the windshield and other objects, possibly
stones, also hit the ambulance. He said the paramedics were not sure
where the objects were coming from or who was throwing them, that
they left and returned with police protection, too late to revive
Carl.
   But the boy's mother, Sharon, said she had been outside the
building trying to flag down a cab to take Carl for help. ``No one
was out there,'' she said. ``My daughter was looking out the window
for the ambulance _ no one was outside.''
   Other residents of the housing project said nothing was being
thrown at the paramedics when they initially refused to enter the
building.
   A secretary for the CHA's Local Advisory Council at the Dearborn
Homes, which include the building where the incident occurred, said
residents told her nothing was thrown.
   The secretary, Sandra Falls, said ambulance workers refused to
enter the building for 15 to 20 minutes, even with police there.
Another Fire Department spokesman, Thomas Sheppard, denied that.
   Under Fire Department policy, paramedics should avoid placing
themselves in danger, even if that means a delay in treatment to a
victim, Sheppard said.
   Paramedics often are accompanied to CHA buildings by police or a
fire unit, making the trip into some high-crime areas safer, Crowley
said. ``Going into the projects alone is a problem.''
   ``There was no one throwing rocks out the window,'' said Randy
Taylor, a resident. ``There was just, I think, fear of the black
community.
   ``I used to have asthma, and this happened to us several times.
My mother used to have to ... scuffle around trying to get me to the
hospital when I was a little boy.''
   The building has 48 apartments, and most residents are black.
   Crowley said he did not know the race of the paramedics. But a
resident who lived a floor above the Jarnagins, 23-year-old Sherry
Teague, said both were white.
   After police arrived, she said, she begged the paramedics to come
to the apartment where the boy was having an asthma attack.
   She said the paramedics complained of having things thrown at
them, and refused to immediately go upstairs.
   ``The lady was saying `We're not going in there,'' Miss Teague
said. ``I'm not going to get my head busted with people throwing
things.'''
   She said she knew of nothing being thrown.
   Crowley was uncertain when paramedics arrived at the building,
but he said they left at 4:28 p.m. Police arrived at 4:34 p.m., and
the ambulance returned six minutes later, he said. Paramedics worked
to revive the boy for 30 minutes before taking him to Mercy
Hospital, where he died, Crowley said.
   An autopsy showed the boy died of bronchial asthma, according to
an intake worker at the Cook County medical examiner's office who
identified himself only by his last name, Morris.
   Morris said he was unsure if the autopsy showed if the boy could
have been saved with quicker treatment. Dr. Margarita Arruza, who
performed the autopsy, was in a meeting and not immediately
available, a secretary said.
   Police received a call for help from the Fire Department at 4:21
p.m., said Officer Charles Marschke. Police entered the fifth-floor
apartment, found the boy ``unresponsive'' and on a floor, tried to
revive him and called for the paramedics to return, he said.
   The police report did not mention whether the ambulance had been
attacked, Marschke said.
   Crowley said the paramedics were upset over Carl's death. ``It
was so frustrating for them that this child passed away,'' he said.
</TEXT>
