<2ND_LINE>AM-South Korea,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leader of South Korea's Governing Party Promises Referendum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing party's new chairman said
Tuesday that a national referendum will be held next year to seek
public endorsement of President Roh Tae-woo's administration.
   Park Joon-kyu said a date will be announced in the next two or
three months.
   Park was named chairman of the governing Democratic Justice Party
last week, when Roh replaced his Cabinet members and party leaders
to defuse national furor over abuses under the rule of his
predecessor and former ally, Chun Doo-hwan. In another reshuffle
Tuesday, Roh replaced 19 governors and officials at the vice
minister level.
   Park was vague when asked what Roh would do if he lost the
referendum.
   ``If the result is miserable, if defeated, we have no choice,''
he said.
   Democratic Justice leaders have said Roh would not step down,
even if he lost. A simple majority, or more than 50 percent, would
be considered approval of the Roh government, Park said.
   Roh has asked the nation to forgive Chun, who went into rural
exile after apologizing for misdeeds under his rule. But the
opposition accused Roh of failing to take strong action against Chun
and demanded that Chun be forced to testify before National Assembly
committes investigating past wrongdoings.
   Several of Chun's relatives and associates have been charged or
convicted of corruption.
</TEXT>
