<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FarmBureau-Grapes     12-13 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Bureau-Grapes,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Group Cancels San Francisco Meeting Over Grapes Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARK RIDGE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Farm Bureau Federation said
Tuesday it will not hold its 1991 annual meeting in San Francisco
after the city's Board of Supervisors voted to support a boycott of
table grapes.
   ``We must interpret the vote as an indication that we are not
welcome,'' said Dean Kleckner, the group's president.
   About 3.7 million farmers belong to the organization, and between
6,000 and 10,000 usually attend the annual meeting, said spokesman
Jack King.
   The supervisors, on a 8-2 vote Monday, endorsed the boycott urged
by the United Farm Workers union, which claims harmful pesticides
are used on table grapes.
   The resolution calls for the city to stop its annual purchase of
about $4,500 in grapes for jail inmates and patients at city
hospitals.
   Eight farm groups, including the farm federation, last week
threatened to cancel conventions if city supervisors backed the
boycott.
   The Convention and Visitors Bureau estimated that San Franciso
could lose $60 million in convention-related business.
   In 1982, the farm federation canceled another convention in San
Francisco when the supervisors endorsed a lettuce and banana boycott.
</TEXT>
