<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 2313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Aircraft     12-13 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Aircraft,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Official Says Training Flight Suspension Will Affect Readiness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The suspension of NATO tactical fighter
training flights after the deadly crash of a U.S. jet will have a
significant impact on the alliance's air defense readiness, a U.S.
official said Tuesday.
   The A-10 Thunderbolt II jet crashed Thursday in a residential
neighborhood in the central city of Remscheid. Six people were
killed, including the American pilot.
   On Monday, defense officials of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization said all tactical training flights over West Germany
would be halted until Jan. 2 in memory of the victims.
   Air Force Maj. Gen. Marcus A. Anderson Anderson said of the
suspension: ``There will be significant readiness impact due to the
stand-down and there will be some readiness standards that will not
be met.
   ``Almost half of the U.S. (Air Force's) tactical forces in Europe
are located in the Federal Republic (West Germany),'' Anderson said
at a news conference. ``So it's a substantial amount of force and a
substantial amount of flying on a daily basis.''
   But he said the ``the extent of that impact has yet to be fully
assessed.''
   Anderson is commander of the U.S. Third Air Force, which is
stationed in Mildenhall, England. The pilot of the jet was under his
command.
   Anderson said it was the first time training flights had been
suspended for such an extended period, and he expressed concern that
it set a precedent for suspensions after future accidents.
   The Remscheid accident renewed a public outcry against military
flights over residential areas.
   Before the crash, 12 major accident involving military aircraft
killed 95 people this year alone. They included 70 people people who
died in an air show crash at the U.S. Air Force base in Ramstein in
August.
   Anderson denied West German published reports that U.S. soldiers
carrying rifles and truncheons roughly prevented residents from
entering their stricken neighborhood.
   ``U.S. personnel were not carrying weapons (rifles) or any kind
of clubs,'' he said.
   He said a squad of U.S. military police officers with pistols
were dispatched to the site after the crash but were pulled out a
few hours later.
   U.S. officials have said security efforts at the scene were
handled largely by West German troops and police.
   Anderson also denied allegations by West German officials that
American authorities mishandled the rescue efforts and delayed
releasing information about the plane and its munitions.
   He said more than $114,000 has been paid in property and other
claims after the accident. Under agreements with West Germany, the
U.S. pays about 80 percent of the claims total.
   Meanwhile, government sources said on condition of anonymity that
the parliamentary undersecretary of defense, Peter Kurt Wuerzbach,
would resign in January.
   Wuerzbach's decision to order a suspension of the West German air
force's low-level training flights immediately after the crash
angered Defense Minister Rupert Scholz, who was in the United States
at the time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
