<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     12-13 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0444</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<HEAD>Pilobolus Dances to Presley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Graceful, joyful, young and charming are unusual
words to apply to Pilobolus, the modern dance company once intent on
figuring out how many ways athletic human bodies could fit together
like spoons and other bent and curved implements.
   But they're the words to describe the company of six dancing to
early recordings by Elvis Presley. ``I'm Left, You're Right, She's
Gone'' had its New York premiere on Tuesday's opening night at the
Joyce Theater.
   Between songs, Dale Reeves, sounding a lot like Presley, gave
dating advice to the ``adolescent'' dancers. ``I'm Left'' isn't
predictable enough to be nostalgia; sometimes it's a bit rude; it's
always fun.
   The two women wear strapless, full-skirted dresses for dancing,
chew bubblegum, wear cheerleading boots and knee pads for being
dragged around the floor. They're also occasionally strangled. In
one song they're passive. In another, after the voice admits, ``I
used to be shy,'' Jack Arnold, Jim Blanc, Austin Hartel and Peter
Pucci approach with increasing confidence. Carol Parker judo tosses
them all to the floor.
   To ``Tutti Frutti,'' Jude Sante shook her seat, sending two of
the men into a twitch and the audience into laughter. The final
song, ``Blue Moon,'' was a series of slow lifts but young swiftness
was back for taking showy bows to ``Shake, Rattle and Roll.''
   The six people who danced it and four more are listed as
choreographers.
   The evening began with ``Carmina Burana, Side II,'' using garbage
cans as props and unlike any other dance company's depiction of this
Carl Orff music.
   Dancers stick their rears into the cans and roll around the
floor. They stick their heads into them and dance, only their legs
and feet showing beneath, like dancing cigarette packs in early TV
ads. A man and woman inside cans scoot their cans together, roll
across the floor, then split.
   Sometimes dancers have tiny painted heads riding on their own
heads, making their arms look out of proportion. It's all for fun.
   Five people choreographed ``Bonsai'' in 1979. Four, looking like
primitives, dance to animal and drum sounds. This is of the
pressed-together-like-spoons school. Austin Hartel's brief solo,
``Pseudopodia,'' with backward somersaults and shoulder stands,
dates from 1974 and has choreography by Jonathan Wolken. Wolken and
Moses Pendleton, who studied dance at Dartmouth College and
cofounded the company in 1971, also compopsed the music.
   Pilobolus will alternate three programs at the Joyce Theater
through Jan. 8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 2310EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush 5thLd-Writethru a0824 12-13 1283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0824,1,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Taps Yeutter for Agriculture, Skinner for Transportation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th graf pvs bgng, `But Yeutter's,' to
UPDATE with report that Bush told Yeutter he would not be expected
to serve a full term</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush has asked U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton Yeutter to be the new agriculture secretary
and has settled on Samuel Skinner of Illinois for secretary of
transportation, presidential transition sources said Tuesday.
   Yeutter earlier Tuesday declined to discuss reports that he was
still under consideration for the agriculture post after he
initially stated he would rather return to private life. But a
source close to Yeutter said he was considering the offer.
   The 58-year-old trade representative told reporters as he arrived
for a Capitol Hill luncheon that his ``proclivity was to return to
the private sector,'' but he added, ``I've learned never to say
never.''
   For the Transportation Department job, transition sources said
Bush has chosen Skinner, 50, a former U.S. attorney in Chicago who
has headed the Regional Transportation Authority in the Chicago area
since 1984.
   Skinner's wife, Sue, said Tuesday night in a telephone interview
from their home, ``I assume he probably will be (appointed
transportation secretary). But I don't think it's been totally
confirmed with him yet.'' Skinner, whose reputation for toughness
has earned him the nickname ``Sam the Hammer,'' was not at home and
could not be reached immediately, his wife said.
   Announcements on the two Cabinet posts could come Wednesday or
Thursday, one source said.
   Two transition sources said Bush had planned to meet Tuesday
evening with Yeutter, an ex-farmer from Nebraska who formerly served
as chief executive officer of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   But Yeutter's daughter, Kim, said that although her father was
attending a party at Bush's home Tuesday evening, a formal meeting
between the two would not be held until Wednesday.
   The Washington Post reported in Wednesday's editions that Bush
tried to persuade a reluctant Yeutter to take the agriculture job by
suggesting that he would not be expected to serve a full term.
Citing unidentified transition sources, the newspaper said Bush told
Yeutter that he would be expected to stay only through the first
summit conference of the leaders of the Western industrial
democracies, a meeting which Bush has said he wanted to devote to
agricultural issues.
   Meanwhile, rumors circulated that an announcement on the defense
secretary position was imminent.
   But Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of staff and co-director of the
transition office, said Tuesday the timing on any such announcement
was still up in the air as the FBI continued background checks on
prospective nominee John Tower, a former senator from Texas.
   Fuller said he expected a Bush to name ``a couple more Cabinet
positions'' this week and that the Cabinet should be filled by
Christmas.
   The field of contenders changed somewhat with Bush's decision
that he'll pick no one from Congress for Cabinet posts.
   Several members of Congress had said they were being considered
for high-level positions in the new administration. But Bush is
putting an end to that, telling them in notes and telephone calls
that it was more important for them to retain their spots in the
Democratic-controlled House and Senate.
   ``The vice president has several friends in the Congress ... who
had expressed an interest in doing something in the departments and
agencies, and he really just decided it wasn't fair to deplete our
strength in Congress by pulling Republicans out,'' said Fuller.
   There was no word Tuesday on the biggest question about an
unfilled position: When, or whether, Bush would name Tower as
secretary of defense.
   Bush, asked about it Tuesday, said, ``The process is still going
forward.'' Fuller said timing of any announcement on the job was
``completely up in the air'' while Tower's background is reviewed.
He noted that Bush still could pick someone else.
   ``We've been working on some of the other agencies,'' he said,
adding that he expects Bush to announce ``a couple more Cabinet
positions'' later this week. He declined to specify which ones.
   Bush spoke briefly to reporters after meeting with
President-elect Carlos Andreas Perez of Venezuela. Responding to
questions, Bush said:
   _He and Perez discussed Latin American debt, Nicaragua and other
subjects, and ``the relationship is off to a very good start.''
   _Bush's administration taking office Jan. 20 could not meet with
the Palestine Liberation Organization based on Yasser Arafat's
speech Tuesday in Geneva. Other officials said Arafat's speech
failed to meet U.S. requirements such as explicit acceptance of
Israel's right to exist and renunciation of terrorism. ``We've got
to get a much clearer statement of everything,'' Bush said.
   As for the Cabinet, Tower is undergoing detailed background
checks covering such matters as his defense industry connections and
allegations made by his ex-wife in their divorce case, various
sources close to the Tower and the transition have said.
   There have also been reports that the Bush team wants to name
Tower's top aides at the Pentagon at the same time the secretary is
chosen, thereby making sure they will be Bush choices.
   Fuller said of Tower, ``There's been the assurance that he would
be involved in the review and evaluation of senior appointments to
the Defense Department should he be chosen as secretary.''
   Sources close to Tower say the FBI could complete its background
work this week. However, checks on other defense appointees could
delay the announcement further.
   For energy secretary, Fuller said Peter Johnson, former head of
Oregon's Bonneville Power Administration, is ``still in the
running'' after being interviewed by transition aides Monday.
   Former Rep. Henson Moore of Louisiana also is under consideration.
   Saying ``a lot of work needs to be done'' in the nuclear area,
along with the department's traditional focus on oil and gas
interests, Fuller said, ``We're looking for somebody who has got the
technical, scientific and management background to deal with that
side of the equation.''
   EPA Administrator Lee M. Thomas has been mentioned as a possible
energy secretary because he is an expert in waste cleanup.
   Bush, meanwhile, met Tuesday with Coretta Scott King, widow of
the slain civil rights leader, Martin Luther King Jr. Mrs. King said
the president-elect reiterated that he would name a black to his
Cabinet.
   ``We didn't mention names,'' she said. She gave a positive report
on the meeting, telling reporters, ``The goals of him and his
administration are very close to the goals I would like to see.''
   One black contender for a Cabinet job is Dr. Louis Sullivan,
president of Morehouse School of Medicine in Atlanta. Fuller said he
was on ``a short list'' the transition team is looking at for
secretary of health and human services.
   Other people Fuller said are still in contention for various
positions are Rep. Jack Kemp of New York and former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole.
   Mrs. Dole, once mentioned as a possible United Nations
ambassador, a post since filled, has been spoken of recently as a
potential head of the Environmental Protection Agency.
   Kemp was considered a contender for secretary of housing and
urban development, but a transition source said he no longer was
under consideration for the Cabinet.
   Fuller said Constance Horner, head of the Office of Personnel
Management, ``is certainly on short lists for consideration in a
couple of areas,'' including labor secretary.
   Robert Teeter, co-director of the transition office, said there
was ``no basis'' to the rumor that he had turned down an offer to be
deputy White House chief of staff. Teeter, reached at his home in
Ann Arbor, Mich., said he was spending a few days sorting out what
he wanted to do next year.
</TEXT>
