<2ND_LINE>AM-Construction Collapse,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Floor Gives Way; Five Construction Workers Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Part of a floor on a building under
construction gave way as workers were pouring concrete, injuring
five men in a 40-foot fall into the basement, authorities said.
   Police said a sixth worker avoided falling by hanging onto a
support when only one edge of the floor held.
   ``It gave way almost like a trap door. It swung down,'' said
police officer Richard F. Bates.
   ``When we first arrived, there was some panic that something else
would fall,'' Bates said. ``There were pieces of concrete and pieces
of Styrofoam falling.''
   The men were working on a raised main floor of the Fuller
Laboratories building under construction at Worcester Polytechnic
Institute, school spokesman Michael Dorsey said. They fell from
there to the sub-basement level.
   ``There just wasn't anything underneath (the main floor),''
Dorsey said. ``The main level is about two stories up from the
street.''
   Police said the workers, employed by D and M Concrete Flooring
Co. of Fall River, were taken to the University of Massachusetts
Medical Center.
   The five were identified as Jose Robeiro, 43, of Clinton, Kenneth
Gould, 48, of Worcester, Carlos Sousa, 31, of Hudson, Joao Mello,
33, of Clinton and William Cunningham, 39, of Stoneham.
   None of the workers were believed to have suffered critical
injuries, said a University of Massachusetts nursing supervisor.
Robeiro was admitted in stable condition, while the other four
injured workers were being transferred to another hospital.
</TEXT>
