<1ST_LINE>a w BC-YE--Decision-Contras Adv00   12-13 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-YE--Decision-Contras, Adv 00,0563</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>1988 Was Beginning of End of U.S. Support for Nicaraguan Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After seven years, tens of thousands of lost
lives and almost $300 million in spending, the United States is
looking for a way out of President Reagan's Contra policy in
Nicaragua.
   Although President-elect George Bush's policy on the Nicaraguan
rebels remains short on detail, Contra opponents and supporters
alike agree that 1988 probably will be viewed as the beginning of
the end for the anti-Sandinista insurgents.
   ``Nineteen eighty-eight was a year in which the policy ...
essentially ended, because the Contras by the end of the year had
become a non-factor,'' said Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., who led
the losing fight in the House of Representatives to continue
military aid for the Contras.
   ``Basically, the war has come to a halt,'' said Rep. David
Bonior, D-Mich., a leader of anti-Contra forces in the House.
   The rebels, who began the year with as many as 16,000 fighters
launching attacks inside Nicaragua, ended it with most of their
forces huddled under makeshift black plastic shelters in camps along
the Honduran border.
   Throughout his presidency, Reagan made the Contras a top
foreign-policy priority.
   Critics said the president's romantic fervor for those he equated
with America's founding fathers, and his fear of Soviet influence in
the region, blinded him to Latin America's larger economic problems
and locked the United States into a no-win policy.
   But Reagan's supporters said military force was the only way to
move the Sandinistas toward fulfilling promises of democratization
made to the Organization of American States after they took power in
1979.
   After years of military aid to the rebels, both covert and overt,
the House voted narrowly Feb. 3 to cut off the flow of weapons,
heeding the call of Costa Rican President Oscar Arias Sanchez and
House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, to ``give peace a chance.''
   The Contras' last military support ran out Feb. 29, and no direct
U.S. weapons aid has flowed since.
   The Democrats, not wanting to be seen as abandoning the rebels
entirely, later approved $75 million in ``humanitarian'' aid for the
Contras _ food, medicine and shelter.
   A shaky cease-fire took effect in 1988 in the Sandinista-Contra
war. Estimates now are that some 10,000 rebel troops, unable to
mount an offensive but unwilling to disband, remain encamped just
inside Honduras, with as many as 30,000 family members.
   Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams, a champion of Contra
aid, contends that the withdrawal of U.S. military aid from the
Contras has emboldened the Sandinistas.
   ``There is more repression (in Nicaragua), more subversion in El
Salvador, essentially undiminished Soviet aid levels,'' Abrams said.
He says the only solution is to revive the rebel resistance to the
Nicaraguan government.
   But few of Washington's key actors still share Abrams' hard-line
stance. Bush's designated secretary of state, James Baker, known as
a pragmatist, is unlikely to begin his relationship with Congress
with a surefire confrontation. And the new House elected in November
will be slightly more anti-Contra than the last.
   Something will have to be done by April 1, when the last of the
non-lethal aid to the rebels expires.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Year-End Editions</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0234 </DOCNO>
