<NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>Wisdom of Whale Decision Still Debated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maybe the local food was too good. Or
maybe they were too young to know better. For whatever reason, in
mid-October three malingering whales became trapped in Alaska's
arctic ice _ and caught in the camera eye of the world.
   Roy Ahmaogak was the first to spot the three California gray
whales, ringed by encroachin on Alaska's northern
coast.
   The Eskimo whaling captain could have gone for the easy kill. But
he wanted to help fill Barrow's whale quota with bowheads, larger
animalsg ice off Barrow. He passed the grays by.
   His hunting instincts told him, however, it wasn't right to let
them suffer. He sought advice from his fellow whalers, and they
sought the advice of the National Marine Fisheries Service.
   Ron Morris, a service biologist, was in Barrow discussing the
matter with the Eskimos when he learned that the key decision had
already been made. Word came from Washington that he should do
everything possible to save the whales.
   The two-week rescue effort that followed captured the world's
imagination, and cost more than $1 million.
   Day after day, rescuers tried untested techniques for freeing the
20,000-pound animals. Finally, the combined efforts of the Eskimos,
U.S. government agenciesdio
warnings, and it gave no indication it was not hostile _ ``so our
grief and despair are tempered by the knowledge we did what we had
to do when we had to do it,'' Rogers said.
   The Navy board of inquiry agreed.
   ``The USS Vincennes did not purposely shoot down an Iranian
commercial airliner. Rather, it engaged an aircraft the commanding
officer ... believed to be hostile and a threat to his ship.''
   The Navy report also said, however, that the ``fog of war,'' the
stress of combat and the unconscious distortion of data by the
Vincennes crew may have played a major role in the incident.
   An investigatory panel of the International Civil Aviation
Organization found the Navy culpable, saying U.S. warships in the
Gulf should have been aware of and monitoring such scheduled
commercial air traffic.
   Little more than a month after the accident, Iran and Iraq would
begin a cease-fire that was still holding months later, ending eight
years of bloody warfare on land and at sea. Oil tankers could
transit the Gulf without any need for U.S. escort.
   Ironically, some American analysts concluded that the loss of
Flight 655 contributed to Iran's acceptance of the truce,
dramatizing to that nation's leaders that they could neither defeat
Iraq nor force the U.S. Navy out of the GUlf, and that civilians
would increasingly bear the consequences.
   Within the Navy, the tragedy produced plans for some changes in
training and minor equipment alterations. The Navy also added
equipment for monitoring civilian air traffic.
   But by refusing to take disciplinary action against Rogers or his
crew, the Pentagon also underscored its willingness to back up any
skipper as long as he didn't make the mistake of the USS Stark
commander in May 1987 and take the first hit.
   ``The orders given to all skippers entering the Persian Gulf made
clear that there should be no repeat'' of the Stark incident, in
which that frigate was hit by two missiles fired by an Iraqi jet,
says Rep. Les Aspen, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee.
   ``We all know that what Captain Rogers did was in error. The
tragedy is that, through the weight of the evidence, a decision to
shoot was logical.''
</TEXT>
