<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   12-13 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0535</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve policymakers, concerned about
renewed signs of inflationary pressures, are poised to drive
interest rates higher in a move that will put the central bank on a
collision course with the incoming Bush administration, private
economists say.
   Many analysts said Monday the Fed has already begun to tighten
credit conditions and they predicted its Federal Open Market
Committee would vote for more restrictive policies at closed-door
strategy sessions today and Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's commercial banks enjoyed record
profits in the July-September quarter, but a top regulator sounded a
cautionary note about an increase in bad loans and rising bank
involvement in leveraged corporate buyouts.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said Monday the 13,239
federally insured commercial banks earned $5.9 billion in the third
quarter, topping the previous record of $5.8 billion in the same
quarter last year.
   ``The statistics are good, but they're not quite as good as they
might appear on the surface,'' FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman told
reporters.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 10 million Americans lost their jobs to
plant closings and layoffs from 1983 to 1988, the government said.
   Nearly 4.7 million of the 9.7 million laid off during the 5-year
period were ``tenured'' workers, meaning they lost jobs they had
held for three years or more, the Bureau of Labor Statistics said.
   Seven out of ten of those workers had new jobs as of January this
year, but only a little more than half of those re-employed matched
or exceeded their previous incomes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A potentially dangerous shortage of nurses in
the United States is best solved by boosting pay scales for career
caregivers and making sure they have time to be nurses instead of
clerks, a federal commission said.
   ``It is the sincere belief of the commission that the health of
this nation will be at risk if the changes suggested in these
recommendations do not occur,'' said the report issued Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennwalt Corp. received a $760 million takeover
offer from a New York investor group, boosting the chemical maker's
stock price and setting the stage for what analysts called a
possibly nasty fight.
   Pennwalt officials declined to comment Monday on the cash tender
offer from Centaur Partners, an investment partnership headed by two
East Coast financiers who already own 12.7 percent of the company's
stock and are offering $100 a share for the rest.
   Pennwalt's stock jumped $14.75 a share by late afternoon to $98
in heavy New York Stock Exchange trading.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The company seeking to acquire Polaroid Corp.
amended its takeover offer to meet a federal court order that was
blocking the bid.
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. said Monday its hostile $42-a-share bid
for Polaroid was now contingent on whether a judge in Delaware
invalidated or rescinded the Polaroid employee stock ownership plan
being challenged by Shamrock.
   Analysts said the move would not dramatically alter Shamrock's
$2.6 billion tender offer, which has been in abeyance pending court
action.
</TEXT>
