<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0474</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co., after spurning Grand
Metropolitan PLC's earlier proposal for a negotiated buyout deal,
has rejected the British company's sweetened $5.5 billion hostile
tender offer.
   The $63-a-share cash offer for the food and restaurant company
represented a $3-a-share increase over Grand Met's earlier tender
offer, but Pillsbury's board of directors called it inadequate
Monday and recommended shareholders hold on to their stock.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc. asked West Point-Pepperell Inc. to
call a special shareholder meeting to consider Farley's $1.4 billion
takeover bid, and the textile maker promptly indicated it would
review the shareholder vote calling for the meeting.
   Farley, an apparel manufacturer, had received requests for a
meeting from shareholders representing more than the required 25
percent of Pepperell's shares, Chairman William Farley said in a
statement Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic advertising spending growth is expected
to slow to a 14-year low of 6.1 percent in 1989 and trail overall
economic growth for the first time since 1975, a prominent
advertising forecaster said.
   ``It will be a rather mediocre year,'' Robert J. Coen, senior
vice president and director of forecasting for the advertising
agency McCann-Erickson, said Monday.
   He warned that the underlying sluggish trend could ``even become
worse if the economy falters and drifts into a recession.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An arbitration board has awarded steelworkers
up to $10 million in back pay in a dispute between the workers and
USX Corp. over outside hiring, the United Steelworkers of America
said.
   The board's decision means USX, owner of the nation's biggest
steelmaker, must reimburse workers at overtime rates in instances _
as many as 1,100 _ where work was lost because of outside hiring
that violated the union's contract.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's trade surplus rose sharply in November,
growing by 38 percent to $6.55 billion from $4.75 billion a year
earlier.
   Economists, after hearing the news Monday, said the country's
attempts to cut its trade surplus by boosting domestic demand
apparently have contributed to economic growth without really
reducing exports.
   Japan's surplus with the United States climbed to $4.42 billion
from $4.21 billion a year earlier, the ministry said, reversing 11
straight months of decline.
</TEXT>
