<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     12-13 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heating, Crude Oil Rise on Cold Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The abrupt arrival of sub-zero temperatures in
the Northeast gave a boost to heating and crude oil futures.
   ``The cold weather news did give heating oil a good lead,'' Bob
Baker, an energy analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said
Monday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
wholesale heating oil settled at 50.20 cents a gallon, up 0.70 cent,
after having risen 1.42 cents on Friday.
   The blast of arctic air _ which set low-temperature records in
some areas _ also lent support to crude oil futures, analysts said.
   The January contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, settled at $16.06 a 42-gallon barrel, up 22
cents from Friday, when it gained 40 cents.
   It was the first time crude prices have closed above $16 since
OPEC members reached a new production agreement late last month.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries signed a new
agreement in November setting a daily production quota of 18.5
million barrels and a benchmark price of $18 a barrel. The new
agreement, which would lower the cartel's production from more than
22 million barrels, is to go into effect Jan. 1.
   Analysts said volume was thin in one of the quietest sessions in
months.
   ``Prices should hold firm until we get more news, or hear more
from OPEC about how much they're producing or if they're cheating,
and we won't know for another month,'' said Dave Kaplan, manager of
energy options for Elders Futures Inc.
   January unleaded gasoline, which gained 0.53 cents on Friday,
fell 0.26 to 44.20 cents a gallon Monday.
   Analysts said gasoline stocks have risen in the last few weeks
and investors expect to see a bigger increase on Tuesday when the
American Petroleum Institute releases its weekly statistics on
energy supplies.
</TEXT>
