<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pennwalt Bjt   12-13 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pennwalt, Bjt,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investor Group Makes $760 Million Offer For Chemical Company; Stock
Jumps</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Securities analysts say a takeover brawl may be
brewing for Pennwalt Corp., a diversified chemical maker that
received a $760 million offer by a pair of financiers who have been
eying the company for months.
   Pennwalt stock surged $14.75 a share to close at $98 in New York
Stock Exchange trading Monday after the investment partnership
Centaur Partners said it would pay $100 a share cash for the 87.3
percent of the company it doesn't own.
   Company officials declined to comment on the tender offer from
Centaur Partners, which came in the midst of a major restructuring
of Pennwalt that was aimed partly at thwarting unwelcome acquirers.
   But Wall Street strategists who follow the Philadelphia-based
company said there was plenty of room for the bidding to go higher,
perhaps attracting rival offers.
   ``I think the company's going to fight it tooth and nail,'' said
Donald A. Pattison, a securities analyst for Cyrus J. Lawrence Inc.
in New York. ``This is not going to be over next week.''
   Centaur principals Abbey J. Butler and Melvyn J. Estrin said in a
letter to the company's chairman and chief executive Edwin E. Tuttle
that they had all the financing needed to complete the deal and were
prepared to negotiate all aspects of their offer, including price.
   ``We believe that our offer represents a fair price and is in the
best interest of Pennwalt's shareholders,'' they stated in the
letter.
   But in a signal that the bidders expected a fight, they sued
Pennwalt in Philadelphia federal court to block its so-called poison
pill shareholders rights takeover defense, which Pennwalt and many
other companies have adopted to thwart unwelcome bids.
   Pennwalt manufactures and markets industrial chemicals used in a
range of products, from swimming pool chlorine to the chemical odor
in natural gas that alerts consumers to leaks. It has 9,000
employees and annual sales exceeding $1 billion.
   Pennwalt also is a leading maker of chlorinated plastic, commonly
used in building cable insulation, and has operations in mineral and
petroleum processing and industrial equipment.
   The size of the Pennwalt takeover offer isn't large when measured
against the multi-billion-dollar bidding wars that have shaped 1988
into the year of unprecedented megadeals.
   Nevertheless, Pennwalt's vulnerability to a takeover typifies the
predicament many diversified industrial companies are facing,
because their operations in many cases are worth more individually
than the company is as a whole.
   By some estimates, Pennwalt's so-called ``bustup value'' is
approximately $120 a share, or more than $900 million.
   Speculation about Pennwalt as a possible takeover target has
persisted since July, when Centaur Partners disclosed it had a 6.5
percent stake that it subsequently doubled.
   The company's management responded by undertaking a major
restructuring that so far has resulted in the sale of its
pharmaceutical business, maker of items such as Desenex foot powder
and Allerest allergy medicine.
   The proceeds of the $460 million sale to Fisons PLC of Britain
were used to help repurchase nearly 40 percent of Pennwalt's
outstanding shares.
   Although those moves boosted the price of the remaining stock,
they evidently weren't sufficient for Centaur principals Butler and
Estrin, who have been financial partners for years and have dabbled
in other takeover investments before.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 0112EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pillsbury Bjt   12-13 0900</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury, Bjt,0928</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Expecting Grand Met To Sweeten Bid Further</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even though Grand Metropolitan PLC says
it has made its ``last and best'' offer to buy Pillsbury Co.,
officials of the food and restaurant giant are expecting the bid to
be sweetened again.
   But for that to happen, Pillsbury's cornerstone ``poison pill''
defense must be left intact, lawyers for the Minneapolis-based
company said Monday in response to legal attacks against the pill by
Grand Met and dissident Pillsbury shareholders.
   The British liquor, hotel, retailing and gambling conglomerate
challenged the pill for the second time before Justice William Duffy
in the Delaware Chancery Court. Duffy, who earlier ruled in favor of
Pillsbury, a Delaware corporation, took the case under advisement
and did not say when he would make a decision.
   Pillsbury lawyer Steven Rothschild said Duffy's original decision
to uphold the pill benefited Pillsbury shareholders because Grand
Met on Monday raised its all-cash tender offer to $63 a share, or
$5.5 billion, up from $60 a share, or $5.23 billion.
   Pillsbury's board of directors called the sweetened bid
inadequate and recommended shareholders hold on to their stock. The
offer is set to expire Dec. 23.
   Pillsbury stock jumped $3.87{ higher to $62.12{ a share Monday on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``The court respectfully should let things run their course,''
Rothschild said in a courtroom crowded with Wall Street arbitrage
experts and other spectators. ``We're in a very fluid situation.
   ``The pill is serving its function,'' Rothschild said. ``They
know it makes economic sense for them to further increase their
offer.''
   But Robert Rifkind, a lawyer for Grand Met, said he had been told
by the company that $63 a share was its ``last and best'' tender
offer.
   Grand Met Chairman Allen Sheppard, in weekend meetings with
Pillsbury Chairman Philip Smith, offered to buy the company for $65
a share on friendly terms, but the offer was rejected. Stuart Gold,
a lawyer for Grand Met, said the higher offer would only stand for a
friendly deal because it would eliminate costs related to the
takeover fight.
   Grand Met conditioned both tender offers on the removal of the
pill, or shareholders' rights plan, which it has said would make a
takeover prohibitively expensive.
   Grand Met also is seeking to block Pillsbury's proposed spinoff
of its Burger King subsidiary, which Gold said would add as much as
$8 a share in tax expenses to the cost of a takeover.
   Partly because Pillsbury has not offered an alternative to the
$63 tender offer of equal, immediate value, the pill should be
removed to give Grand Met control, Rifkind said.
   ``Shareholders have a fundamental right to sell their shares to
whomever they please, whenever they want,'' Rifkind said. ``If they
(Pillsbury) can merely label it (the offer) as inadequate and that
is allowed to sustain the poison pill, there will be no more tender
offers.''
   ``Shareholders will have lost a fundamental right to sell their
shares to the highest bidder,'' Rifkind said.
   The best Pillsbury has been able to offer shareholders is a vague
recapitalization program that its advisers say could improve the
company's value to the range of $68 to $73 a share, Rifkind and Gold
said.
   And those projections are based on a 5-year plan to spin off
Burger King and have it sold in addition to selling Pillsbury in a
few years, Rifkind said.
   ``They're talking about the distant future at best,'' Rifkind
said. ``What they are not offering shareholders is a trading value
anything like the Grand Met offer.''
   Gold said the valuations of up to $73 a share for Pillsbury are
based on ``super-aggressive projections'' that are ``wildly
optimistic'' about management's ability to turn the faltering
company around.
   ``Their refusal to redeem the pill is sort of the nuclear weapon
in the arsenal of the board,'' said Rifkind, who said there is no
threat to merit its use.
   Grand Met's lawyers repeatedly noted that 87.4 percent of
outstanding Pillsbury shares had been tendered to Grand Met and not
withdrawn as of Friday.
   But Rothschild said the percentage is high because Grand Met's
offer is ``coercive.'' Shareholders fear they will be left out of
the deal if they do not tender their shares even though Grand Met
has said the offer would be extended to those who don't, Rothschild
said.
   He said there are circumstances under which Grand Met would not
be obligated to pay the offered price to shareholders who don't
tender.
   Rifkind said Duffy should block the Burger King spinoff, which
has a record date of Dec. 19, for the same reason he should
invalidate the pill because the spinoff would amount to a ``poison
tax.''
   Under the proposed spinoff, Pillsbury shareholders would be
issued stock in a newly separate Burger King, which would borrow
money to issue a special dividend.
   Rothschild said Grand Met could prevent the spinoff of Burger
King by offering a fair price for Pillsbury.
   ``If Grand Met doesn't want to step up to the plate with a higher
offer before this date arrives,'' Rothschild said, ``then that's a
business decision they have to make.
   ``Grand Met must recognize and it better recognize that only the
surface of our negotiating skills have been scratched,'' Rothschild
said. ``Let Mr. Sheppard make no mistake about it: He's not going to
buy Pillsbury on the cheap.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
