<DOCNO> AP881213-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 0114EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AdSpending Bjt   12-13 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ad Spending, Bjt,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forecaster Expects 6.1 Percent Ad Spending Growth in 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The traditional post-Olympic slump and weakness
in local advertising spending are being blamed as projections for
1989 point to the slowest growth in domestic ad spending in 14 years.
   ``It will be a rather mediocre year,'' Robert J. Coen, senior
vice president and director of forecasting for the advertising
agency McCann-Erickson, said Monday in projecting 6.1 percent ad
spending growth next year.
   He warned that the underlying sluggish trend could ``even become
worse if the economy falters and drifts into a recession.''
   The 6.1 percent growth to $125.6 billion in 1989 would be down
from the 7.9 percent rise Coen expects this year and it would be the
slowest growth since a 4.8 percent rate of increase in 1975.
   A decline in ad spending growth is typical in the year after the
Olympics and a presidential election, both of which are believed to
attract extra money into advertising.
   In post-Olympic years, the dropoff in national ad spending has
sometimes been cushioned by local ad growth. But growth in the local
category is also expected to suffer this time around, Coen said.
   Coen said he expects national ad spending will rise 6.5 percent
next year, while local spending will be up 5.6 percent. National ad
spending rose an estimated 8.9 percent this year, while local ad
spending rose about 6.7 percent.
   He said 1989 will also be the first time since 1975 that ad
spending failed to exceed the expected 6.8 percent growth including
inflation that many economists forecast for the economy next year.
   Meanwhile, foreign ad spending was projected to exceed U.S. ad
spending for the first time this year and is expected to widen its
lead next year.
   Coen said foreign ad spending grew 18 percent to about $121.4
billion in 1988, compared with spending of $118.3 billion in the
United States.
   Next year, he said while U.S. ad spending rises to $125.6
billion, foreign ad spending should rise 12 percent to $136 billion.
   In the U.S. market, Coen blamed the sluggish pace of local ad
spending growth on ``turmoil in retail marketing'' partly to recent
acquisitions and restructuring in the retail business. He said the
activity has left less money available for spending on local
advertising.
   He also said the volume of classified advertising in newspapers
appears to have flattened out after several years of rapid growth.
He cited a decline in real estate activity due to higher mortgage
rates and slower growth in help-wanted advertising.
   He expects local ad spending will reach $55.3 billion next year.
   Coen said he expects 1989 spending on the national broadcast
media will rise 4.5 percent to $21.2 billion, national print
spending will be up 5.8 percent to $10.2 billion and other national
ad spending such as the fast-growing direct mail will be up 7.8
percent to $38.9 billion.
   Spending on network television will be flat because of the
absence of an estimated $1 billion in spending related to the
Olympics, but cable and syndicated television should have
double-digit gains again, Coen said.
   National ad spending in newspapers should be flat, while spending
in magazines may fall back, particularly if automotive and toiletry
sectors scale back the growth in their ad spending.
   Coen was more optimistic about his longer-term outlook for ad
spending.
   ``The correction in over-expanded ad spending of the early 1980s
has been completed and most budgets are back in line with other
operating costs,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881213-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 0142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Polaroid Bjt   12-13 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polaroid, Bjt,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamrock Amends Offer for Polaroid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Disney-held company seeking to acquire Polaroid
Corp. has amended its takeover offer to meet a federal court order
that had blocked the $2.6 billion bid from going forward.
   Shamrock Holdings Inc. said Monday its hostile $42-a-share bid
for the instant camera pioneer was now contingent on whether a judge
in Delaware invalidates or rescinds Polaroid's controversial
employee stock ownership plan.
   Analysts said the move would not dramatically alter Shamrock's
tender offer, which has been in abeyance pending court action.
   In Delaware, U.S. District Judge Caleb Wright on Monday ordered
Shamrock to modify the language of the offer and issue a news
release on the changes. The Burbank, Calif.-based television
company, wholly-owned by the Roy E. Disney family, met the
conditions immediately.
   Shamrock said it would purchase Polaroid shares under the
$42-a-share offer only if the employee stock plan is invalidated by
the Delaware Chancery Court, where Shamrock is challenging the plan.
   Previously, Shamrock had maintained that the deal could have
proceeded merely if the 10 million shares in the stock plan were
ruled not part of the company's outstanding shares.
   If the $300 million employee stock plan is invalidated, Shamrock
would try to buy 62 million outstanding shares. If not, it would be
faced with acquiring about 72 million shares under an earlier
$40-a-share offer, analysts said.
   Shamrock currently owns 5 million shares of Polaroid.
   Polaroid spokeswoman Marcia Phillips said the company had no
comment on the development.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Philadelphia last month
ordered the district court to issue a preliminary injunction
blocking the takeover bid until Shamrock clarified its position on
the employee stock plan.
   The plan places 14 percent of Polaroid stock in employee hands, a
move Shamrock claims was designed intentionally to defend against
its hostile takeover bid. Under Delaware law, a hostile bidder must
acquire at least 85 percent of a company.
   Polaroid, which introduced instant snapshots in 1948, is based in
Cambridge, Mass., but incorporated in Delaware.
   ``I don't think this implies a change in the approach of Shamrock
to the offer or really any material change in the offer,'' said Alex
Henderson, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Arguments in the Chancery Court case are scheduled for Friday.
Shamrock said it would extend its offer for Polaroid past next
Monday's expiration date to wait for a court ruling.
</TEXT>
