<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady in Thin European Trading, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was holding steady in lackluster trading
in Europe late this morning, and traders said they expected little
movement before the Wednesday release of U.S. trade figures for
October.
   Gold prices moved up.
   Several traders said that provided the trade report doesn't
contain any major surprises, the U.S. currency is likely to maintain
its stability through the end of the week, and possibly through the
end of the year.
   A widely expected increase in a key West German interest rate on
Thursday and a possible increase in U.S. interest rates also aren't
expected to have a major impact on the dollar.
   ``Most of the banks are done for the year,'' one Rome trader
said. In addition, he said, the market feels that ``there's a
political will to keep the dollar stable.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.14 yen to a closing 123.06 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 123.20 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.7438 West German marks, up from 1.7410; 1.4680
Swiss francs, up from 1.4650; 5.9625 French francs, up from 5.9520;
1.9552 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9635; 1,285.30 Italian lire, up
from 1,282.75; 1.2008 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1983.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.8300, compared with
$1.8418 Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $419.50 a troy ounce,
down from $419.75 bid late Monday. But at midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price of
$420.05.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $420.00, up from $419.25 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 75 cents to close at a bid
$421.54.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.14 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Monday.
