<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up In Tokyo, Stocks Tumble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen in thin
trading today as the market awaited new U.S. trade figures. Share
prices fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 123.06 yen, up 0.14 yen from Monday's close
of 122.92 yen. The currency opened at 122.90 yen and stayed in a
narrow range between 122.89 yen and 123.15 yen.
   Takamasa Yamasaki of Daiwa Bank said most currency traders were
sitting on the sidelines to await the U.S. Commerce Department's
announcement Wednesday of the nation's trade figures for October.
   Meanwhile, Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita indicated today
he will maintain the central bank's present monetary stance.
   Speaking at a luncheon, Sumita said the current dollar-yen
exchange level is more or less acceptable.
   On the stock market, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which
shed 121.13 points on Monday, fell 74.48 points, or 0.25 percent,
Tuesday, closing at 29,597.81. After the index dropped 18.91 points
shortly after trading began, following a similar trend on overseas
markets, the Tokyo market could not reverse its downtrend.
   ``The index fell because domestic interest rates rose as the
dollar's uptrend began,'' said an analyst with Nomura Securities,
Japan's largest brokerage.
   He said rising interest rates generally discourage interest in
buying stocks.
   ``It's kind of a formula in stock trading,'' he added.
   Other dealers said most institutional investors, as well as
individuals, were sitting on the sidelines ahead of the U.S. trade
report.
</TEXT>
