<HEAD>London Shares Up At Midday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were higher but below their morning
peaks at midday Tuesday, boosted by a growing belief that British
interest rates won't have to be increased further.
   Dealers said prices were marked up in very thin trading, with
many players still cautious ahead of Wednesday's release of U.S.
trade figures for October.
   But property and retailing stocks, hurt recently by fears of yet
higher interest rates, proved especially strong Tuesday as the
interest rate concerns receded.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was up 9.9
points, or 0.6 percent, at 1,757.8 at about 12:45 p.m., below the
peak of 15.5 points up.
   Volume was a modest 287.8 million shares, but up from 230.1
million shares at the same time a day earlier.
   The market continued to react to Monday's news that British
retail sales volume dropped 0.5 percent in November from October,
apparently suggesting that recent interest rate increases are
already cutting back consumer spending.
   That suggests the government won't have to boost base lending
rates above the present 13 percent to choke off the consumer boom
and squeeze out inflationary pressures, dealers said.
