<2ND_LINE>PM-Acustar Layoffs,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Announces Layoff Of 500 Acustar Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chrysler Corp. subsidiary says it will lay off
500 workers at Detroit Trim, one of four Acustar Inc. plants that
the United Auto Workers union agreed to allow to close in its
contract with Chrysler.
   The workers' last day will be Dec. 23, which is when production
is scheduled to end, company and union officials said Monday.
   The plant makes seat covers and other soft automotive trim.
   Last March, Chrysler announced the plant would close. Chrysler
Vice President Anthony St. John said Monday the exact closing date
was only recently determined.
   The plant employed 1,064 people when the closing was announced,
and about 800 employees are still working. The workers remaining
after Dec. 23 will be laid off March 3, Chrysler and UAW officials
said.
   All Detroit Trim workers will be eligible for the Chrysler-UAW
job bank and will continue to receive full paychecks and benefits
until they find other jobs within Chrysler.
   ``Most of the people are disturbed about leaving their jobs,''
said Sam Palazzola, president of Local 212. ``I don't know what's in
the future.''
   In addition to Detroit Trim, the UAW contract allowed Chrysler to
sell or close its Amplex Van Wert powdered metal plant in Van Wert,
Ohio; Trenton, Mich., Chemical and Detroit Forge.
</TEXT>
