<2ND_LINE>PM-Farley-Pepperell,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farley Wants Pepperell Shareholder Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc. is asking West Point-Pepperell Inc. to
call a shareholder meeting to consider a $1.4 billion takeover bid,
but the Georgia-based textile maker first wants to determine who
supports such a gathering.
   Farley, a Chicago-based apparel manufacturer, had received
requests for a meeting from shareholders representing more than 25
percent of Pepperell's shares, Chairman William Farley said Monday.
   ``We can now look forward to hearing that the board of West
Point-Pepperell has set a meeting date so that our offer finally can
be considered,'' Farley said.
   A Pepperell spokeswoman said the company received the request and
asked the Corporation Trust Co. of Wilmington, Del., to review the
solicitations that have been received by Farley.
   A report should be issued by Dec. 19, said the spokeswoman, who
asked that her name not be used.
   Pepperell stock on Monday rose 75 cents to close at 42\.
   Based in West Point, Ga., West Point-Pepperell is the country's
largest publicly held textile manufacturer. It makes Gold Toe socks,
Arrow shirts and Martex towels.
   Farley, maker of Fruit of the Loom underwear and several other
clothing brands, last Wednesday extended its $48-per-share buyout
bid until midnight EST Dec. 14. The company announced on Dec. 2 its
intention to seek the special shareholder meeting.
   ``Our intention from the outset has been to sit down with
Pepperell's board and negotiate a mutually acceptable acquisition of
Pepperell,'' Farley said. ``But the board would not meet with us.''
   At the meeting, Farley would ask shareholders to replace the
board with nominees representing the Chicago company, Farley said.
   The new board would then dismantle defenses Pepperell has
arranged against takeovers.
   Farley is seeking to overturn Pepperell's ``poison pill''
shareholder rights plan in court. The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals has scheduled a hearing on the matter in Atlanta for the
week of Jan. 9.
</TEXT>
