<2ND_LINE>PM-Popeyes-Church's,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Clears Way For Popeyes To Begin Buying Church's Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken and Biscuits
could start moving forward again in its hostile takeover of Church's
Fried Chicken following a federal judge's approval of certain
financial disclosures by Popeyes owner Al Copeland.
   Copeland has said he's been offered 14.6 million Church's shares
_ about 40.6 percent of the company's outstanding common stocks _ at
$8 per share. But U.S. District Judge Charles Schwartz issued an
order Nov. 28 preventing Copeland from buying the tendered stock
until 10 days after he provided additional financial information
related to the buyout.
   Schwartz approved the disclosures Monday and agreed to lift the
blocking order as soon as Copeland makes some minor court-ordered
changes.
   Popeyes attorney Peter Butler said the New Orleans-based company
was pleased with the ruling and planned to submit the new text by
Wednesday.
   Among other items, the disclosures lay out a tentative plan for
disposing of Church's 1,076 company-owned restaurants. Copeland
wants to keep 83 restaurants under the Church's name, put 303 under
the Popeyes name, and sell 440 for about $160 million. He would also
immediately close 250 Church's restaurants.
   San Antonio-based Church's announced Monday it was closing 120
restaurants in 20 states, effective Saturday. Ernest Renaud,
president and chief executive officer, said the stores lost $7.4
million in the past year.
   ``They should have been closed a year ago, but this is just part
of my plan to make the company profitable again,'' Renaud said.
   Church's board of directors is trying to find other buyers to
fend off Popeyes $290 million buyout offer, which it has said is not
enough.
   But the directors have been sued by a shareholder who says the
Popeyes offer is fair and the board's refusal to accept it could
harm shareholders' financial interests.
</TEXT>
