<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Plessey     12-13 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Plessey,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC To Examine Siemens-GEC Bid For Plessey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community will
examine the joint bid for Plessey Co., a British electronics
company, by rival General Electric Co. and Siemens AG of Germany
following a formal complaint by Plessey, an EEC spokesman said on
Tuesday.
   The spokesman said that Plessey's complaint focused on a breach
of EEC antitrust rules by Siemens and GEC in making the joint 1.7
billion pound bid, which amounts to $3.1 billion.
   The EEC bans industrial agreements which are likely to distort
free competition.
   The Plessey case is the second major takeover battle that the EEC
has been asked to deal with in recent months and shows that its role
in policing mergers in the EEC is growing, the spokesman said.
   In August, the EEC blocked a consortium bid for Irish Distillers
Group and forced the companies in the consortium to bid
independently for the Irish whiskey maker.
   Normally the EEC can intervene in mergers only after they take
place except if the takeover involves a consortium of companies. It
is trying to persuade EEC govermments to adopt rules that will allow
the EEC antitrust authorities to intervene in mergers before they
occur.
</TEXT>
