<HEAD>MITI Official Says Japan Won't Meet Surplus Reduction Target</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior official of Japan's Ministry of
International Trade and Industry said Tuesday that Japan won't be
able to reduce its trade surplus to the government's target for
calendar 1988.
   The official did not predict how much the surplus would shrink.
He noted, however, that over the past three monthly reports the
trade surplus has risen in comparison to a year earlier, probably
putting the target out of reach.
   The government's target was to cut about $11 billion off Japan's
1987 surplus, which came to $79.8 billion. The surplus in calendar
1987 was narrower than the 1986 surplus of $82.7 billion.
   On Monday, the Finance Ministry said Japan's merchandise trade
surplus soared 38 percent in November to $6.55 billion in comparison
with $4.75 billion in November 1987.
