<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0354</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices drifted lower today, reflecting
nervousness about interest rates in advance of an important report
on trade.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which lost 3.91 points
on Monday, was down another 5.87 at 2,133.71 after the 90 minutes of
trading.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of 7 to 4 among
issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 391 up, 739 down
and 617 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 40.59 million shares at
midmorning compared with 45.10 million shares at the same point in
Monday's session.
   Trading was subdued today as the market looked ahead to
Wednesday's scheduled release of the nation's merchandise trade
deficit for October.
   Most analysts expect the deficit will be little changed from the
$10.46 billion imbalance reported for September.
   But many traders were reluctant to take a position in advance of
the trade number, which could affect the Federal Reserve's credit
stance.
   Federal Reserve policymakers gathered today to begin a private
two-day meeting at which they were expected to chart a course on
money policy for the next few weeks.
   Some analysts think the Fed may tighten credit before the end of
the year if the economy shows signs of expanding too rapidly.
   In a new report today, the Commerce Department said retail sales
jumped 1.1 percent in November, following a revised 1.6 percent rise
in October. The November gain was about twice as large as most
analysts had expected.
   Among the active issues on the NYSE was Detroit Edison, up \ at
16|.
   Texaco rose 1{ to 52\. A group led by Carl Icahn disclosed it
holds a 15.83 percent stake in the oil company.
   Pillsbury was up \ at 62]. On Monday, it rejected as inadequate a
sweetened $63-a-share takeover offer from Grand Metropolitan.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.33 at 155.01. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
index was off 0.62 at 296.05.
</TEXT>
