<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   12-13 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South American Showers Pressure Soybean Futures At Opening</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell sharply at the opening
of trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade in a drop triggered
by continuing showers in the South American soybean belt, analysts
said.
   Grain futures opened slightly lower.
   ``I think it's all pretty much the rain in South America
pressuring the market,'' said Mario Balletto, a soybean market
analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc. in New York.
   The weather has been unusually hot and dry during the ongoing
planting period for South American soybeans. But Argentina received
significant precipitation during the weekend and showers were
expected today in the Brazilian state of Parana, a major
soybean-producing region, Balletto said.
   In early trading, soybeans were unchanged to 5\ cents lower with
January at $7.64{ a bushel; wheat was 1 cent to 3 cents lower with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.25{ a bushel; corn was {
cent to 1\ cents lower with December at $2.60{ a bushel; and oats
were unchanged to 1 cent lower with December at $2.07 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .03 cent higher with December
at 72.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .20
cent higher with January at 84.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .07
cent lower to .28 cent higher with December at 42.70 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .35 cent lower to .10 cent higher with
February at 44.40 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled sharply higher on Monday.
</TEXT>
