<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     12-13 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0466</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gave ground today, reflecting
nervousness about interest rates after a stronger-than-expected rise
in November retail sales.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which lost 3.91 points
on Monday, was down another 5.16 at 2,134.42 at noontime on Wall
Street.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of 7 to 4 among
issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 458 up, 750 down
and 641 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 61.73 million shares at noon
compared with 63.67 million shares at the same point in Monday's
session.
   Analysts attributed the decline this morning to deepening worries
that interest rates could be headed higher, making short-term
Treasury issues relatively attractive compared with stocks.
   As Federal Reserve policymakers gathered for a private two-day
meeting at which they are expected to chart a course on credit, the
government reported stronger-than-expected growth in November retail
sales.
   The Commerce Department said November sales rose 1.1 percent,
about twice as big a gain as many analysts had expected. It also
revised upward its estimate of growth in October to 1.6 percent from
the initial report of 0.9 percent.
   The report sent bond prices lower early in the session, and stock
prices followed. Both bonds and stocks later retraced some lost
ground.
   ``It's the old good news is bad news syndrome,'' said Larry
Wachtel, a market analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   ``Anything that smacks of economic vigor does not sit well with
the market,'' he said.
   Trading volume was relatively subdued, however, in advance of
Wednesday's scheduled release of the nation's merchandise trade
deficit for October.
   Most analysts expect the deficit will be little changed from the
$10.46 billion imbalance reported for September.
   But many traders were reluctant to take a position in advance of
the trade number, which could affect the Federal Reserve's credit
stance.
   Some analysts think the Fed may tighten credit before the end of
the year if it determines the economy is expanding too rapidly.
   Texaco rose 1[ to 51~ and was among the most active issues on the
NYSE. A group led by Carl Icahn disclosed it holds a 15.83 percent
stake in the oil company.
   Pillsbury was up { at 62|. On Monday, it rejected as inadequate a
sweetened $63-a-share takeover offer from Grand Metropolitan.
   Among other actively-traded blue-chip issues, General Electric
was off | at 45], Exxon was unchanged at 44| and American Telelphone
& Telegraph was unchanged at 29\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.32 at 155.02. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
index was off 0.76 at 295.91.
</TEXT>
