<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1444EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Japan-BurgerWar Adv19   12-13 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Burger War, Adv 19,0857</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Dec. 19 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>McDonald's Says ``Sankyu'' And Other Burger News From Japan</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonald's is the king of the fast-burger business
in Japan, but only at the cost of constant price wars and assaults
by competitors who entice the Japanese palate with recipes including
soy sauce and rice.
   American-style fast food has become a multibillion-dollar annual
business since McDonald's Co. arrived 17 years ago in this nation of
sushi and noodle soup eaters.
   Thousands of outlets are being added at a rate of almost one a
day, and the competition to grab customers has intensified in recent
months.
   McDonald's, which sold 300 million hamburgers and had $1.2
billion in sales here last year, launched a campaign in October
featuring a hamburger, french fries and a cola for 360 yen ($2.95).
   McDonald's spokesman Tatsuki Kubo said the campaign celebrates
the achievement of one trillion yen ($8.1 billion) in sales since
the company began its business in Japan in 1971.
   The new promotion offers a 25-cent discount from last year's
``Sankyu set,'' which triggered a price war. ``Sankyu'' is the
Japanese pronunciation of ``thank you'' and also means ``39'' _ a
reference to the price of 390 yen ($3.20) for the same combination.
   ``We can lower prices by combining a hamburger with fries and a
drink, cost prices of which are very cheap,'' Kubo said.
   Lotteria Co., the No. 2 chain with $496 million in sales in 1987,
said McDonald's campaign is an attempt to win back customers that
Lotteria had grabbed with its ``380-yen trio'' that was launched a
few months after McDonald's ``Sankyu Set.''
   Lotteria first tried to compete by putting a little more meat and
lettuce in sandwiches, said the firm's Tetsuo Uchimoto, but bigger
burgers weren't attracting more customers. So, in the summer of 1987
Lotteria undercut McDonald's price by 10 yen (8 cents) on the
burger-fries-cola combination.
   Now that McDonald's is down to 360 yen, yet another competitor,
Meiji Sante Ole, with 75 outlets in eastern Japan, has knocked 20
yen (16 cents) from three sets on sale at about 10 outlets located
near McDonald's restaurants, said an official of Sante Ole, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Wendy's, a U.S. chain that has 30 outlets mainly in eastern Japan
after eight years in the country, has joined the price war, said
Ryokichi Morishita of the Daiei Corp., Wendy's parent company in
Japan.
   Wendy's ``cannot compete with others on the same level,''
Morishita said, but it has set prices from 280 yen to 390 yen ($2.30
to $3.20) on combinations normally costing 320 yen to 560 yen.
   Cheaper prices may not always increase sales, however. A
27-year-old stockbroker anonymously said, ``I wouldn't buy a 360-yen
set when I only want a hamburger.''
   Yuko Nomura, a 23-year-old office worker, said in a letter
published recently in the Asahi Shimbun daily that she was offended
when a clerk strongly recommended ``a set'' when she had ordered a
hamburger and coffee.
   Meanwhile, Mos Food Service is competing by opening new Mos
Burgers outlets at a break-neck pace and tops the list with 747
followed by McDonald's 644 and Lotteria's 542, though Mos is third
in sales, with $434 million last year.
   Mos Burgers made the largest sales increase of 38.2 percent last
year, followed by McDonald's 10.1 percent and Lotteria's 8.2 percent.
   Its locations, however, are less visible than those of the top
two companies, which are easily found along major highways and at
the center of big cities.
   ``We don't want to spend money on buying expensive pieces of
land,'' Mos spokesman Kazuhiro Kobayashi said, adding, ``instead, we
have tried to build more shops in cheaper areas.''
   Kobayashi said the company plans to open about 150 new outlets a
year, while McDonald's and Lotteria said each will add about 50.
   Mos Burgers' menu, more Japanese than the others, includes
chicken teriyaki sandwiches and rice-burgers _ the latter has meat
flavored with soy sauce in a rice cake instead of a bun. Those two
sandwiches accounted for 20 percent of sales last year, Kobayashi
said.
   Another competitor, Morinaga Love, recently added a ``Healthy
Burger,'' with 20 percent less fat than normal hamburger, according
to the company.
   The First Kitchen, a chain which introduced a ``Beef-salad
Burger'' in October, said, ``It's a pain that McDonald's 360-yen set
may attract many customers who tend to think `the cheaper the
better.'''
   Burger chains said unanimously that their survival strategy is to
offer something new and different, and to create tastes that suit
Japan's food culture.
   And to take on the Big Mac.
   ``I guess taste is the ultimate factor to be successful in any
kind of food business,'' Lotteria's Uchimoto said.
   ``I don't care if kids go to McDonald's for the 20-yen
difference, because we aim at adults,'' he said, ``McDonald's is the
target until we beat it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Dec. 19</NOTE>
