<1ST_LINE>a f BC-PersonalFile-Copeland Adv16   12-13 0879</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Personal File-Copeland, Adv 16,0908</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday Dec. 16 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Al Copeland, Popeyes Founder, Has Expansion on His Mind</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Al Copeland's bid to take over Church's
Fried Chicken falls through, it will cost him, by his own
estimation, about $5 million.
   He can afford it, however.
   ``I'm not interested in losing money. I don't expect to,'' says
Copeland, whose net worth is put at $200 million. ``I think I can
always make more, though. I've always had that kind of faith in
myself. I can always make another million.''
   Not bad for a guy who grew up in a New Orleans housing project,
dropped out of school at 16, and started his working life as a soda
jerk.
   ``I'm having a ball. I really am. My life is like a story about
the American Dream. I always had the desire to make it big and I
always knew I had the ability to make it big,'' said the 44-year-old
founder of Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken & Biscuits.
   He owns 96 percent of Popeyes and, although he still puts in
12-hour work days, he finds plenty of time to enjoy everything from
offshore powerboat racing, to his splashy display of Christmas
lights that attracts hundreds of thousands of viewers to his
corporate headquarters every year.
   As a 16-year-old high school dropout with no training and no
special skills, Copeland worked two jobs _ days at a local
supermarket soda counter and nights at his brother's doughnut shop.
   He scraped together enough money to buy his own doughnut shop in
1962. But even then he was thinking chicken.
   ``The chicken business looked pretty attractive to me, but I knew
that I'd have to have a product I considered better than Kentucky
Fried Chicken's if I was going to compete,'' he said.
   In 1972, he opened ``Chicken on the Run'' in New Orleans,
featuring fast service, but a chicken recipe that lacked bite. He
had toned down his own pepper-laden, Cajun style formula at the
behest of friends who said it wouldn't sell.
   In the first year, he said, the store lost almost $13,000.
   He decided to go with his original recipe. He renamed the
business Popeyes and started what became the third largest chicken
chain in the country.
   Popeyes now has 725 outlets and is expected to do about $500
million in business this year.
   ``I set a goal of being a millionaire by the time I was 30,'' he
said. He made it easily.
   After that, Copeland said he set himself a goal of making $100
million. He has now reached that goal.
   ``Now it's a billion dollars. It's not the money anymore. Now
it's just a way of keeping track. You have to have a goal, so that's
mine,'' he said.
   Copeland is not at all shy about using his wealth to do what he
likes.
   His 12-car collection now includes a new Rolls Royce, a
custom-made Porsche, and a $100,000 Lamborghini. He has four racing
boats and has held the U.S. title for a record five years in
offshore power boat racing.
   He owns a helicopter, and a 100-foot yacht.
   His corporate offices, on the fifth floor of Popeyes Plaza in
suburban New Orleans, feature art deco interiors, electronic blinds,
and push buttons that produce hidden televisions, bars, and indirect
lighting. His 26-room mansion in New Orleans has an indoor pool and
a gym where he works out two-hours a day with a personal trainer.
   The kid who once marveled at the Christmas lights along Canal
Street in New Orleans, now sets up a 500,000 light display at his
office that attracts 350,000 sightseers a year. The electric bill
alone runs $50,000 a month.
   He used to have the display set up at his house, but a neighbor,
who was upset because he couldn't drive down his street because of
the traffic, sued to stop the practice.
   Copeland's effort to take over Church's, the second largest
chicken chain in the country, landed him in court again. But a
federal judge this week apparently cleared the way for Copeland's
tender offer to proceed.
   Copeland has said he's been offered 14.6 million Church's shares
_ about 40.6 percent of the company's outstanding common stocks _ at
$8 per share.
   And he's confident the takeover will benefit everyone involved.
   ``Look, they have 1,500 stores, twice as many as we have, but
we'll sell as much this year as they will. That's with half as many
units. We could really be a good thing for them,'' he said.
   If the takeover goes through, Copeland will move into second
place in the chicken business, behind Kentucky Fried Chicken.
   If he doesn't get Church's, Copeland said he'll continue to
expand Popeyes and look for new challenges. He's already broken out
of the fast-food mold with a series of his Copeland's Cajun-American
Cafes _ sit-down restaurants with a menu of spicy offerings.
   ``It's not money now,'' Copeland says as he talks about his
expanding empire. ``I've got that. Now I just want to make my mark.
You know what I mean. I want to have made my mark by the time I'm
done.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday Dec. 16</NOTE>
