<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0034,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed slightly higher Tuesday after
seesawing throughout the session ahead of a late rally.
   Shares rose briskly in early business in what dealers called a
technical response to recent sharp declines.
   The market then was unnerved in the afternoon by news of
stronger-than-expected growth in U.S. retail sales. But traders
regained their confidence, amid speculation that for the moment
Britain's inflationary picture seems under control.
   The market in early trading was reacting to Monday's news that
British retail sales volume dropped 0.5 percent in November from
October, analysts said. That apparently suggests recent interest
rate increases already are cutting back consumer spending seen as
fueling inflation.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed up 4.7
points, or 0.3 percent, at 1,752.6. The index rose as much as 15.5
points at late morning before falling back in the afternoon.
   Volume totaled 473.9 million shares, compared with Monday's 460.7
million shares.
</TEXT>
