<HEAD>Bidders Extend Offer for Parent of Denny's Restaurant Chain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs TW Services... to RESTORE dropped word
`comment.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group seeking to buy TW Services
Inc. for $1.14 billion extended its tender offer Tuesday until Jan.
5 and sent the food-service giant the draft of a takeover agreement
to show its sincerity.
   TW Services officials had no immediate comment on the moves by
Coniston Partners, an investment concern run by three New York
takeover strategists who have been pursuing the company for months.
   Coniston said in a statement that under the $29-a-share tender
offer it began in late October, 85.3 percent of TW's 48.6 million
shares of stock outstanding had been been tendered.
   TW has been fighting the takeover with its so-called poison pill
defense designed to make a hostile bid prohibitively expensive.
Coniston has challenged the defense in court.
   The target company has called Coniston's offer too cheap and
implied the investment group is interested only in selling its 9.3
million shares for a profit or breaking up the company and selling
it piecemeal.
   In response, Coniston said it had given TW's board of directors
copies of a draft merger agreement, to demonstrate that the
investment group is seriously interested in running the company.
   ``We urge you to give the enclosed form of agreement prompt and
serious consideration, and we remain ready to meet with you or your
advisors at any time,'' Coniston said in the letter, which it made
public.
   New York-based TW is the parent company of 1,200 Denny's
restaurants, 400 Hardee's fast-food drive-ins, the food service
concern Canteen Corp., 27 nursing homes and two retirement homes.
</TEXT>
