<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose against major foreign currencies in
Europe Tuesday, but traders said there was little trading ahead of
Wednesday's release of U.S. trade figures for October.
   Gold prices also rose.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar largely was sidelined by
a drop in the British pound as some investors took profits from
sterling's recent surge. Dealers said most of the drop took place
earlier in Tokyo, but the pound continued drifting lower during the
European day.
   The pound has fallen consistently since last Wednesday. The pound
had risen strongly before then as investors moved to take advantage
of the latest, Nov. 25 increase in British interest rates.
   In London, the pound fell to $1.8280 from $1.8418 on Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.7470 West German marks, up from 1.7410; 1.4705
Swiss francs, up from 1.4650; 5.9775 French francs, up from 5.9520;
1.9715 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9635; 1,286.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,282.75; and 1.1995 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1983.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.14 Japanese yen to close at 123.06
yen. Later, in London, the dollar was quoted at 123.09 yen.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $420.75 a troy ounce,
compared with $419.75 late Monday. In Zurich, gold rose to close at
$420.45 compared with a bid of $419.25 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 75 cents to close at a bid of
$421.54 an ounce.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid of $6.17 a troy ounce, compared with
Monday's $6.14.
</TEXT>
