<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-13 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corn Rallies, Soybeans Fall, Wheat Ends Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn futures closed strongly higher Tuesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade on hopes for new export sales while soybean
prices fell and wheat finished mixed.
   Corn's rally was fueled by a late surge of buying on persistent
rumors that the Soviet Union was in the market for up to 1 million
metric tons of U.S. corn and sorghum, analysts said.
   ``They're always talking about exports but it remains to be seen
if anything comes up,'' said Jon Horton, an analyst with Research
Department Inc. in Chicago.
   The soybean market was weak all day on reports of rain in the
South American soybean belt and forecasts for more precipitation in
Brazil, the world's second-largest soybean producer after the United
States. Conditions have been unusually dry during the South American
planting period.
   Wheat's mixed performance reflected disappointment that an
expected offer of up to 3 million metric tons of subsidized U.S.
wheat to the Soviet Union had not materialized, analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents lower to 2 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.27 a bushel; corn was 1 cent
to 4\ cents higher with December at $2.65 a bushel; oats were 1 cent
lower to 2{ cents higher with December at $2.06{ a bushel; soybeans
were 1{ cents to 6 cents lower with January at $7.65{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
