<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1939EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LettuceCrop     12-13 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lettuce Crop,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bugs, Heat Bothering Current Crop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL CENTRO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Imperial Valley's winter iceberg
lettuce crop is threatened by insects and bad weather, the same
problems blamed for shortages and high prices a year ago.
   However, experts don't expect prices to soar to last winter's
levels.
   Whiteflies have been a problem in the desert area that stretches
from California's Imperial Valley to Yuma, Arizona and that provides
almost all of the nation's iceberg lettuce each winter.
   ``We have a very similar situation to last year, but what has
made it a little tougher and accentuated the deep problem was the
extreme heat here in October,'' said grower Joe Colace.
   The heat put stress on young lettuce plants and increased the
number of the flies that can stunt formation of lettuce heads or
cause leaves to yellow, he said.
   Desert iceberg lettuce is bringing $10 to $14 for a carton of 24
heads, more than the price received two years ago but well under
last year's prices.
   ``This time last year we were upwards of $20 a box,'' said Colace.
   However, industry experts did not predict prices to equal last
winter, when supermarkets sold iceberg lettuce as high as $1.59 a
head.
   Prices have been kept from soaring as high as in 1987 by late and
heavy harvests that lasted through November in the southern San
Joaquin Valley and the Ventura areas, but Colace expected tight
supplies through the rest of December.
   Any shortage was expected to be less severe because Imperial
Valley growers planted about 35,000 acres to iceberg lettuce this
year, up about 12 percent from 1987.
   ``Last year was a very, very unusual season. I don't think you'll
see another like it,'' said Bob Lee of the Arizona agriculture
department's fruit and vegetable division in Yuma. ``I think people
will give up lettuce before they pay those prices again.''
   Lettuce, California's number one vegetable crop, grossed $598
million for the state growers last year compared with $485 million
in 1986, according to Department of Food and Agriculture statistics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
