<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing Order,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>America West Orders 25 Jets For $800 Million, Takes Options On 25
More</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America West Airlines announced Tuesday that it
had ordered 15 737-300 jetliners and 10 757 commercial jets from
Boeing Co. in a deal worth about $800 million.
   The Phoenix-based carrier also took options for 10 more 737-300s
and 15 757s.
   The airline will receive the initial 25 planes over a three-year
period beginning in 1992.
   The 737-300 is a twin-engine plane that can carry 141 passengers
up to 2,800 miles. It sells for $25 million to $30 million,
depending on configuration.
   The 757 is a larger twin-engine plane, capable of carrying 178 to
197 passengers, with a 4,600-mile range and a price tag of $41
million to $47 million.
   Michael J. Conway, president of America West, said money for the
new planes would come from company earnings, proceeds from selling
currently owned aircraft, and financing.
