<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Dun&BradstreetProbe     12-13 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dun & Bradstreet Probe,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Service Investigating Dun & Bradstreet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Inspection Service said Tuesday
it is investigating allegations that Dun & Bradstreet Corp., one of
the nation's largest credit rating companies, defrauded customers
who purchase its credit information.
   Joseph Clark, the Cincinnati postal inspector handling the
investigation, said Tuesday he has questioned several Dun &
Bradstreet employees, but declined to give further details.
   Clark said the investigation developed from allegations in a
lawsuit pending in U.S. District Court in Cincinnati.
   The suit was filed by Dun & Bradstreet salesman Joseph M.
Davidoski, who alleged that the company engaged in
misrepresentations to induce customers to purchase more
credit-reporting services than they needed. The company has denied
the allegations and said it has started an internal investigation.
   Davidoski said he sued after he took his complaints to a company
supervisor in June and received no satisfaction.
   U.S. Postal Service investigators have requested internal Dun &
Bradstreet documents, and the company is complying with the request,
said Bill Doescher, a spokesman at Dun & Bradstreet's New York City
headquarters.
   The Wall Street Journal reported Tuesday that the investigation
focuses on Dun & Bradstreet's Cincinnati office.
   Dun & Bradstreet salesmen William Lewis and Gary J. Mertz told
the Journal that Clark interviewed them and several of their
colleagues.
   Lewis and Mertz told the newspaper that Dun & Bradstreet managers
routinely encouraged the company's sales representatives for years
to misrepresent to customers how much of the credit data they were
buying was actually needed. Customers who relied on those
representations would buy more credit information than necessary,
Lewis and Mertz told the newspaper.
   Dun & Bradstreet has said it reached settlements with 11
Philadelphia-area customers who said they were persuaded to buy more
credit-report services than they needed. Those customers complained
to Dun & Bradstreet after receiving an anonymous letter, apparently
from inside the company, the Journal reported.
</TEXT>
