<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Finish Narrowly Mixed in Advance of Trade Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A late surge in blue-chip issues left the stock
market narrowly mixed Tuesday amid worries about the course of
interest rates.
   A spurt in the final minutes of trading enabled the market's
best-known indicator to erase exactly the modest loss it recorded a
day earlier. But several broader market gauges finished lower for
the day.
   And analysts said the pace of activity was tempered by
anticipation of the October trade report which is to be released on
Wednesday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which lost 3.91 points
on Monday, made it all back on Tuesday, gaining 3.91 to close at
2,143.49.
   The index had been down nearly 15 points with 30 minutes
remaining in the session and was off nearly 10 points five minutes
before the close.
   ``The blue chips have been leading the market and maybe they are
doing it again,'' said Thomas Czech, first vice president for
research at the brokerage Blunt Ellis Loewi in Milwaukee.
   He noted that the dollar has been strong, and said the late
blue-chip buyers may suspect the trade deficit report will help the
market.
   In the broader market, however, declining issues outnumbered
gainers by about 9-to-5 in nationwide trading of New York Stock
Exchange-listed stocks, with 541 issues up, 890 down and 570
unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 132.34 million shares, up
from 124.16 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
157.30 million shares.
   Analysts attributed the decline in the broader indexes to
deepening worries that interest rates could be headed higher, making
yields on short-term Treasury issues more competitive with the
uncertain returns on stocks.
   The nervousness was heightened because Federal Reserve
policymakers were gathering for a private two-day meeting at which
they are expected to assess the economy's strength and whether
inflation is becoming a problem.
   In the latest indication of the economy's health, the Commerce
Department reported that November retail sales rose 1.1 percent,
about twice as big a gain as many analysts had expected. It also
revised upward its estimate of growth in October to 1.6 percent from
the initial report of 0.9 percent.
   The report sent bond prices lower early in the session, and stock
prices followed.
   ``It's the old good news is bad news syndrome,'' said Larry
Wachtel, a market analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
``Anything that smacks of economic vigor does not sit well with the
market.''
   Also on Tuesday, a majority of the nation's purchasing managers
who responded to a survey indicated they expect the U.S. economy to
do better next year than it has in 1988.
   But analysts said traders were reluctant to take a position in
advance of Wednesday's report on nation's merchandise trade deficit
for October, which many economists expect will be little changed
from the $10.46 billion imbalance reported for September.
   Texaco was one of the most active issues on the NYSE, rising ~ to
51| on takeover speculation as a group led by Carl Icahn disclosed
it holds a 15.8 percent stake in the oil company.
   Bormans was the biggest percentage gainer on the NYSE, rising 11}
to 24~ after disclosing it was negotiating on a takeover offer at
$27 a share.
   Pillsbury rose } to 62~. On Monday, it rejected as inadequate a
sweetened $63-a-share takeover offer from Grand Metropolitan.
   Among other actively-traded blue-chip issues, American Telephone
& Telegraph rose [ to 29], General Electric fell [ to 45~ and Exxon
rose ~ to 45{.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market fell $2.288 billion, or 0.08
percent, in value.
   The NYSE composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
0.10 to 155.24.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index slipped 0.01 to 318.42, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index fell 0.21 to 276.31.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
1.22 to 372.98. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index fell 0.85 to 295.82.
</TEXT>
