<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1915EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-HollyFarms     12-13 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holly Farms,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tyson Argues Holly Farms Misled Tyson in Takeover Bidding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. misled Tyson Foods Inc.
in an effort to thwart the poultry giant's hostile takeover bid for
its smaller rival, an attorney for Tyson Foods argued Tuesday in
Delaware Chancery Court.
   Memphis, Tenn.-based Holly Farms, the fifth-largest poultry
producer in the country, has rejected two takeover offers from
Tyson, based in Springdale, Ark., and the nation's top poultry
producer.
   Holly Farms' board of directors, saying Tyson's latest offer was
not in the best interest of shareholders, said last week it would
proceed with a proposed merger with ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb.
   Both deals are valued at about $1 billion.
   The merger agreement, which has yet to be approved by the
companies' shareholders, would allow ConAgra to purchase key assets
of Holly Farms if the deal fails to go through.
   Tyson processes about 2 billion to 2.2 billion of the
ready-to-cook chicken that is raised in the United States.
   ConAgra, a diversified company, produces about 1.5 billion pounds
a year, and Holly Farms processes 1.2 billion pounds.
   The three companies handle about 30 percent of the ready-to-cook
chicken market.
   Tyson went to Chancery Court seeking a preliminary injunction
that would block the ConAgra merger. Attorneys said after Tuesday's
hearing that Chancery Court Vice Chancellor Maurice Hartnett was not
expected to rule on the injunction until later in the week.
   In rejecting Tyson's latest offer, Holly Farms rejected a bid
that would have given shareholders $53 per share plus a
quarter-share of Tyson stock for each Holly Farms share traded.
Holly Farms has about 20 million shares outstanding.
   Tyson said the cash and stock offer was worth $57 a share to
Holly Farms stockholders.
   In trading Tuesday, Holly Farms rose 62{ cents a share to $54.25
on the New York Stock Exchange, while Tyson rose 62{ cents a share
to $16.75 in over-the-counter trading.
   In its request for the injunction, Tyson argued that the
stockholders' right to the best price was not enforced by Holly
Farms' board of directors. Attorneys claimed the board was
influenced by Holly Farms managers who were unfriendly to Tyson.
   A Tyson takeover likely would lead to top management changes at
Holly Farms, while the ConAgra merger would not, industry observers
say.
   ``The directors' concern was not to get the best price for the
stockholders but to get the best defense against Tyson,'' Tyson
attorney Rodman Ward said.
   Holly Farms failed to get the best offer because it did not press
Tyson for a better one while negotiations were under way with
ConAgra, Ward said.
   At one point during the negotiations, Ward said, a Holly Farms
representative said Tyson could be bidding against itself, although
at that time the board was on the verge of an agreement with ConAgra.
   Ward called that ``an intentional deception of Tyson.''
   But Holly Farms' attorney Steven M. Barna said Tyson knew ConAgra
was a rival.
   Tyson publicly disclosed it had begun takeover discussions with
Holly Farms in October, and mentioned ConAgra in bank documents that
month as a potential competitor, Barna said.
   The terms of bids by ConAgra, the nation's second-largest chicken
producer, and Tyson, required complete secrecy, Barna said.
   ``What they wanted was to have been told who was out there, but
they couldn't have been, under rules established by all parties,''
Barna said.
   ``The process was to get the best offer by giving them no
information,'' Barna said.
   Bruce McNew, an attorney representing shareholders, asked the
court to require open bidding between the two companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
