<FILEID>AP-NR-12-13-88 1958EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RooneyPace     12-13 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rooney Pace,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Self-Regulatory Group Expels Bankrupt Firm For Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Association of Securities Dealers
has expelled a bankrupt New York investment firm, suspended its
ex-president and punished five former brokers for stock
manipulation, the self-regulatory organization said Tuesday, calling
it a flagrant fraud that victimized investors.
   The disciplinary action against Rooney, Pace Inc. and the six
individuals capped a 2-year investigation into questionable dealings
in American Educational Computer Inc., an over-the-counter security
that the firm encouraged clients to buy aggressively based on
misleading information. The stock subsequently tumbled under
mysterious circumstances.
   ``These are serious sanctions,'' John Pinto, NASD vice president
for compliance, said in a telephone interview from the association's
Washington headquarters. ``We went after the individuals who were
active in the security and put them out of business for awhile.''
   The NASD runs the U.S. electronic market for over-the-counter
stocks and is the self-regulatory authority for firms that make
markets in these securities. Expulsion and suspension are among its
most powerful disciplinary tools.
   Although the sanctions won't have any practical impact on Rooney,
Pace because it is not active in the securities business anyway,
they could lead to more serious Securities and Exchange Commission
penalties against the individuals.
   In a press statement, the NASD said Rooney, Pace was expelled
from NASD membership, fined $50,000 and censured. Randolph Pace, its
former president, was fined $100,000, suspended from assocation with
any NASD member for two years and suspended from association with
any NASD member in a supervisory role for an additional five years.
   The NASD also said Joe P. Foor of Norman, Okla., a senior vice
president of the firm, and Coy E. Dean, its Oklahoma City branch
office manager, were each censured, fined $50,000 and barred from
association with an NASD member.
   Lesser sanctions were imposed on Daniel Dispigno, a Rooney, Pace
trader from Smithtown, N.Y., and Terry L. Rogers and Thomas C.
Henry, registered representatives with the firm's Oklahoma City
office.
   A person answering the telephone at Rooney, Pace's New York
office said nobody was available to comment and that the whereabouts
of its current president Arnold Weinberg were unclear.
   Rooney, Pace once had 14 offices nationwide and was ranked as the
81st largest brokerage, specializing in underwriting securities of
start-up companies.
   It unsuccessfully sought a merger with another investment group
in late 1986, and intensifying financial trouble subsequently pushed
it into bankruptcy court proceedings.
   The NASD sanctions were not the first time Rooney, Pace was named
in a fraud investigation. In June 1986 it was charged by the SEC
with participating in a stock manipulation scheme that the
enforcement agency said netted more than $4 million in illegal
profits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
